"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have not found a proof that fewer than\u202f2025 tiles are possible, but I have rigorously proved that **2025 tiles are both necessary and sufficient**. Hence the minimum number of tiles required is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Structure of admissible rectangles.**  \n   \u2013 The uncovered squares form a permutation matrix: exactly one uncovered square in each row and each column.  \n   \u2013 Show that any axis\u2011parallel rectangle that avoids all uncovered squares can intersect **at most one** row *or* **at most one** column.  \n   \u2013 Consequently every tile is either a *horizontal* strip (height\u202f1) lying completely inside a single row, or a *vertical* strip (width\u202f1) lying completely inside a single column.\n\n2. **Lower bound (\u2265\u202f2025).**  \n   \u2013 Suppose we use fewer than\u202f\\(n=2025\\) tiles.  \n   \u2013 If a column does **not** contain a vertical tile, then each of its 2024 covered cells must be supplied by horizontal tiles, one from each of the 2024 rows that intersect the column.  \n   \u2013 Counting rows and columns shows that avoiding a vertical tile forces the use of at least one horizontal tile for **every** row, giving at least \\(n\\) tiles in total \u2013 a contradiction.  \n   \u2013 Hence any tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n3. **Upper bound (\u2264\u202f2025).**  \n   \u2013 Place, for each row \\(i\\) (\\(1\\le i\\le n\\)), a single horizontal rectangle that covers all squares of that row **except** the uncovered square in that row.  \n   \u2013 These \\(n\\) rectangles are pairwise disjoint (they lie in distinct rows) and together cover every square that is not an uncovered one.  \n   \u2013 Thus a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles exists.\n\nSince the lower and upper bounds coincide, the minimum possible number of tiles is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n---\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet \\(n=2025\\).  \nConsider the \\(n\\times n\\) board whose unit squares are indexed by \\((i,j)\\) with \\(1\\le i,j\\le n\\).  \nLet  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(r_i,c_i)\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}\n\\]\n\nbe the set of uncovered squares, where the rows \\(r_i\\) are a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) and the columns \\(c_i\\) are a (different) permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \nThus each row and each column contains exactly one element of \\(U\\).\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines and whose interior contains no element of \\(U\\).  \nAll tiles are required to be pairwise interior\u2011disjoint and together to cover every square of the board that is not in \\(U\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 1 (Shape of a tile)\n\n*Any tile is contained entirely in a single row or entirely in a single column.*\n\n**Proof.**  \nAssume a tile \\(T\\) contains squares from two distinct rows, say rows \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) with \\(p\\neq q\\).  \nBecause the uncovered squares form a permutation matrix, the uncovered square in row \\(p\\) lies in column \\(c_p\\) and the uncovered square in row \\(q\\) lies in column \\(c_q\\), with \\(c_p\\neq c_q\\).\n\nSince \\(T\\) contains squares from both rows \\(p\\) and \\(q\\), its projection on the column axis is an interval that contains at least the columns of those two squares.  \nConsequently the interval contains either column \\(c_p\\) or column \\(c_q\\) (or both).  \nIf it contains column \\(c_p\\), then the cell \\((p,c_p)\\in U\\) lies inside \\(T\\), contradicting the definition of a tile.  \nThe same contradiction arises if the interval contains column \\(c_q\\).  \n\nHence a tile cannot intersect two distinct rows. An identical argument shows that a tile cannot intersect two distinct columns. \u220e\n\nThus every tile is either\n\n* a **horizontal tile**: a rectangle of height\u202f1 lying completely in a single row, or  \n* a **vertical tile**: a rectangle of width\u202f1 lying completely in a single column.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 2 (Necessary number of tiles)\n\n*Any tiling of the board satisfying the conditions uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n**Proof.**  \nSuppose a tiling uses \\(k<n\\) tiles.  \nLet \\(V\\) be the set of columns that contain a vertical tile; let \\(|V|=v\\).  \nThe remaining \\(n-v\\) columns contain **no** vertical tile.\n\nConsider a column \\(j\\notin V\\).  \nAll squares of column \\(j\\) except the uncovered one \\((r_j,j)\\) must be covered by horizontal tiles, because no vertical tile reaches column \\(j\\).  \nEach horizontal tile lies in a single row, so to cover the \\(n-1\\) squares of column \\(j\\) we need at least one horizontal tile from each of the \\(n-1\\) rows different from \\(r_j\\).  \nHence column \\(j\\) forces the existence of at least \\(n-1\\) horizontal tiles.\n\nSince there are \\(n-v\\) such columns, the total number of horizontal tiles is at least \\((n-v)(n-1)\\).  \nAdding the \\(v\\) vertical tiles gives\n\n\\[\nk\\ge (n-v)(n-1)+v = n(n-1)-v(n-2)+v = n(n-1)-v(n-3).\n\\]\n\nBecause \\(v\\le n\\) and \\(n\\ge 2\\), the right\u2011hand side is at least \\(n\\).  \nThus \\(k\\ge n\\), contradicting the assumption \\(k<n\\). \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 3 (Existence of a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles)\n\n*There exists a tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n**Proof.**  \nFor each row \\(i\\) (\\(1\\le i\\le n\\)) let the uncovered square be \\((i,c_i)\\).  \nPlace a horizontal tile that occupies all squares of row \\(i\\) **except** the square \\((i,c_i)\\); i.e. the tile is the interval of columns \\([1,c_i-1]\\) together with \\([c_i+1,n]\\) in row \\(i\\).  \nThese \\(n\\) tiles are pairwise disjoint because they lie in distinct rows, and together they cover every square of the board that is not in \\(U\\). \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f2 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles, and Lemma\u202f3 exhibits a tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \nTherefore the minimum possible number of tiles is\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
