"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains a **Critical Error** and is therefore invalid.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f1 \u2013 \u201cAssume a tile\u202f\\(T\\) contains squares from two distinct rows\u2026 Consequently this interval contains either column\u202f\\(\\pi(p)\\) or column\u202f\\(\\pi(q)\\)\u2026\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 The argument that a rectangle spanning two rows must contain at least one of the two uncovered columns is false; a rectangle can span the rows while staying entirely in a column interval that avoids both uncovered columns. This invalidates Lemma\u202f1 and all subsequent reasoning that depends on it.  \n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Preliminary Setup\nThe solution defines the set of uncovered squares \\(U=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) where \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation. This follows directly from the condition \u201ceach row and each column has exactly one uncovered square\u201d and is correct.\n\n### Lemma\u202f1 \u2013 Claim: \u201cEvery tile lies in a single row or a single column\u201d\n\n**Quoted text:**  \n> \u201cAssume a tile \\(T\\) contains squares from two distinct rows, say rows \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) with \\(p\\neq q\\). \u2026 Since \\(T\\) contains squares from both rows, its projection on the column axis is an interval that contains at least the columns of those two squares. Consequently this interval contains either column \\(\\pi(p)\\) or column \\(\\pi(q)\\) (or both).\u201d\n\n**Analysis:**  \nA tile is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines. If it contains squares from rows \\(p\\) and \\(q\\), then its vertical extent includes both rows, and its horizontal extent is some interval of columns \\([a,b]\\). The uncovered squares in those rows are at columns \\(\\pi(p)\\) and \\(\\pi(q)\\). The argument assumes that the interval \\([a,b]\\) must contain at least one of \\(\\pi(p),\\pi(q)\\). This is **not** forced: the interval could be placed entirely between the two columns, e.g. if \\(\\pi(p)=3\\) and \\(\\pi(q)=8\\), the tile could occupy columns \\(4,5,6,7\\). In that case the rectangle spans rows \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) but avoids both uncovered squares, so it does **not** contradict the definition of a tile.\n\nThus the statement \u201cthe interval contains either column \\(\\pi(p)\\) or column \\(\\pi(q)\\)\u201d is false in general. Consequently the conclusion \u201ca tile cannot intersect two distinct rows\u201d is unsupported.\n\n**Classification:** **Critical Error** \u2013 the logical step is invalid, breaking the chain of reasoning. Because Lemma\u202f1 is false, the classification of all tiles as strictly horizontal or vertical is unjustified.\n\n**Consequence:** All later lemmas (Lemma\u202f2 and Lemma\u202f3) rely on the dichotomy \u201chorizontal vs. vertical tiles\u201d. Since this dichotomy is not established, the lower bound argument in Lemma\u202f2 and the construction in Lemma\u202f3 are not guaranteed to be optimal or even valid for the original problem.\n\n### Impact on Subsequent Parts\n- **Lemma\u202f2** assumes every tile is either horizontal (height\u202f1) or vertical (width\u202f1). With Lemma\u202f1 invalid, a tile could be a genuine rectangle of size \\(>1\\) in both dimensions, which would change the counting argument. Therefore the inequality \\(|H|+|V|\\ge n\\) does not necessarily hold for arbitrary tilings.\n- **Lemma\u202f3** provides a construction using only horizontal tiles, which indeed yields a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles. However, because Lemma\u202f1 is false, the proof that this construction is *optimal* (i.e., that no tiling can use fewer than \\(n\\) tiles) is not established. The existence of a tiling with fewer than \\(n\\) tiles is not ruled out by the presented argument.\n\n### Overall Assessment\nThe solution\u2019s initial reduction to a permutation of uncovered squares is correct, but the pivotal Lemma\u202f1 is flawed. This critical error invalidates the lower\u2011bound proof, leaving the claimed minimum of \\(2025\\) tiles unsubstantiated. Consequently the solution cannot be accepted as correct."
