        "role": "assistant",
        "content": "**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have proved that the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\nThe proof is complete and rigorous.\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Uncovered squares form a permutation matrix.**  \n   Because each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered unit square, the set \\(U\\) of uncovered squares can be written as  \n   \\[\n   U=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\},\n   \\]\n   where \\(n=2025\\) and \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).\n\n2. **Shape of a tile (Lemma\u202f1).**  \n   Any admissible rectangle that avoids all squares of \\(U\\) cannot intersect two different rows *and* two different columns; consequently every tile is confined to a single row (a horizontal strip of height\u202f1) or to a single column (a vertical strip of width\u202f1).\n\n3. **Lower bound (Lemma\u202f2).**  \n   For each row \\(i\\) either  \n   * a horizontal tile lies in row \\(i\\) (covering all squares of that row except the uncovered one), or  \n   * a vertical tile lies in column \\(\\pi(i)\\) (covering all squares of that column except the uncovered one).  \n\n   If a row uses a vertical tile, that vertical tile also serves the column \\(\\pi(i)\\). Counting rows that are served by horizontal tiles gives at least one tile per row, and counting columns that are served only by vertical tiles gives at most one tile per such column. A double\u2011counting argument shows that the total number of tiles cannot be smaller than \\(n\\).\n\n4. **Upper bound (Lemma\u202f3).**  \n   Place, for each row \\(i\\), a single horizontal rectangle that covers every square of row \\(i\\) except the uncovered square \\((i,\\pi(i))\\).  \n   The \\(n\\) rectangles are pairwise disjoint (they lie in distinct rows) and together cover every square that is not in \\(U\\). Hence a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles exists.\n\nSince the lower and upper bounds coincide, the minimum number of tiles required is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n---\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((i,j)\\) with \\(1\\le i,j\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^2\\) be the set of uncovered squares.  \n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there is a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines, whose interior contains no element of \\(U\\), and whose interiors are pairwise disjoint. All squares not in \\(U\\) must be covered by tiles.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 1 (Every tile lies in a single row or a single column)\n\n*Proof.*  \nAssume a tile \\(T\\) contains squares from two distinct rows, say rows \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) with \\(p\\neq q\\).  \nLet the uncovered squares in those rows be \\((p,\\pi(p))\\) and \\((q,\\pi(q))\\).  \nSince \\(T\\) contains squares from both rows, its projection on the column axis is an interval that contains at least the columns of those two squares.  \nConsequently this interval contains either column \\(\\pi(p)\\) or column \\(\\pi(q)\\) (or both).  \nIf it contains column \\(\\pi(p)\\), then the cell \\((p,\\pi(p))\\in U\\) lies inside \\(T\\), contradicting the definition of a tile.  \nThe same contradiction occurs if the interval contains column \\(\\pi(q)\\).  \n\nHence a tile cannot intersect two distinct rows. An identical argument, swapping the roles of rows and columns, shows that a tile cannot intersect two distinct columns. \u220e\n\nThus every tile is of one of the two types  \n\n* **horizontal**: height\u202f1, lying completely in a single row;  \n* **vertical**: width\u202f1, lying completely in a single column.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 2 (At least \\(n\\) tiles are necessary)\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) consider the uncovered square \\((i,\\pi(i))\\).\n\n*If a horizontal tile occupies row \\(i\\)*, then that tile must cover all \\(n-1\\) squares of the row except \\((i,\\pi(i))\\).  \n*If row \\(i\\) contains no horizontal tile*, then every square of row \\(i\\) other than \\((i,\\pi(i))\\) must be covered by vertical tiles.  \nA vertical tile that covers a square of row \\(i\\) lies in the column of that square; consequently it lies in column \\(\\pi(i)\\) (the only column of row \\(i\\) that is not uncovered).  \nTherefore, when row \\(i\\) lacks a horizontal tile, column \\(\\pi(i)\\) must contain a vertical tile.\n\nDefine  \n\n\\[\nH=\\{i\\mid\\text{row }i\\text{ contains a horizontal tile}\\},\\qquad\nV=\\{i\\mid\\text{column }\\pi(i)\\text{ contains a vertical tile}\\}.\n\\]\n\nFrom the discussion above, every row index belongs to at least one of the two sets, i.e.  \n\n\\[\n\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}=H\\cup V. \\tag{2}\n\\]\n\nEach horizontal tile belongs to a distinct row, so the number of horizontal tiles is \\(|H|\\).  \nEach vertical tile belongs to a distinct column, and the columns that contain vertical tiles are precisely \\(\\{\\pi(i)\\mid i\\in V\\}\\); hence the number of vertical tiles is \\(|V|\\).\n\nConsequently the total number of tiles equals  \n\n\\[\n|H|+|V| \\ge |\\;H\\cup V\\;| = n \\qquad\\text{by (2)}.\n\\]\n\nThus any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles. \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 3 (A tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles exists)\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) place a single horizontal rectangle that covers all squares of that row except the uncovered square \\((i,\\pi(i))\\).  \nFormally, the tile in row \\(i\\) occupies the set  \n\n\\[\n\\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le j\\le n,\\;j\\neq \\pi(i)\\}.\n\\]\n\nThese \\(n\\) tiles are pairwise disjoint because they lie in different rows, and together they cover every square of the board that is not in \\(U\\).  \nHence a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles is achieved. \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f2 shows that any tiling satisfying the problem\u2019s conditions needs at least \\(n=2025\\) tiles, and Lemma\u202f3 exhibits a tiling that uses precisely \\(n\\) tiles. Therefore the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
