        "role": "user",
        "content": "\n======================================================================\n### Problem ###\n\n*** Problem Statement ***\n\nConsider a $2025\\times2025$ grid of unit squares. Matilda wishes to place on the grid some rectangular tiles, possibly of difference sizes, such that each side of every tile lies on a grid line and every unit square is covered by at most one tile.\n\nDetermine the minimum number of tiles Matilda needs to place so that each row and each column of the grid has exactly one unit square that is not covered by any tile.\n\n======================================================================\n### Solution ###\n\n**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((i,j)\\) with \\(1\\le i,j\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\) be the set of uncovered squares.\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines, whose interior contains no element of \\(U\\), and whose interiors are pairwise disjoint. All squares not belonging to \\(U\\) must be covered by tiles.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 1  \n*No tile can contain all \\(n-1\\) covered squares of two distinct rows (and, by symmetry, of two distinct columns).*\n\n*Proof.*  \nConsider a tile \\(T\\). Let its projection on the column axis be the interval \\([c_{1},c_{2}]\\) (with integer endpoints, \\(1\\le c_{1}<c_{2}\\le n\\)).  \nIf \\(T\\) contains all covered squares of a row \\(r\\), then it must contain every column except the uncovered one \\(\\pi(r)\\); consequently the column interval of \\(T\\) must be exactly the set \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\). Hence the interval has length \\(n-1\\) and **excludes precisely the column \\(\\pi(r)\\)**.\n\nAssume, for contradiction, that the same tile also contains all covered squares of a different row \\(s\\neq r\\). Then the column interval would have to exclude the column \\(\\pi(s)\\) as well. Because \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation, \\(\\pi(s)\\neq\\pi(r)\\). An interval of columns cannot simultaneously omit two distinct columns while still having size \\(n-1\\); the only interval of size \\(n-1\\) is the complement of a single column. Hence such a tile cannot exist.\n\nThe argument is symmetric with rows and columns interchanged, giving the second statement. \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 2 (Lower bound)\n\n*At least \\(n\\) tiles are necessary.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) the set of squares that must be covered is  \n\n\\[\nR_{i}= \\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le j\\le n,\\;j\\neq \\pi(i)\\},\n\\]\n\nwhich contains exactly \\(n-1\\) squares.  \nBy Lemma\u202f1 a single tile can supply all squares of \\(R_{i}\\) for **at most one** index \\(i\\).  \nTherefore the \\(n\\) distinct sets \\(R_{1},\\dots ,R_{n}\\) require at least \\(n\\) distinct tiles. \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 3 (Upper bound)\n\n*There exists a tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) place the horizontal rectangle  \n\n\\[\nT_{i}= \\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le j\\le n,\\;j\\neq \\pi(i)\\}.\n\\]\n\n\\(T_{i}\\) is a legitimate tile because it avoids the uncovered square \\((i,\\pi(i))\\) and its interior contains no other uncovered square.  \nThe rectangles \\(T_{1},\\dots ,T_{n}\\) lie in distinct rows, so they are pairwise disjoint.  \nTogether they cover every square of the board that is not in \\(U\\).  \nHence we have produced a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles. \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f2 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles, while Lemma\u202f3 exhibits a tiling that uses precisely \\(n\\) tiles. Consequently the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n\n### Verification Task Reminder ###\n\nYour task is to act as an IMO grader. Now, generate the **summary** and the **step-by-step verification log** for the solution above. In your log, justify each correct step and explain in detail any errors or justification gaps you find, as specified in the instructions above.\n\n"
