"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains a **Critical Error** and is therefore invalid.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f3 (Upper bound) \u2013 \u201cFor each row\u202f\\(i\\) place the horizontal rectangle \\(T_{i}= \\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le j\\le n,\\;j\\neq \\pi(i)\\}\\).\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the set \\(T_{i}\\) is **not** a rectangle (it is a row with one unit square removed), violating the definition of a tile. This destroys the construction claimed in Lemma\u202f3 and invalidates the upper\u2011bound argument.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Preliminary definitions\n- The problem is correctly restated: we have an \\(n\\times n\\) board (\\(n=2025\\)), each row and column must contain exactly one uncovered unit square, and tiles must be axis\u2011aligned rectangles whose interiors are pairwise disjoint and contain no uncovered squares.  \n- The notation \\(U=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) correctly captures the condition that the uncovered squares form a permutation matrix. No issue here.\n\n### Lemma\u202f1\n**Statement:** \u201cNo tile can contain all \\(n-1\\) covered squares of two distinct rows (and, by symmetry, of two distinct columns).\u201d\n\n**Reasoning:**  \n- The proof argues that a tile covering all covered squares of a given row must span all columns except the column of the uncovered square, i.e. its column interval must be \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\).  \n- Since a tile is a rectangle, its column interval must be a **contiguous** interval of integers. The only contiguous interval of size \\(n-1\\) is indeed the complement of a single column, so the argument is sound.  \n- If the same tile were to cover all covered squares of a second row \\(s\\neq r\\), it would have to omit both \\(\\pi(r)\\) and \\(\\pi(s)\\), which is impossible for a contiguous interval of size \\(n-1\\).  \n\n**Assessment:** The argument is rigorous and correctly uses the definition of a rectangle (contiguous interval). **No error.**\n\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Lower bound)\n**Statement:** \u201cAt least \\(n\\) tiles are necessary.\u201d\n\n**Reasoning:**  \n- For each row \\(i\\) the set \\(R_i\\) of squares that must be covered consists of the \\(n-1\\) squares of that row except the uncovered one.  \n- By Lemma\u202f1 a single tile can supply all squares of \\(R_i\\) for **at most one** index \\(i\\).  \n- Hence the \\(n\\) distinct sets \\(R_1,\\dots,R_n\\) each require a distinct tile, giving a lower bound of \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n**Assessment:** The deduction from Lemma\u202f1 is valid; each \\(R_i\\) cannot be covered by a tile that also covers another \\(R_j\\). Therefore the lower bound argument is correct. **No error.**\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Upper bound) \u2013 **Critical Error**\n**Statement:** \u201cThere exists a tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles. For each row \\(i\\) place the horizontal rectangle \\(T_i = \\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le j\\le n,\\;j\\neq \\pi(i)\\}\\).\u201d\n\n**Problematic step:**  \n- By definition, a **tile** must be a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines. A rectangle in the grid is a set of unit squares of the form \\(\\{(x,y)\\mid a\\le x\\le b,\\;c\\le y\\le d\\}\\) for some integers \\(a\\le b,\\;c\\le d\\).  \n- The set \\(T_i\\) described above is a **row with one unit square removed**. It consists of two disjoint horizontal segments: \\(\\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le j<\\pi(i)\\}\\) and \\(\\{(i,j)\\mid \\pi(i)<j\\le n\\}\\). This set is **not contiguous** in the column direction, hence it is **not** a rectangle.  \n- Consequently \\(T_i\\) does **not** satisfy the problem\u2019s tile definition. The construction therefore does **not** produce a valid tiling.\n\nBecause Lemma\u202f3 provides the only argument that the lower bound \\(n\\) is attainable, the failure of this construction means the claimed upper bound is unsupported. The solution does not demonstrate any tiling with \\(n\\) tiles, nor does it give an alternative construction. Hence the conclusion that the minimum number of tiles equals \\(2025\\) is unjustified.\n\n**Impact:** This critical error invalidates the entire solution. The lower bound remains correct, but without a valid upper bound the problem is unsolved.\n\n### Overall conclusion\n- Lemma\u202f1 and Lemma\u202f2 are correct and rigorously justified.  \n- Lemma\u202f3 contains a critical error: the proposed \u201ctiles\u201d are not rectangles, violating the problem\u2019s constraints.  \n- As a result, the solution fails to establish the existence of a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles, and the final answer cannot be accepted."
