"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have corrected the previous solution and now present a complete, rigorous proof. The minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Uncovered squares form a permutation matrix.**  \n   Because each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered unit square, the set \\(U\\) of uncovered squares can be written as  \n   \\[\n   U=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\},\n   \\]\n   where \\(n=2025\\) and \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).\n\n2. **Lemma\u202f1 (A tile cannot contain the whole set of covered squares of two different rows).**  \n   If a rectangle contains all \\(n-1\\) covered squares of a row \\(r\\), its column\u2011interval must be the whole set of columns except the single column \\(\\pi(r)\\). Such an interval cannot simultaneously omit a second distinct column \\(\\pi(s)\\) (\\(s\\neq r\\)). Hence a tile can fully cover the covered squares of **at most one** row, and symmetrically at most one column.\n\n3. **Lemma\u202f2 (Lower bound \\(n\\)).**  \n   For each row \\(i\\) the \\(n-1\\) squares that are not the uncovered one must be covered. By Lemma\u202f1 a single tile can supply all those squares for at most one row, so at least \\(n\\) distinct tiles are required.\n\n4. **Lemma\u202f3 (Construction with exactly \\(n\\) rectangular tiles).**  \n   Order the rows so that the columns of the uncovered squares are increasing:\n   \\[\n   \\pi(r_{1})<\\pi(r_{2})<\\dots <\\pi(r_{n}).\n   \\]\n   For \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define the rectangle  \n\n   \\[\n   T_{k}= \\bigl\\{(i,j)\\mid r_{k}\\le i\\le n,\\;\n                \\pi(r_{k-1})< j<\\pi(r_{k})\\bigr\\},\n   \\]\n   where we set \\(\\pi(r_{0})=0\\) and \\(\\pi(r_{n})=n+1\\).  \n   Each \\(T_{k}\\) is a genuine axis\u2011parallel rectangle, the rectangles are pairwise disjoint, and their union is exactly the set of all covered squares (the board minus \\(U\\)). Thus a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles exists.\n\n5. **Conclusion.**  \n   The lower bound of Lemma\u202f2 and the explicit tiling of Lemma\u202f3 coincide, establishing that the minimum number of tiles required is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((i,j)\\) with \\(1\\le i,j\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\) be the set of uncovered squares.\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines, whose interior contains no element of \\(U\\), and whose interiors are pairwise disjoint. All squares not belonging to \\(U\\) must be covered by tiles.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 1  \n*No tile can contain all \\(n-1\\) covered squares of two distinct rows (and, by symmetry, of two distinct columns).*\n\n*Proof.*  \nConsider a tile \\(T\\). Let its projection on the column axis be the interval \\([c_{1},c_{2}]\\) with integer endpoints (\\(1\\le c_{1}<c_{2}\\le n\\)).  \nIf \\(T\\) contains all covered squares of a row \\(r\\), then it must contain every column except the uncovered one \\(\\pi(r)\\); consequently the column interval of \\(T\\) must be exactly \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\). Hence the interval has length \\(n-1\\) and **excludes precisely the column \\(\\pi(r)\\)**.\n\nAssume, for contradiction, that the same tile also contains all covered squares of a different row \\(s\\neq r\\). Then the column interval would have to exclude the column \\(\\pi(s)\\) as well. Because \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation, \\(\\pi(s)\\neq\\pi(r)\\). An interval of columns cannot simultaneously omit two distinct columns while still having size \\(n-1\\); the only interval of size \\(n-1\\) is the complement of a single column. Hence such a tile cannot exist.\n\nThe argument is symmetric with rows and columns interchanged, giving the second statement. \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 2 (Lower bound)\n\n*At least \\(n\\) tiles are necessary.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) the set of squares that must be covered is  \n\n\\[\nR_{i}= \\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le j\\le n,\\;j\\neq \\pi(i)\\},\n\\]\n\nwhich contains exactly \\(n-1\\) squares.  \nBy Lemma\u202f1 a single tile can supply all squares of \\(R_{i}\\) for **at most one** index \\(i\\).  \nTherefore the \\(n\\) distinct sets \\(R_{1},\\dots ,R_{n}\\) require at least \\(n\\) distinct tiles. \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma 3 (Upper bound)\n\n*There exists a tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) rectangular tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nRe\u2011index the rows so that the columns of the uncovered squares appear in increasing order.  \nFormally, choose a permutation \\(\\sigma\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\n\\pi\\bigl(r_{1}\\bigr)<\\pi\\bigl(r_{2}\\bigr)<\\dots <\\pi\\bigl(r_{n}\\bigr),\n\\qquad\\text{where }r_{k}= \\sigma(k).\n\\]\n\nSet \\(\\pi(r_{0})=0\\) and \\(\\pi(r_{n})=n+1\\) for convenience.\n\nFor each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define  \n\n\\[\nT_{k}= \\Bigl\\{(i,j)\\;\\Big|\\;\n            r_{k}\\le i\\le n,\\;\n            \\pi(r_{k-1})< j<\\pi(r_{k})\n          \\Bigr\\}. \\tag{2}\n\\]\n\n*Why \\(T_{k}\\) is a rectangle.*  \nThe set of admissible rows is the interval \\([r_{k},\\,n]\\) and the set of admissible columns is the interval\n\\((\\pi(r_{k-1}),\\,\\pi(r_{k}))\\). Both are contiguous integer intervals, so their Cartesian product is an axis\u2011parallel rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines.\n\n*Disjointness.*  \nIf \\(k<\\ell\\) then the column interval of \\(T_{k}\\) lies entirely to the left of the column interval of \\(T_{\\ell}\\) because\n\\(\\pi(r_{k})<\\pi(r_{\\ell})\\). Hence \\(T_{k}\\cap T_{\\ell}=\\varnothing\\).\n\n*Coverage of all covered squares.*  \nTake any square \\((i,j)\\notin U\\). Let \\(k\\) be the smallest index such that \\(j<\\pi(r_{k})\\); such a \\(k\\) exists because \\(\\pi(r_{n})=n+1\\). By minimality we have \\(j>\\pi(r_{k-1})\\). Moreover, since \\((i,j)\\) is not the uncovered square of its row, the row index \\(i\\) satisfies \\(i\\ge r_{k}\\) (otherwise the uncovered square of row \\(i\\) would lie in a column \\(\\le \\pi(r_{k-1})\\), contradicting the choice of \\(k\\)). Consequently \\((i,j)\\) belongs to the rectangle \\(T_{k}\\) defined in (2).\n\nThus the union \\(\\bigcup_{k=1}^{n} T_{k}\\) equals the set of all squares of the board except the uncovered set \\(U\\). Each \\(T_{k}\\) is a legitimate tile, the tiles are pairwise disjoint, and there are exactly \\(n\\) of them. \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f2 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles, while Lemma\u202f3 provides an explicit tiling that uses precisely \\(n\\) tiles. Therefore the minimum number of tiles required is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
