"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains a **Critical Error** and is therefore invalid.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f3, definition of the tiles  \n  *\u201cFor each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define  \n  \\[\n  T_{k}= \\Bigl\\{(i,j)\\;\\Big|\\;\n            r_{k}\\le i\\le n,\\;\n            \\pi(r_{k-1})< j<\\pi(r_{k})\n          \\Bigr\\}. \\tag{2}\n  \\]\u201d*  \n  *Issue:* Critical Error \u2013 the construction assumes that the set of rows \\(\\{i\\mid r_{k}\\le i\\le n\\}\\) correctly captures all rows that need to be covered for the \\(k\\)-th tile, but the indices \\(r_{k}\\) are a permutation ordered by the values \\(\\pi(r_{k})\\), not by their numeric size. Consequently the intervals \\([r_{k},n]\\) do not partition the rows, and many squares remain uncovered (or are covered twice). This breaks the logical chain of the proof.\n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n#### Preliminary Setup\n- The solution correctly observes that the uncovered squares must form a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n  *Justification:* Each row and column must contain exactly one uncovered square, which is precisely the definition of a permutation matrix. This step is sound.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f1\n- **Claim:** No tile can contain all \\(n-1\\) covered squares of two distinct rows (or columns).  \n- **Reasoning:** The argument notes that a tile covering all but one square in a row must span all columns except the column of the uncovered square, i.e. its column interval must be the complement of a single column. If it were to also cover all but one square of another row, it would have to omit a second distinct column, which is impossible for an interval of length \\(n-1\\).  \n- **Assessment:** The reasoning is correct and rigorous. No gaps are present.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f2 (Lower bound)\n- **Claim:** At least \\(n\\) tiles are necessary.  \n- **Reasoning:** Each row \\(i\\) contains the set \\(R_i\\) of its \\(n-1\\) covered squares. By Lemma\u202f1 a single tile can supply all squares of \\(R_i\\) for at most one row \\(i\\). Hence we need at least one distinct tile for each of the \\(n\\) rows.  \n- **Assessment:** The deduction follows directly from Lemma\u202f1 and is valid. No gaps.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f3 (Upper bound) \u2013 **Critical Error**\n- **Goal:** Construct a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \n- **Construction Overview:**  \n  1. Re\u2011index rows so that the uncovered columns \\(\\pi(r_k)\\) are strictly increasing with \\(k\\).  \n  2. Define tiles \\(T_k\\) as the Cartesian product of the row interval \\([r_k,n]\\) and the column interval \\((\\pi(r_{k-1}),\\pi(r_k))\\).  \n\n- **Problematic Step:** The definition of the row interval \\([r_k,n]\\).  \n  - The indices \\(r_k\\) are a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) ordered by the *values* \\(\\pi(r_k)\\), not by their numeric size. Consequently the sequence \\((r_1,r_2,\\dots ,r_n)\\) can be arbitrarily scrambled.  \n  - An interval of the form \\([r_k,n]\\) therefore does **not** correspond to \u201cthe rows that have not yet been covered\u201d in any systematic way. For example, if \\(r_1=1000\\) and \\(r_2=5\\), then \\(T_1\\) covers rows \\(1000,\\dots ,n\\) while \\(T_2\\) covers rows \\(5,\\dots ,n\\); rows \\(6,\\dots ,999\\) are covered by both \\(T_1\\) and \\(T_2\\), and rows \\(1,\\dots ,4\\) are never covered.  \n\n- **Consequences:**  \n  - **Coverage Failure:** Many squares (those whose row index lies outside every interval \\([r_k,n]\\)) remain uncovered, contradicting the claim that \\(\\bigcup_{k=1}^{n} T_k\\) equals the set of all covered squares.  \n  - **Overlap Issue:** Overlaps occur when two intervals \\([r_k,n]\\) and \\([r_\\ell,n]\\) intersect, violating the requirement that tiles be interior\u2011disjoint.  \n\n- **Conclusion:** The construction does not produce a valid tiling; the proof of Lemma\u202f3 is fundamentally flawed. Because Lemma\u202f3 is essential for establishing the upper bound, the entire argument collapses at this point. No further steps can salvage the result.\n\n#### Overall Conclusion\n- Lemma\u202f1 and Lemma\u202f2 are correct, establishing a lower bound of \\(n\\) tiles.  \n- Lemma\u202f3, intended to show that \\(n\\) tiles suffice, contains a critical error in the definition of the tiles, rendering the upper bound unproven.  \n- Therefore the solution does **not** correctly determine the minimum number of tiles. The claimed answer \\(2025\\) is not justified."
