"**Final Verdict:** The solution is **invalid** because it contains a **Critical Error** that breaks the construction of an \\(n\\)-tile tiling.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f3, step\u202f3.1 \u2013 \u201cEach set \\(R\\) produced in step\u202f3 is a genuine rectangle.\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the argument that removing the uncovered squares \\(U\\) from the large axis\u2011parallel rectangle leaves a (possibly smaller) rectangle is false; the resulting set can be non\u2011rectangular. This invalidates the claimed existence of an \\(n\\)-tile tiling and therefore the upper\u2011bound proof.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Preliminary definitions (correct)\n\n- The notation \\(U=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) correctly captures the condition that each row and column contains exactly one uncovered square.  \n- The description of a **tile** as a rectangle whose interior avoids \\(U\\) and whose interiors are pairwise disjoint is precise.\n\n### Lemma\u202f1 (correct)\n\n- The proof correctly shows that a tile cannot contain all covered squares of two distinct rows (or columns) because its column (or row) interval would have to omit two distinct columns (or rows), which an interval of length \\(n-1\\) cannot do. No logical gaps are present.\n\n### Lemma\u202f2 (correct)\n\n- Using Lemma\u202f1, the argument that each set \\(R_i\\) (the \\(n-1\\) covered squares in row \\(i\\)) requires a distinct tile is valid, establishing the lower bound of \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 \u2013 Upper bound (contains a Critical Error)\n\n#### Step\u202f3 (algorithm definition)\n\n- The algorithm is clearly described: it repeatedly selects the smallest row whose uncovered square is still present, defines a set \\(R\\) as in (2), adds \\(R\\) to the list of tiles, and removes \\(R\\) from the uncovered\u2011to\u2011cover set \\(C\\).\n\n#### Step\u202f3.1 \u2013 Claim that each \\(R\\) is a rectangle  \n\n> \u201cBecaus