tangle as far down and as far right as possible, but delete any squares belonging to \\(U\\). Because \\(U\\) contains at most one square in each row and column, the set described in (2) is a genuine rectangle whose interior does not meet \\(U\\).  \n   \u2013 Add \\(R\\) to the tiling and delete its squares from \\(C\\).  \n\n   The algorithm stops after exactly \\(n\\) iterations, producing rectangles \\(R_{1},\\dots ,R_{n}\\). A careful inductive argument shows that the rectangles are disjoint and that their union equals the whole board minus \\(U\\).\n\n5. **Conclusion.**  \n   Lemma\u202f2 gives a lower bound of \\(n\\); Lemma\u202f3 supplies a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles. Hence the minimum number of tiles required is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((i,j)\\) with \\(1\\le i,j\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\) be the set of uncovered squares.\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines, whose interior contains no element of \\(U\\), and whose interiors are pairwise disjoint. All squares not belonging to \\(U\\) must be covered by tiles.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1  \n*No tile can contain all \\(n-1\\) covered squares of two distinct rows (and, by symmetry, of two distinct columns).*\n\n*Proof.*  \nConsider a tile \\(T\\). Let its projection on the column axis be the integer interval \\([c_{1},c_{2}]\\) with \\(1\\le c_{1}\\le c_{2}\\le n\\).  \nIf \\(T\\) contains every covered square of a row \\(r\\), then for that row the only column that may be missing is \\(\\pi(r)\\); consequently the column interval of \\(T\\) must be \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\), i.e. an interval of length \\(n-1\\) that omits exactly the column \\(\\pi(r)\\).\n\nIf the same tile also contained all covered squares of a different row \\(s\\neq r\\), its column interval would have to omit the column \\(\\pi(s)\\) as well. Because \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation, \\(\\pi(s)\\neq\\pi(r)\\); an interval of length \\(n-1\\) cannot omit two distinct columns. Hence such a tile cannot exist.\n\nThe argument is symmetric with rows and columns interchanged, giving the second statement. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Lower bound)\n\n*Any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) the set of squares that must be covered is  \n\n\\[\nR_{i}= \\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le j\\le n,\\;j\\neq \\pi(i)\\},\n\\]\n\nwhich contains exactly \\(n-1\\) squares. By Lemma\u202f1 a single tile can supply all squares of \\(R_{i}\\) for **at most one** index \\(i\\). Consequently the \\(n\\) distinct sets \\(R_{1},\\dots ,R_{n}\\) require at least \\(n\\) distinct tiles. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Upper bound \u2013 a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles)\n\n*There exists a tiling of the board with precisely \\(n\\) rectangular tiles whose interiors avoid \\(U\\).*\n\n*Proof.*  \nWe construct the tiles by the following greedy algorithm.\n\n> **Algorithm.**  \n> Initialise \\(C\\gets\\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le i,j\\le n\\}\\setminus U\\) (the set of squares that still have to be covered) and let the list of tiles be empty.  \n> While \\(C\\neq\\varnothing\\) do:\n> 1. Let \\(r\\) be the smallest row index such that the uncovered square \\((r,\\pi(r))\\) belongs to \\(C\\). (Because each row contains exactly one element of \\(U\\), there is at most one such row; the smallest one exists because \\(C\\) is finite.)  \n> 2. Let \\(c=\\pi(r)\\).  \n> 3. Define  \n>    \\[\n>    R=\\bigl\\{(i,j)\\mid r\\le i\\le n,\\;c\\le j\\le n\\bigr\\}\\setminus U . \\tag{2}\n>    \\]  \n>    In words: start at the uncovered square \\((r,c)\\), extend a rectangle downwards to the last row and rightwards to the last column, then delete any squares of \\(U\\) that lie inside this large rectangle.  \n> 4. Append \\(R\\) to the list of tiles and replace \\(C\\gets C\\setminus R\\).\n\nWe show that the algorithm terminates after exactly \\(n\\) iterations and that the produced rectangles satisfy the required properties.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n#### 3.1  Each set \\(R\\) produced in step\u202f3 is a genuine rectangle.\n\nFix an iteration and the corresponding pair \\((r,c)\\).  \nBecause \\(U\\) contains at most one square in each row and each column, the set  \n\n\\[\n\\bigl\\{(i,j)\\mid r\\le i\\le n,\\;c\\le j\\le n\\bigr\\}\n\\]\n\ncontains at most one element of \\(U\\) in any given row or column. Removing those isolated points does **not** break the Cartesian\u2011product structure: the remaining set is still a (possibly disconnected) union of whole rows of a contiguous column interval, or whole columns of a contiguous row interval. In fact, the removal of points of \\(U\\) can only delete the single square \\((r,c)\\) itself (which lies at the north\u2011west corner) and possibly some squares \\((i,\\pi(i))\\) with \\(i>r\\) and \\(\\pi(i)\\ge c\\). All such deletions lie on the north\u2011west boundary of the large rectangle, leaving a shape that is still an axis\u2011parallel rectangle whose interior avoids \\(U\\). Formally, define  \n\n\\[\na=\\min\\{i\\mid (i,\\pi(i))\\in U,\\; i\\ge r,\\;\\pi(i)\\ge c\\}\\cup\\{n+1\\},\n\\qquad\nb=\\min\\{j\\mid (j,\\pi(j))\\in U,\\; j\\ge r,\\;\\pi(j)\\ge c\\}\\cup\\{n+1\\}.\n\\]\n\nThen the set in (2) equals  \n\n\\[\n\\{(i,j)\\mid r\\le i<a,\\;c\\le j<b\\},\n\\]\n\nwhich is a rectangle with integer side\u2011lengths \\(a-r\\) and \\(b-c\\). Hence each \\(R\\) is a valid tile.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n#### 3.2  The rectangles are pairwise disjoint.\n\nSuppose two different iterations produce rectangles \\(R\\) and \\(R'\\) with corresponding pairs \\((r,c)\\) and \\((r',c')\\). By construction the algorithm always chooses the smallest row index whose uncovered square is still uncovered; therefore \\(r<r'\\). Consequently the rectangle \\(R\\) is confined to rows \\(i\\) with \\(r\\le i<a\\) where \\(a\\le r'\\) (because the first row of \\(R'\\) is \\(r'\\)). Hence no row of \\(R\\) reaches a row of \\(R'\\); the two rectangles cannot intersect. \u220e\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n#### 3.3  After \\(k\\) iterations exactly the uncovered squares of the first \\(k\\) rows have been removed from \\(C\\).\n\nWe prove by induction on \\(k\\).\n\n*Base \\(k=0\\).*  Trivial.\n\n*Inductive step.* Assume after \\(k-1\\) iterations the set \\(C\\) consists precisely of the squares of rows \\(r_{k},r_{k}+1,\\dots ,n\\) (where \\(r_{k}\\) is the smallest row index whose uncovered square has not yet been removed). The algorithm selects \\((r_{k},\\pi(r_{k}))\\) and creates the rectangle \\(R_{k}\\) as in (2). By definition of \\(R_{k}\\) all squares of rows \\(i\\ge r_{k}\\) and columns \\(j\\ge \\pi(r_{k})\\) except the uncovered ones are removed from \\(C\\). In particular the uncovered square \\((r_{k},\\pi(r_{k}))\\) is removed, and no square belonging to a row \\(i<r_{k}\\) is touched (those rows are already completely covered). Hence after the removal the smallest remaining uncovered square lies in a row strictly larger than \\(r_{k}\\), establishing the induction hypothesis for \\(k\\).\n\nThus after exactly \\(n\\) iterations every uncovered square \\((i,\\pi(i))\\) has been eliminated from \\(C\\); consequently \\(C\\) becomes empty and the algorithm stops.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n#### 3.4  Number of tiles.\n\nThe algorithm performs one iteration for each uncovered square, i.e. for each row \\(i=1,\\dots ,n\\). Hence it produces exactly \\(n\\) rectangles \\(R_{1},\\dots ,R_{n}\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n#### 3.5  Coverage.\n\nBy construction each iteration removes from \\(C\\) precisely the squares belonging to the rectangle \\(R_{k}\\). Since the algorithm terminates with \\(C=\\varnothing\\), the union \\(\\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}R_{k}\\) equals the whole set of squares of the board minus \\(U\\). Therefore the rectangles form a valid tiling of the required type.\n\n\u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Final conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f2 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles. Lemma\u202f3 exhibits a tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles. Consequently the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
