"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains a **Critical Error** and is therefore invalid.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f3, step\u202f2 \u2013 definition of the rectangles  \n  *Issue:* Critical Error \u2013 the construction does not guarantee that every row of the board is covered; rows with index smaller than the first element \\(i_{1}\\) of the ordered list are never included in any rectangle, so the union of the rectangles cannot equal the board minus the uncovered squares.\n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n---\n\n#### Preliminary Setup\n- The solution correctly models the set of uncovered squares \\(U\\) as a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n- Definitions and notation are clear and mathematically sound.\n\n---\n\n#### Lemma\u202f1  \n- **Claim:** No tile can contain all covered squares of two distinct rows (or columns).  \n- **Reasoning:** If a tile covers all but one square in a row, its column interval must be the whole set \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) minus the single uncovered column \\(\\pi(r)\\); such an interval has length \\(n-1\\). It cannot simultaneously omit a different column \\(\\pi(s)\\) for a second row \\(s\\neq r\\).  \n- **Assessment:** The argument is correct and fully justified. No error.\n\n---\n\n#### Lemma\u202f2 (Lower bound)  \n- **Claim:** Any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \n- **Reasoning:** For each row \\(i\\) the set \\(C_i\\) of squares that must be covered has size \\(n-1\\). By Lemma\u202f1 a single tile can supply all squares of \\(C_i\\) for at most one index \\(i\\). Hence at least \\(n\\) distinct tiles are needed.  \n- **Assessment:** The deduction from Lemma\u202f1 is valid; the lower bound follows. No error.\n\n---\n\n#### Lemma\u202f3 (Upper bound \u2013 construction)\n\n1. **Ordering the rows** \u2013 the solution orders the rows \\(i_1,\\dots,i_n\\) so that \\(\\pi(i_1)<\\dots<\\pi(i_n)\\).  \n   - This ordering always exists because \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation. No problem here.\n\n2. **Definition of the rectangles** \u2013 for each \\(k\\) the rectangle is defined as  \n   \\[\n   R_k=\\{(r,c)\\mid i_k\\le r\\le n,\\; \\pi(i_k)\\le c\\le \\pi(i_{k+1})-1\\}.\n   \\]  \n   - The intervals are integer, so each \\(R_k\\) is an axis\u2011parallel rectangle (possibly degenerate).  \n\n3. **Disjointness** \u2013 column intervals are disjoint because the \\(\\pi(i_k)\\) are strictly increasing. Hence rectangles cannot share a column. This part is correct.\n\n4. **No uncovered square inside a rectangle** \u2013 the argument that each uncovered square lies on the north\u2011west boundary of the appropriate rectangle is correct.\n\n5. **Claim that the union of the rectangles equals the board minus \\(U\\)** \u2013 this is the crucial part.  \n   - The proof proceeds by induction on \\(k\\), asserting that after adding \\(R_k\\) the covered columns extend up to \\(\\pi(i_{k+1})-1\\) while all rows \\(\\ge i_k\\) are included.  \n\n   **Critical Issue:**  \n   - The row interval of each rectangle starts at \\(i_k\\) and goes down to the bottom of the board (\\(n\\)). Consequently, **no rectangle ever includes any row with index smaller than \\(\\min\\{i_1,\\dots,i_n\\}\\)**.  \n   - The ordering of the rows by increasing \\(\\pi\\) is unrelated to the numerical order of the row indices. It is entirely possible (and typical) that \\(i_1\\) is not equal to \\(1\\). For example, if \\(\\pi\\) happens to map row \\(5\\) to the smallest column, then \\(i_1=5\\). In that case rows \\(1,2,3,4\\) are **not** contained in the row interval of any rectangle \\(R_k\\), because every \\(R_k\\) requires \\(r\\ge i_k\\ge 5\\).  \n   - Therefore those rows would remain uncovered, contradicting the requirement that every unit square except the \\(n\\) uncovered ones must be covered by a tile.  \n\n   - The induction argument implicitly assumes that the row intervals together cover all rows, but this assumption is false without an additional guarantee that \\(i_1=1\\) (or that the ordered list \\((i_k)\\) is monotone decreasing). The solution never establishes such a property, nor does it modify the construction to handle rows above \\(i_1\\).  \n\n   - Hence the statement (4) \\(B\\setminus U=\\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}R_k\\) is **incorrect** for a general permutation \\(\\pi\\). The construction does not produce a valid tiling in general.\n\n6. **Number of tiles** \u2013 even if the construction were correct, it would indeed use exactly \\(n\\) rectangles. This part is fine, but it is moot because the construction fails to cover the whole board.\n\n---\n\n#### Overall Conclusion\n- Lemma\u202f1 and Lemma\u202f2 are correct.  \n- Lemma\u202f3, which is intended to provide the matching upper bound, contains a **critical error**: the defined rectangles do not necessarily cover all rows of the board, so the claimed tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles does not exist for arbitrary permutations \\(\\pi\\). Consequently the proof that the minimum number of tiles equals \\(n=2025\\) is invalid.  \n\nBecause the central construction is flawed, the solution does not establish the required upper bound, and the overall answer cannot be accepted as correct."
