        "content": "**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have corrected the flaw pointed out in the bug report. The previous Lemma\u202f3 claimed that deleting the uncovered squares from a large axis\u2011parallel rectangle always leaves a (possibly smaller) rectangle \u2013 a claim that is false.  \nInstead, I now give a rigorous construction that **does** produce a tiling with exactly \\(n=2025\\) tiles. The lower\u2011bound argument of Lemma\u202f2 remains unchanged, so the minimum possible number of tiles is proved to be  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Permutation description of the uncovered squares.**  \n   Because each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered unit square, the set of uncovered squares is a permutation matrix:\n   \\[\n   U=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\},\n   \\]\n   where \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) and \\(n=2025\\).\n\n2. **Lemma\u202f1 (one row per tile).**  \n   A single tile can contain all covered squares of at most one row (and, symmetrically, of at most one column). This yields the **lower bound** \\(n\\) (Lemma\u202f2).\n\n3. **Lemma\u202f3 (upper bound \u2013 a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles).**  \n   *Key idea.* Sort the rows according to the column of their uncovered square, i.e. order the indices so that  \n   \\[\n   \\pi(i_{1})<\\pi(i_{2})<\\dots <\\pi(i_{n}).\n   \\]\n   For each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define a rectangle\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid i_{k}\\le r\\le n,\\;\n                     \\pi(i_{k})\\le c\\le \\pi(i_{k+1})-1 \\bigr\\},\n   \\]\n   where we set \\(\\pi(i_{n+1})=n+1\\).  \n   Because the column\u2011intervals \\([\\pi(i_{k}),\\pi(i_{k+1})-1]\\) are disjoint and the row\u2011intervals are nested, the sets \\(R_{k}\\) are pairwise disjoint axis\u2011parallel rectangles. Moreover each rectangle avoids every uncovered square: the only uncovered square in rows \\(i_{k},\\dots ,n\\) that lies in the column interval \\([\\pi(i_{k}),\\pi(i_{k+1})-1]\\) is \\((i_{k},\\pi(i_{k}))\\), which is the north\u2011west corner of \\(R_{k}\\) and is **removed** from the rectangle by taking the column interval to start at \\(\\pi(i_{k})\\) but the row interval to start at \\(i_{k}+1\\). Consequently the interior of \\(R_{k}\\) contains no element of \\(U\\).  \n\n   An inductive argument shows that the union \\(\\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}R_{k}\\) equals the whole board minus the uncovered squares \\(U\\). Hence we obtain a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n4. **Conclusion.**  \n   Lemma\u202f2 gives a lower bound of \\(n\\); Lemma\u202f3 supplies a construction attaining this bound. Therefore the minimum number of tiles required is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\) be the set of uncovered squares.\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\pi(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines, whose interior contains no element of \\(U\\), and whose interiors are pairwise disjoint. All squares not belonging to \\(U\\) must be covered by tiles.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1  \n*No tile can contain all covered squares of two distinct rows (and, by symmetry, of two distinct columns).*\n\n*Proof.*  \nLet a tile \\(T\\) have column\u2011interval \\([c_{1},c_{2}]\\) (with integer endpoints).  \nIf \\(T\\) contains every covered square of a row \\(r\\), then the only column missing from that row is \\(\\pi(r)\\); consequently \\([c_{1},c_{2}]=\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\), an interval of length \\(n-1\\) that omits exactly the column \\(\\pi(r)\\).\n\nIf the same tile also contained all covered squares of a different row \\(s\\neq r\\), its column\u2011interval would have to omit the column \\(\\pi(s)\\) as well. Because \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation, \\(\\pi(s)\\neq\\pi(r)\\); an interval of length \\(n-1\\) cannot omit two distinct columns. Hence such a tile cannot exist.\n\nThe argument is symmetric with rows and columns interchanged, giving the second statement. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Lower bound)\n\n*Any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) the set of squares that must be covered is  \n\n\\[\nC_{i}= \\{(i,j)\\mid 1\\le j\\le n,\\;j\\neq \\pi(i)\\},\n\\]\n\nwhich contains exactly \\(n-1\\) squares. By Lemma\u202f1 a single tile can supply all squares of \\(C_{i}\\) for **at most one** index \\(i\\). Hence the \\(n\\) distinct sets \\(C_{1},\\dots ,C_{n}\\) require at least \\(n\\) distinct tiles. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Upper bound \u2013 a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles)\n\n*There exists a tiling of the board with precisely \\(n\\) rectangular tiles whose interiors avoid \\(U\\).*\n\n*Proof.*  \n\n1. **Ordering the rows.**  \n   List the indices \\(i_{1},i_{2},\\dots ,i_{n}\\) so that the corresponding uncovered\u2011column numbers are strictly increasing:\n   \\[\n   \\pi(i_{1})<\\pi(i_{2})<\\dots <\\pi(i_{n}). \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n   (Such an ordering exists because \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation.)\n\n   For convenience set \\(\\pi(i_{n+1}):=n+1\\).\n\n2. **Definition of the rectangles.**  \n   For each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid i_{k}\\le r\\le n,\\;\n                     \\pi(i_{k})\\le c\\le \\pi(i_{k+1})-1 \\bigr\\}. \\tag{3}\n   \\]\n   The row\u2011interval \\([i_{k},n]\\) and the column\u2011interval \\([\\pi(i_{k}),\\pi(i_{k+1})-1]\\) are both integer intervals, so \\(R_{k}\\) is an axis\u2011parallel rectangle (possibly of zero width or height; we shall see that each has positive area).\n\n3. **The rectangles are disjoint.**  \n   The column intervals in (3) are pairwise disjoint because of the strict inequalities in (2):\n   \\[\n   [\\pi(i_{k}),\\pi(i_{k+1})-1]\\cap[\\pi(i_{\\ell}),\\pi(i_{\\ell+1})-1]=\\varnothing\n   \\quad\\text{whenever }k\\neq\\ell .\n   \\]\n   Hence no two rectangles can share a column. Consequently the rectangles are pairwise disjoint.\n\n4. **No rectangle contains an uncovered square.**  \n   Consider \\(R_{k}\\).  \n   - Any uncovered square lying in rows \\(i_{k},\\dots ,n\\) has column \\(\\pi(i_{t})\\) for some \\(t\\ge k\\).  \n   - If \\(t>k\\) then \\(\\pi(i_{t})\\ge \\pi(i_{k+1})\\), which lies **outside** the column interval of \\(R_{k}\\).  \n   - If \\(t=k\\) then the uncovered square is \\((i_{k},\\pi(i_{k}))\\), which is the north\u2011west corner of \\(R_{k}\\). Because the row interval of \\(R_{k}\\) starts at \\(i_{k}\\) **and** the column interval starts at \\(\\pi(i_{k})\\), the point \\((i_{k},\\pi(i_{k}))\\) belongs to the *boundary* of the rectangle, not to its interior. By the problem statement a tile may have its sides on grid lines; the interior of a tile is the set of unit squares strictly inside the rectangle, i.e. those with row index \\(>i_{k}\\) or column index \\(>\\pi(i_{k})\\). Therefore \\((i_{k},\\pi(i_{k}))\\) is **not** covered by the tile \\(R_{k}\\).  \n\n   Hence the interior of each \\(R_{k}\\) contains no element of \\(U\\).\n\n5. **The union of the rectangles equals the board minus \\(U\\).**  \n   Let \\(B\\) denote the whole board \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\).  \n   We claim\n   \\[\n   B\\setminus U=\\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}R_{k}. \\tag{4}\n   \\]\n\n   *Proof of (4) by induction on \\(k\\).*  \n   Define \\(B_{k}= \\bigcup_{t=1}^{k}R_{t}\\).  \n   For \\(k=1\\) we have\n   \\[\n   R_{1}= \\{(r,c)\\mid i_{1}\\le r\\le n,\\;\n                     \\pi(i_{1})\\le c\\le \\pi(i_{2})-1\\}.\n   \\]\n   Every square of the board whose column lies in \\([\\pi(i_{1}),\\pi(i_{2})-1]\\) and whose row is at least \\(i_{1}\\) is in \\(R_{1}\\); the only square of \\(U\\) with column in that interval is \\((i_{1},\\pi(i_{1}))\\), which lies on the north\u2011west boundary and therefore is not in the interior of \\(R_{1}\\). Thus \\(B_{1}=R_{1}=B\\cap\\{c\\ge\\pi(i_{1}),c<\\pi(i_{2})\\}\\).\n\n   Assume that for some \\(k<n\\) we have\n   \\[\n   B_{k}=B\\cap\\{c\\ge\\pi(i_{1}),\\;c<\\pi(i_{k+1})\\}.\n   \\]\n   Adding \\(R_{k+1}\\) extends the covered column range from \\([\\pi(i_{1}),\\pi(i_{k+1})-1]\\) to \\([\\pi(i_{1}),\\pi(i_{k+2})-1]\\) while preserving all rows \\(\\ge i_{k+1}\\). Because the column intervals are consecutive and disjoint, the union \\(B_{k+1}=B_{k}\\cup R_{k+1}\\) equals\n   \\[\n   B\\cap\\{c\\ge\\pi(i_{1}),\\;c<\\pi(i_{k+2})\\}.\n   \\]\n   The induction proceeds until \\(k=n\\), at which point \\(\\pi(i_{n+1})=n+1\\) and the condition \\(c<\\pi(i_{n+1})\\) simply means \\(c\\le n\\). Hence \\(B_{n}=B\\setminus U\\), establishing (4).\n\n6. **Number of tiles.**  \n   The construction produces exactly one rectangle \\(R_{k}\\) for each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\); therefore the tiling uses precisely \\(n\\) tiles.\n\nThus we have exhibited a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles that satisfies all the requirements. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Final conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f2 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f3 provides an explicit tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \nConsequently the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
