her cover **all** rows \\(1,\\dots ,n\\); the column\u2011intervals \\([\\pi(i_{k})+1,\\pi(i_{k+1})]\\) are also consecutive and together cover all columns \\(1,\\dots ,n\\).  \n   Because the column intervals are disjoint, the rectangles \\(R_{k}\\) are pairwise disjoint.  \n   The only uncovered square that lies inside the row\u2011interval of \\(R_{k}\\) and whose column lies inside the column\u2011interval of \\(R_{k}\\) is \\((i_{k+1},\\pi(i_{k+1}))\\); this square is the **south\u2011east** corner of \\(R_{k}\\) and therefore belongs to the boundary, not to the interior of the tile. Consequently every interior of \\(R_{k}\\) avoids \\(U\\).\n\n   An elementary induction shows that  \n\n   \\[\n   \\bigcup_{k=0}^{n-1}R_{k}= \\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\setminus U,\n   \\]\n\n   i.e. the rectangles cover exactly the set of squares that must be tiled.  \n   Thus we obtain a tiling with precisely \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n4. **Conclusion.**  \n   Lemma\u202f1 gives the lower bound \\(n\\); Lemma\u202f2 supplies a construction attaining this bound. Hence the minimum number of tiles required is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\) be the set of uncovered squares.\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines; the interior of a tile consists of the unit squares whose row and column indices lie strictly inside the rectangle. Tiles must be pairwise interior\u2011disjoint and together must cover every square of the board that is not in \\(U\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Lower bound)\n\n*No tile can contain the covered squares of two distinct rows (and, by symmetry, of two distinct columns). Consequently any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nConsider a tile \\(T\\) whose column interval is \\([c_{1},c_{2}]\\) (with integer endpoints).  \nIf \\(T\\) contains all covered squares of row \\(r\\), then the only column missing from that row is \\(\\pi(r)\\); therefore \\([c_{1},c_{2}]=\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\), an interval of length \\(n-1\\) that omits exactly the column \\(\\pi(r)\\).\n\nIf the same tile also contained all covered squares of a different row \\(s\\neq r\\), its column interval would have to omit the column \\(\\pi(s)\\) as well. Because \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation, \\(\\pi(s)\\neq\\pi(r)\\); an interval of length \\(n-1\\) cannot omit two distinct columns. Hence such a tile cannot exist.\n\nThe argument is symmetric with rows and columns interchanged, giving the second statement. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Upper bound \u2013 a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles)\n\n*There exists a tiling of the board with precisely \\(n\\) rectangular tiles whose interiors avoid \\(U\\).*\n\n*Proof.*  \n\n1. **Ordering the rows.**  \n   Choose a permutation \\((i_{1},i_{2},\\dots ,i_{n})\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n   \\[\n   \\pi(i_{1})<\\pi(i_{2})<\\dots <\\pi(i_{n}). \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n\n   (Such an ordering exists because \\(\\pi\\) is a bijection.)\n\n   For convenience introduce the \u201cvirtual\u2019\u2019 indices  \n\n   \\[\n   i_{0}=0,\\qquad i_{n+1}=n+1,\n   \\]\n   and define  \n\n   \\[\n   \\pi(i_{0})=0,\\qquad \\pi(i_{n+1})=n+1.\n   \\]\n\n   Note that \\(i_{0}\\) and \\(i_{n+1}\\) are **not** actual rows of the board; they are only used to simplify the notation.\n\n2. **Definition of the rectangles.**  \n   For each \\(k=0,1,\\dots ,n-1\\) set  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid i_{k}+1\\le r\\le i_{k+1},\\;\n                     \\pi(i_{k})+1\\le c\\le \\pi(i_{k+1})\\bigr\\}. \\tag{3}\n   \\]\n\n   The row interval \\([i_{k}+1,i_{k+1}]\\) and the column interval \\([\\pi(i_{k})+1,\\pi(i_{k+1})]\\) are ordinary integer intervals, so each \\(R_{k}\\) is an axis\u2011parallel rectangle (possibly of width or height \\(1\\), but never empty because the inequalities in (2) are strict).\n\n3. **The rectangles are pairwise disjoint.**  \n   The column intervals in (3) are disjoint: for distinct \\(k,\\ell\\) we have  \n\n   \\[\n   [\\pi(i_{k})+1,\\pi(i_{k+1})]\\cap[\\pi(i_{\\ell})+1,\\pi(i_{\\ell+1})]=\\varnothing,\n   \\]\n   because the numbers \\(\\pi(i_{1}),\\dots ,\\pi(i_{n})\\) are strictly increasing.  \n   Hence no two rectangles share a column, and therefore they are interior\u2011disjoint.\n\n4. **No rectangle contains an uncovered square.**  \n   Fix \\(k\\). Any uncovered square lying in rows \\(i_{k}+1,\\dots ,i_{k+1}\\) has the form \\((i_{t},\\pi(i_{t}))\\) with \\(k<t\\le k+1\\).  \n\n   * If \\(t=k+1\\) then the uncovered square is \\((i_{k+1},\\pi(i_{k+1}))\\). By construction this point is the **south\u2011east** corner of \\(R_{k}\\); it belongs to the boundary of the rectangle, not to its interior, and therefore is not covered by the tile.  \n\n   * If \\(t\\le k\\) then \\(\\pi(i_{t})\\le\\pi(i_{k})\\), which lies **left** of the column interval of \\(R_{k}\\).  \n\n   Consequently the interior of \\(R_{k}\\) contains no element of \\(U\\).\n\n5. **The union of the rectangles equals the board minus \\(U\\).**  \n   The row intervals in (3) are consecutive and together cover all rows \\(1,\\dots ,n\\):\n   \\[\n   \\bigcup_{k=0}^{n-1}[i_{k}+1,i_{k+1}]=\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n   \\]\n   Likewise the column intervals are consecutive and together cover all columns \\(1,\\dots ,n\\):\n   \\[\n   \\bigcup_{k=0}^{n-1}[\\pi(i_{k})+1,\\pi(i_{k+1})]=\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n   \\]\n\n   Hence every board square \\((r,c)\\) with \\(r,c\\in\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) belongs to exactly one rectangle \\(R_{k}\\) **unless** it is the south\u2011east corner \\((i_{k+1},\\pi(i_{k+1}))\\) of that rectangle. The set of all such corners is precisely the set \\(U\\) defined in (1). Therefore  \n\n   \\[\n   \\bigcup_{k=0}^{n-1}R_{k}= \\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\setminus U. \\tag{4}\n   \\]\n\n   Equation (4) shows that the interiors of the \\(n\\) rectangles tile exactly the required squares.\n\n6. **Number of tiles.**  \n   The construction produces one rectangle for each \\(k=0,1,\\dots ,n-1\\); thus the tiling uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.\n\nThus a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles exists. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Final conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f1 proves that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f2 exhibits a tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \nHence the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
    },
