        "content": "\n======================================================================\n### Problem ###\n\n*** Problem Statement ***\n\nConsider a $2025\\times2025$ grid of unit squares. Matilda wishes to place on the grid some rectangular tiles, possibly of difference sizes, such that each side of every tile lies on a grid line and every unit square is covered by at most one tile.\n\nDetermine the minimum number of tiles Matilda needs to place so that each row and each column of the grid has exactly one unit square that is not covered by any tile.\n\n======================================================================\n### Solution ###\n\n**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\) be the set of uncovered squares.\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines; the interior of a tile consists of the unit squares whose row and column indices lie strictly inside the rectangle. Tiles must be pairwise interior\u2011disjoint and together must cover every square of the board that is not in \\(U\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Lower bound)\n\n*No tile can contain the covered squares of two distinct rows (and, by symmetry, of two distinct columns). Consequently any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nConsider a tile \\(T\\). Let its column interval be \\([c_{1},c_{2}]\\) (with integer endpoints). If \\(T\\) contains all covered squares of row \\(r\\), then the only column missing from that row is \\(\\pi(r)\\); therefore \\([c_{1},c_{2}]=\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\), an interval of length \\(n-1\\) that omits exactly the column \\(\\pi(r)\\).\n\nIf the same tile also contained all covered squares of a different row \\(s\\neq r\\), its column interval would have to omit the column \\(\\pi(s)\\) as well. Because \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation, \\(\\pi(s)\\neq\\pi(r)\\); an interval of length \\(n-1\\) cannot omit two distinct columns. Hence such a tile cannot exist.\n\nThe argument is symmetric with rows and columns interchanged, giving the second statement. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Upper bound \u2013 a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles)\n\n*There exists a tiling of the board with precisely \\(n\\) rectangular tiles whose interiors avoid \\(U\\).*\n\n*Proof.*  \n\n1. **Ordering the columns.**  \n   Write the numbers \\(\\pi(1),\\dots ,\\pi(n)\\) in increasing order and denote them  \n\n   \\[\n   0=\\pi_{0}<\\pi_{1}<\\pi_{2}<\\dots <\\pi_{n}<\\pi_{n+1}=n+1 .\n   \\]\n\n   For each \\(k\\in\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) let \\(r_{k}\\) be the (unique) row whose uncovered column equals \\(\\pi_{k}\\); i.e. \\(\\pi(r_{k})=\\pi_{k}\\).  \n   The rows \\(r_{1},\\dots ,r_{n}\\) form a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).\n\n2. **Definition of the rectangles.**  \n   For every \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le n,\\;\n                     \\pi_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\pi_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n\n   The set on the right\u2011hand side is a genuine axis\u2011parallel rectangle: its rows are the consecutive integers \\(r_{k},r_{k}+1,\\dots ,n\\) and its columns are the consecutive integers \\(\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\dots ,\\pi_{k}\\).\n\n3. **The rectangles are pairwise interior\u2011disjoint.**  \n   The column intervals \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\) are disjoint because the \\(\\pi_{k}\\)\u2019s are strictly increasing. Hence two different rectangles cannot share a column, and therefore their interiors are disjoint even though the row intervals are nested (\\(r_{1},\\dots ,r_{n}\\) need not be monotone).\n\n4. **No rectangle contains an uncovered square.**  \n   The only uncovered square whose column lies in \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\) is \\((r_{k},\\pi_{k})\\). This square is the north\u2011west corner of \\(R_{k}\\); it belongs to the boundary of the rectangle, not to its interior, and consequently is not covered by the tile.\n\n5. **The union of the rectangles equals the board minus \\(U\\).**  \n\n   *Covering all columns.*  \n   By construction the column intervals form a partition of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\); every column \\(c\\) belongs to exactly one interval \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\).\n\n   *Covering all rows for a fixed column.*  \n   Fix a column \\(c\\) and let \\(k\\) be the unique index with \\(c\\in[\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\).  \n   For any row \\(r\\) we have two possibilities:\n\n   *If \\(r\\ge r_{k}\\)*, then \\((r,c)\\in R_{k}\\) by definition (2).\n\n   *If \\(r< r_{k}\\)*, then because the rows \\(r_{1},\\dots ,r_{n}\\) are a permutation, there exists an index \\(\\ell>k\\) such that \\(r_{\\ell}\\le r\\). Indeed, among the rows whose uncovered columns are larger than \\(\\pi_{k}\\) (i.e. indices \\(\\ell>k\\)) the smallest row number is at most \\(r\\). For this \\(\\ell\\) we have \\(c\\in[\\pi_{\\ell-1}+1,\\pi_{\\ell}]\\) (since \\(\\ell>k\\) the column interval of \\(R_{\\ell}\\) also contains \\(c\\)) and \\(r\\ge r_{\\ell}\\); consequently \\((r,c)\\in R_{\\ell}\\).\n\n   Thus **every** square \\((r,c)\\) with \\(c\\in\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) and \\(r\\in\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) lies in at least one rectangle \\(R_{k}\\). The only squares that are not interior points of any rectangle are the north\u2011west corners \\((r_{k},\\pi_{k})\\), \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\), which are exactly the uncovered squares \\(U\\) by definition. Hence  \n\n   \\[\n   \\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}R_{k}= \\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\setminus U . \\tag{3}\n   \\]\n\n6. **Number of tiles.**  \n   The construction produces one rectangle for each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\); therefore the tiling uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.\n\nThus a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles exists. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Final conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f1 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f2 provides an explicit tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \nConsequently the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n\n### Verification Task Reminder ###\n\nYour task is to act as an IMO grader. Now, generate the **summary** and the **step-by-step verification log** for the solution above. In your log, justify each correct step and explain in detail any errors or justification gaps you find, as specified in the instructions above.\n\n"
    }
