"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains a **Critical Error** and is therefore invalid.\n\n**List of Findings**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f1, first paragraph: \u201cIf\u202f\\(T\\) contains all covered squares of row\u202f\\(r\\), then \u2026 \\([c_{1},c_{2}]=\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\), an interval of length \\(n-1\\) \u2026\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the argument assumes that the set of columns occupied by a tile that covers all *covered* squares of a row must be the whole set of columns except the uncovered one, and that this set is necessarily a single contiguous interval. This is false: a tile may omit the uncovered column by stopping at its left or right side, producing an interval that does **not** contain the uncovered column but is still of length \\(n-1\\) only when the uncovered column is at an extreme; otherwise the required set is not an interval at all. Consequently the conclusion that a tile cannot cover two rows is unjustified, breaking the lower\u2011bound argument.\n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n#### Preliminary definitions\n- The solution defines \\(n=2025\\) and the set of uncovered squares \\(U\\) as a permutation graph \\(\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\}\\).  \n  *Correct*: This follows directly from the condition \u201cexactly one uncovered square in each row and column\u201d.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f1 (Lower bound)\n\n1. **Statement**: \u201cNo tile can contain the covered squares of two distinct rows \u2026 Consequently any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.\u201d\n   - The intended conclusion is plausible, but the proof given is flawed.\n\n2. **Proof step**:  \n   > \u201cConsider a tile \\(T\\). Let its column interval be \\([c_{1},c_{2}]\\) (with integer endpoints). If \\(T\\) contains all covered squares of row \\(r\\), then the only column missing from that row is \\(\\pi(r)\\); therefore \\([c_{1},c_{2}]=\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\), an interval of length \\(n-1\\) that omits exactly the column \\(\\pi(r)\\).\u201d\n\n   - **Error analysis**:  \n     * A tile is a rectangle whose **interior** consists of unit squares whose row and column indices lie *strictly* inside the rectangle. Hence a tile covering all *covered* squares of row \\(r\\) must contain every column **except possibly the uncovered one**, **but it need not contain the columns on both sides of the uncovered column**.  \n     * For example, if the uncovered column in row \\(r\\) is \\(\\pi(r)=5\\) in a board of size \\(n=10\\), a tile could be the rectangle covering columns \\(1\\) through \\(4\\) (i.e. \\([1,4]\\)) and all rows from some \\(r_0\\) to \\(n\\). This rectangle\u2019s column interval \\([1,4]\\) does **not** equal \\(\\{1,\\dots ,10\\}\\setminus\\{5\\}\\); it is a proper sub\u2011interval that still contains all covered squares of that row because the uncovered square lies to the right of the tile.  \n     * The claim that the column set must be exactly \u201call columns except the uncovered one\u201d is therefore false unless the uncovered column happens to be at the extreme left or right of the board. The solution never justifies why the tile must extend to both sides of the uncovered column, nor why the column set must be contiguous.  \n     * Because the set \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\pi(r)\\}\\) is **not** an interval when \\(\\pi(r)\\) is interior, the statement \u201can interval of length \\(n-1\\)\u201d is incorrect.\n\n   - **Consequence**: The deduction that a tile cannot contain the covered squares of two different rows relies on the (false) premise that the column interval would have to omit two distinct columns while remaining a single interval of length \\(n-1\\). Since the premise is invalid, the conclusion does not follow.\n\n   - **Classification**: This is a **Critical Error** because it invalidates the entire lower\u2011bound argument. Once the lower bound is not established, the claim that at least \\(n\\) tiles are necessary is unsupported.\n\n3. **Symmetry argument**: The proof repeats the same flawed reasoning for rows. Since the initial reasoning is already incorrect, this part is also invalid, but it does not introduce a new error.\n\n4. **Result of Lemma\u202f1**: Because the proof of Lemma\u202f1 fails, the statement \u201cany admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles\u201d is unproven.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f2 (Upper bound)\n\nThe construction of a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles is presented in several steps. We evaluate each step assuming the construction is correct; the correctness of the construction does not depend on Lemma\u202f1.\n\n1. **Ordering the columns** \u2013 The solution orders the values \\(\\pi(1),\\dots ,\\pi(n)\\) and introduces \\(\\pi_0=0,\\ \\pi_{n+1}=n+1\\).  \n   *Correct*: This is a standard way to create a sorted list of the uncovered column indices.\n\n2. **Definition of the rectangles** \u2013 For each \\(k\\) the rectangle \\(R_k\\) is defined as  \n   \\[\n   R_k=\\{(r,c)\\mid r_k\\le r\\le n,\\; \\pi_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\pi_k\\}.\n   \\]  \n   *Correct*: The definition yields an axis\u2011parallel rectangle (possibly of height \\(n-r_k+1\\) and width \\(\\pi_k-\\pi_{k-1}\\)). The notation is clear.\n\n3. **Pairwise interior\u2011disjointness** \u2013 The argument states that column intervals are disjoint, therefore interiors are disjoint even though row intervals are nested.  \n   *Correct*: Since rectangles are defined with *closed* column intervals that are mutually exclusive, no two rectangles share any interior point (they may touch along a vertical edge, which is allowed).\n\n4. **No rectangle contains an uncovered square** \u2013 The only uncovered square with column in \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_k]\\) is \\((r_k,\\pi_k)\\), which is the north\u2011west corner of \\(R_k\\) and lies on the boundary.  \n   *Correct*: By construction, \\((r_k,\\pi_k)\\) is excluded from the interior because the row condition is \\(r\\ge r_k\\) and the column condition is \\(c\\le \\pi_k\\); the point \\((r_k,\\pi_k)\\) satisfies both equalities, placing it on the boundary, not the interior.\n\n5. **Covering argument** \u2013 The solution attempts to show that every covered square belongs to at least one rectangle.  \n   - The \u201ccovering all columns\u201d part is fine: the column intervals partition \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   - The \u201ccovering all rows for a fixed column\u201d part contains a **Justification Gap**:  \n\n     The claim is that for a column \\(c\\) belonging to interval \\(k\\) and a row \\(r<r_k\\), there exists an index \\(\\ell>k\\) with \\(r_\\ell\\le r\\). The argument given (\u201camong the rows whose uncovered columns are larger than \\(\\pi_k\\) \u2026 the smallest row number is at most \\(r\\)\u201d) is not rigorously proved. It relies on an ordering property of the pairs \\((r_i,\\pi_i)\\) that has not been established; in particular, the rows \\(r_1,\\dots ,r_n\\) need not be monotone with respect to the ordered columns \\(\\pi_i\\). Without a formal proof, the existence of such an \\(\\ell\\) remains unverified.  \n\n     *Classification*: **Justification Gap** \u2013 the step may be true, but the solution does not provide a rigorous argument.\n\n   - Assuming the gap is filled, the rest of the covering argument follows.\n\n6. **Number of tiles** \u2013 The construction clearly uses exactly \\(n\\) rectangles.  \n   *Correct*.\n\nThus Lemma\u202f2, modulo the noted justification gap, does produce a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n#### Final conclusion\n\nThe solution\u2019s final statement \u201cthe minimum possible number of tiles is 2025\u201d depends on both Lemma\u202f1 (lower bound) and Lemma\u202f2 (upper bound). Because Lemma\u202f1 contains a **Critical Error**, the lower bound of \\(n\\) tiles is not established. Consequently the conclusion that the minimum equals \\(n\\) is unsupported. Even though Lemma\u202f2 correctly exhibits a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles, without a valid proof that fewer than \\(n\\) tiles are impossible, the answer cannot be claimed as minimal.\n\n**Overall assessment:** The solution is invalid due to a critical flaw in the lower\u2011bound argument (Lemma\u202f1). Additionally, Lemma\u202f2 contains a justification gap in the covering argument, but the decisive issue is the critical error that undermines the entire proof of minimality."
