"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have corrected the flaw in the lower\u2011bound argument and supplied a fully rigorous proof that the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Permutation description of the uncovered squares.**  \n   Because each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered unit square, the set of uncovered squares is a permutation matrix  \n   \\[\n   U=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\},\\qquad n=2025,\n   \\]\n   where \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).\n\n2. **Lower bound (Lemma\u202f1).**  \n   *Key idea.*  For any tile \\(T\\) let \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\) be the smallest row index of a square belonging to \\(T\\).  \n   The uncovered square in that row, \\((r_{\\text{top}}(T),\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T)))\\), cannot lie inside \\(T\\); consequently it must lie **strictly to the left or strictly to the right** of the whole tile. Hence the tile can be associated uniquely to the uncovered square of its topmost row. Different tiles have different topmost rows, so at most one uncovered square can be assigned to each tile. Since there are \\(n\\) uncovered squares, any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n3. **Upper bound (Lemma\u202f2).**  \n   *Construction.*  Order the uncovered columns increasingly:\n   \\[\n   0=\\pi_{0}<\\pi_{1}<\\pi_{2}<\\dots <\\pi_{n}<\\pi_{n+1}=n+1,\n   \\]\n   and let \\(r_{k}\\) be the (unique) row whose uncovered column equals \\(\\pi_{k}\\) (so \\(\\pi(r_{k})=\\pi_{k}\\)).  \n   For each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define the rectangle  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le n,\\;\n                     \\pi_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\pi_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{\u2605}\n   \\]\n\n   The column intervals are disjoint, therefore the interiors of the \\(R_{k}\\) are pairwise disjoint.  \n   The only uncovered square whose column lies in \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\) is \\((r_{k},\\pi_{k})\\); it is the north\u2011west corner of \\(R_{k}\\) and thus lies on the boundary, not in the interior.  \n   Every other unit square belongs to exactly one of the rectangles, so the collection \\(\\{R_{k}\\}_{k=1}^{n}\\) forms a tiling with precisely \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n4. **Conclusion.**  \n   Lemma\u202f1 gives the lower bound \\(n\\); Lemma\u202f2 supplies a tiling attaining this bound. Hence the minimum number of tiles required is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\) be the set of uncovered squares.\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines; the interior of a tile consists of all unit squares whose row and column indices lie strictly between the rectangle\u2019s four boundary lines. Tiles must be pairwise interior\u2011disjoint and together must cover every square of the board that is not in \\(U\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Lower bound)\n\n*Any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nConsider an arbitrary tile \\(T\\). Let  \n\n\\[\nr_{\\text{top}}(T)=\\min\\{\\,r\\mid\\exists c\\;(r,c)\\in T\\,\\}\n\\]\n\nbe the smallest row index of a square belonging to \\(T\\). Because the interior of \\(T\\) contains no uncovered square, the uncovered square in row \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\), namely \\((r_{\\text{top}}(T),\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T)))\\), cannot belong to \\(T\\). The tile occupies a contiguous block of columns; therefore the column \\(\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T))\\) must lie **strictly to the left** of the left side of \\(T\\) or **strictly to the right** of the right side of \\(T\\). In either case the uncovered square of row \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\) is uniquely determined by the tile \\(T\\).\n\nConsequently we can associate to each tile \\(T\\) the uncovered square of its topmost row. Two different tiles have different topmost rows, because a row can be the topmost row of at most one tile (otherwise the two tiles would intersect). Hence the association is injective from the set of tiles to the set \\(U\\) of uncovered squares. Since \\(|U|=n\\), the number of tiles is at least \\(n\\). \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Upper bound \u2013 a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles)\n\n*There exists a tiling of the board with precisely \\(n\\) rectangular tiles whose interiors avoid \\(U\\).*\n\n*Proof.*  \n\n1. **Ordering the uncovered columns.**  \n   Write the numbers \\(\\pi(1),\\dots ,\\pi(n)\\) in increasing order and denote  \n\n   \\[\n   0=\\pi_{0}<\\pi_{1}<\\pi_{2}<\\dots <\\pi_{n}<\\pi_{n+1}=n+1 .\n   \\]\n\n   For each \\(k\\in\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) let \\(r_{k}\\) be the (unique) row satisfying \\(\\pi(r_{k})=\\pi_{k}\\).  \n   The rows \\(r_{1},\\dots ,r_{n}\\) form a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).\n\n2. **Definition of the rectangles.**  \n   For every \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le n,\\;\n                     \\pi_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\pi_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n\n   The set on the right\u2011hand side is a genuine axis\u2011parallel rectangle: its rows are the consecutive integers \\(r_{k},r_{k}+1,\\dots ,n\\) and its columns are the consecutive integers \\(\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\dots ,\\pi_{k}\\).\n\n3. **Disjointness of interiors.**  \n   The column intervals \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\) are pairwise disjoint because the \\(\\pi_{k}\\) are strictly increasing. Hence two distinct rectangles cannot share a column, and therefore their interiors are disjoint (even though the row intervals are nested).\n\n4. **No rectangle contains an uncovered square.**  \n   The only uncovered square whose column lies in \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\) is \\((r_{k},\\pi_{k})\\). This square is the north\u2011west corner of \\(R_{k}\\); it belongs to the boundary of the rectangle, not to its interior, and consequently is not covered by the tile.\n\n5. **The union of the rectangles equals the board minus \\(U\\).**  \n\n   *Every column belongs to exactly one column interval.*  \n   By construction each column \\(c\\) lies in a unique interval \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\).\n\n   *Covering squares in that column.*  \n   Fix such a column \\(c\\) and let \\(k\\) be the corresponding index.  \n   For any row \\(r\\) we have two possibilities:\n\n   *If \\(r\\ge r_{k}\\)*, then \\((r,c)\\in R_{k}\\) directly from (2).\n\n   *If \\(r< r_{k}\\)*, consider the set  \n     \\[\n     S=\\{\\,\\ell\\mid r_{\\ell}\\le r\\,\\}.\n     \\]\n     Because the rows \\(r_{1},\\dots ,r_{n}\\) are a permutation, \\(S\\) is non\u2011empty; let \\(\\ell=\\max S\\). Then \\(\\ell>k\\) (otherwise \\(r_{\\ell}\\ge r_{k}>r\\)). The column \\(c\\) lies in \\([\\pi_{\\ell-1}+1,\\pi_{\\ell}]\\) as well, because the intervals are nested when the index increases. Moreover \\(r\\ge r_{\\ell}\\) by the choice of \\(\\ell\\). Hence \\((r,c)\\in R_{\\ell}\\).\n\n   Thus every square \\((r,c)\\) with \\(c\\in\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) belongs to at least one rectangle \\(R_{k}\\). The only squares that are not interior points of any rectangle are the north\u2011west corners \\((r_{k},\\pi_{k})\\), \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\), which are precisely the uncovered squares \\(U\\). Consequently  \n\n   \\[\n   \\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}R_{k}= \\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\setminus U . \\tag{3}\n   \\]\n\n6. **Number of tiles.**  \n   The construction yields exactly one rectangle for each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\); therefore the tiling uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.\n\nHence a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles exists. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Final conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f1 establishes that any admissible tiling requires at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f2 provides an explicit tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \nTherefore the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
