"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains **Justification Gaps** and therefore is not fully rigorous.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, step\u202f5 (\u201cBecause the column intervals \u2026 are nested when the index increases.\u201d)  \n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 the claim that the column intervals are nested is false; they are disjoint. The argument that every square is covered therefore lacks a rigorous justification.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, step\u202f5 (overall covering argument)  \n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 the reasoning that any square with row\u202f\\(r<r_k\\) is covered by some rectangle \\(R_\\ell\\) is incomplete and relies on the incorrect nesting claim. A rigorous proof that every such square belongs to some rectangle is missing.\n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n---\n\n#### Preliminary Setup  \n\n- The solution defines \\(n=2025\\) and the set of uncovered squares \\(U\\) as a permutation graph \\(\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\}\\).  \n  *Correct.* This follows directly from the condition that each row and each column contains exactly one uncovered unit square.\n\n---\n\n#### Lemma\u202f1 (Lower bound)\n\n1. **Definition of \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\).**  \n   *Correct.* The minimal row index of squares belonging to a tile is well\u2011defined.\n\n2. **Argument that the uncovered square in that row lies strictly left or right of the tile.**  \n   The tile occupies a contiguous block of columns; since the uncovered square of that row is not inside the tile, its column must be outside the tile\u2019s column interval.  \n   *Correct.* This uses the fact that a tile\u2019s interior contains no uncovered squares.\n\n3. **Injective association from tiles to uncovered squares.**  \n   The proof claims that two different tiles cannot share the same topmost row, because otherwise they would intersect.  \n   *Correct.* If two tiles had the same topmost row, their column intervals would overlap, forcing an interior intersection, which is prohibited.\n\n4. **Conclusion \\(|\\text{tiles}|\\ge |U|=n\\).**  \n   *Correct.* The injection yields the desired lower bound.\n\n*No errors or gaps identified in Lemma\u202f1.*\n\n---\n\n#### Lemma\u202f2 (Upper bound \u2013 construction)\n\n**Step\u202f1 \u2013 Ordering the uncovered columns.**  \n- The permutation values \\(\\pi(1),\\dots,\\pi(n)\\) are sorted to obtain a strictly increasing sequence \\(\\pi_0,\\pi_1,\\dots,\\pi_{n+1}\\).  \n  *Correct.* This is a standard re\u2011indexing.\n\n**Step\u202f2 \u2013 Definition of the rectangles \\(R_k\\).**  \n- \\(R_k=\\{(r,c)\\mid r_k\\le r\\le n,\\; \\pi_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\pi_k\\}\\).  \n  *Correct.* Each \\(R_k\\) is an axis\u2011parallel rectangle whose rows run from \\(r_k\\) down to the bottom of the board and whose columns occupy the \\(k\\)-th column interval.\n\n**Step\u202f3 \u2013 Disjointness of interiors.**  \n- The column intervals \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_k]\\) are pairwise disjoint because the \\(\\pi_k\\) are strictly increasing. Hence interiors are disjoint.  \n  *Correct.* Disjoint column intervals guarantee that interiors cannot intersect, even though the row intervals are nested.\n\n**Step\u202f4 \u2013 No rectangle contains an uncovered square.**  \n- The only uncovered square with column in \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_k]\\) is \\((r_k,\\pi_k)\\), which is the north\u2011west corner of \\(R_k\\) and lies on the boundary, not the interior.  \n  *Correct.* By construction the uncovered square sits at the top\u2011most row of the rectangle and at its rightmost column, i.e., on the boundary.\n\n**Step\u202f5 \u2013 Claim that the union of the rectangles equals the board minus \\(U\\).**  \n\n- **First part (\u201cEvery column belongs to exactly one column interval\u201d).**  \n  *Correct.* By construction each column \\(c\\) lies in a unique interval \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_k]\\).\n\n- **Second part (covering squares in that column).**  \n  The solution splits into two cases:\n\n  1. *If \\(r\\ge r_k\\), then \\((r,c)\\in R_k\\).*  \n     *Correct.* Directly from the definition of \\(R_k\\).\n\n  2. *If \\(r< r_k\\), consider the set \\(S=\\{\\ell\\mid r_\\ell\\le r\\}\\)\u2026*  \n\n     Here the argument becomes problematic:\n\n     - The set \\(S\\) is indeed non\u2011empty because the rows \\(r_1,\\dots,r_n\\) form a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots,n\\}\\); thus there exists at least one \\(\\ell\\) with \\(r_\\ell\\le r\\).  \n     - Let \\(\\ell=\\max S\\). The solution then claims \u201c\\(\\ell>k\\) (otherwise \\(r_\\ell\\ge r_k>r\\))\u201d. This inequality is **incorrect**: from \\(\\ell\\le k\\) we would have \\(r_\\ell\\ge r_k\\) only if the sequence \\(r_1,\\dots,r_n\\) were monotone, which it is not. The rows \\(r_k\\) are a permutation in arbitrary order, so no monotonicity relation between indices and row values can be inferred. Consequently the conclusion \\(\\ell>k\\) is unjustified.\n\n     - The next claim, \u201cthe column \\(c\\) lies in \\([\\pi_{\\ell-1}+1,\\pi_\\ell]\\) as well, because the intervals are nested when the index increases,\u201d is **false**. The intervals \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_k]\\) are *disjoint* (they partition the set of columns), not nested. Therefore a column belonging to the interval for index \\(k\\) cannot simultaneously belong to the interval for a different index \\(\\ell\\neq k\\).\n\n     - Because of these two incorrect statements, the reasoning that a square with \\(r<r_k\\) is covered by some rectangle \\(R_\\ell\\) is **not established**. The solution does not provide an alternative argument to guarantee coverage of such squares.\n\n  *Conclusion for Step\u202f5:* **Justification Gap** \u2013 the proof that every square not in \\(U\\) lies in the interior of some rectangle is incomplete and contains false statements about the ordering of the \\(r_k\\) and about the nesting of column intervals.\n\n- **Step\u202f5 final statement (\u201cConsequently \u2026 \\(\\bigcup_{k=1}^{n}R_k = \\{1,\\dots,n\\}^2\\setminus U\\)\u201d).**  \n  This follows from the previous claim, which is not rigorously justified; therefore the equality is not proven.\n\n**Step\u202f6 \u2013 Number of tiles.**  \n- Assuming the construction works, there are exactly \\(n\\) rectangles.  \n  *Correct* under the assumption that the construction indeed covers the whole board minus \\(U\\).\n\n**Overall assessment of Lemma\u202f2:**  \nThe construction is plausible, but the crucial covering argument (Step\u202f5) contains a **justification gap**: it relies on false monotonicity and nesting properties, and does not rigorously demonstrate that squares with rows above the top of their column\u2019s rectangle are covered. Consequently the proof that a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles exists is incomplete.\n\n---\n\n#### Final Conclusion  \n\n- Lemma\u202f1 is sound and establishes the lower bound of \\(n\\) tiles.  \n- Lemma\u202f2 attempts to exhibit a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles, but the covering argument is not rigorously justified; it contains false statements and leaves a gap in the proof.\n\n**Therefore, the solution is not fully rigorous due to the identified justification gaps.**"
