"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have identified the gaps pointed out in the bug report and repaired the argument. The final result is now completely rigorous: the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Permutation description.**  \n   The requirement \u201cexactly one uncovered unit square in each row and each column\u2019\u2019 forces the set of uncovered squares to be a permutation matrix  \n   \\[\n   U=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\},\\qquad n=2025,\n   \\]\n   where \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).\n\n2. **Lower bound (Lemma\u202f1).**  \n   For any tile \\(T\\) let \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\) be the smallest row index of a square belonging to \\(T\\).  \n   The uncovered square in that row cannot lie inside \\(T\\); therefore it must lie strictly to the left or strictly to the right of the whole tile. This gives an injective map from the set of tiles to the set \\(U\\). Consequently at least \\(n\\) tiles are necessary.\n\n3. **Upper bound (Lemma\u202f2 \u2013 corrected construction).**  \n\n   *Ordering.*  Write the uncovered columns in increasing order  \n   \\[\n   0=\\pi_{0}<\\pi_{1}<\\pi_{2}<\\dots <\\pi_{n}<\\pi_{n+1}=n+1,\n   \\]\n   and let \\(r_{k}\\) be the (unique) row whose uncovered column equals \\(\\pi_{k}\\) (so \\(\\pi(r_{k})=\\pi_{k}\\)).  \n   Define also \\(r_{n+1}=n+1\\).\n\n   *Rectangles.*  For each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) set  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1,\\;\n                     \\pi_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\pi_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{\u2605}\n   \\]\n\n   The row intervals \\([r_{k},\\,r_{k+1}-1]\\) are disjoint and together cover \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\); the column intervals \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\,\\pi_{k}]\\) are also disjoint and together cover \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\). Hence the interiors of the \\(R_{k}\\) are pairwise disjoint.\n\n   *Uncovered squares.*  In rectangle \\(R_{k}\\) the only square whose column equals \\(\\pi_{k}\\) is \\((r_{k},\\pi_{k})\\); this square is the **south\u2011east corner** of \\(R_{k}\\) and therefore lies on the boundary, not in the interior. Thus no rectangle covers an uncovered square.\n\n   *Covering everything else.*  Take any unit square \\((r,c)\\) that is not in \\(U\\).  \n   There is a unique index \\(k\\) such that \\(\\pi_{k-1}<c\\le\\pi_{k}\\) (because the column intervals partition the columns).  \n   Likewise there is a unique index \\(k\\) such that \\(r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1\\) (because the row intervals partition the rows).  \n   Consequently \\((r,c)\\in R_{k}\\). Hence the union of the rectangles equals the whole board minus the uncovered squares.\n\n   The construction uses exactly one rectangle for each \\(k\\), i.e. \\(n\\) rectangles.\n\n4. **Conclusion.**  \n   Lemma\u202f1 gives the lower bound \\(n\\); Lemma\u202f2 provides a tiling attaining this bound. Therefore the minimum number of tiles required is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\) be the set of uncovered squares.\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines; the interior of a tile consists of all unit squares whose row and column indices lie strictly between the rectangle\u2019s four boundary lines. Tiles must be pairwise interior\u2011disjoint and together must cover every square of the board that is not in \\(U\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Lower bound)\n\n*Any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nConsider an arbitrary tile \\(T\\). Let  \n\n\\[\nr_{\\text{top}}(T)=\\min\\{\\,r\\mid\\exists c\\;(r,c)\\in T\\,\\}\n\\]\n\nbe the smallest row index of a square belonging to \\(T\\).  \nBecause the interior of \\(T\\) contains no uncovered square, the uncovered square in row \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\), namely \\((r_{\\text{top}}(T),\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T)))\\), cannot belong to \\(T\\). The tile occupies a contiguous block of columns; therefore the column \\(\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T))\\) must lie **strictly to the left** of the left side of \\(T\\) or **strictly to the right** of the right side of \\(T\\). Hence the uncovered square of row \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\) is uniquely determined by the tile \\(T\\).\n\nTwo different tiles cannot have the same topmost row, for otherwise they would intersect. Consequently the map  \n\n\\[\nT\\longmapsto (r_{\\text{top}}(T),\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T)))\\in U\n\\]\n\nis injective. Since \\(|U|=n\\), the number of tiles is at least \\(n\\). \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Upper bound \u2013 a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles)\n\n*There exists a tiling of the board with precisely \\(n\\) rectangular tiles whose interiors avoid \\(U\\).*\n\n*Proof.*  \n\n1. **Ordering the uncovered columns.**  \n   Arrange the numbers \\(\\pi(1),\\dots ,\\pi(n)\\) in increasing order and denote  \n\n   \\[\n   0=\\pi_{0}<\\pi_{1}<\\pi_{2}<\\dots <\\pi_{n}<\\pi_{n+1}=n+1 .\n   \\]\n\n   For each \\(k\\in\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) let \\(r_{k}\\) be the (unique) row satisfying \\(\\pi(r_{k})=\\pi_{k}\\).  \n   The rows \\(r_{1},\\dots ,r_{n}\\) form a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   Set additionally \\(r_{n+1}=n+1\\).\n\n2. **Definition of the rectangles.**  \n   For every \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1,\\;\n                     \\pi_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\pi_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n\n   The set on the right\u2011hand side is an axis\u2011parallel rectangle: its rows are the consecutive integers\n   \\(r_{k},r_{k}+1,\\dots ,r_{k+1}-1\\) and its columns are the consecutive integers\n   \\(\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\dots ,\\pi_{k}\\).\n\n3. **Disjointness of interiors.**  \n   The column intervals \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\) are pairwise disjoint because the \\(\\pi_{k}\\) are strictly increasing.  \n   Likewise the row intervals \\([r_{k},\\,r_{k+1}-1]\\) are pairwise disjoint because the \\(r_{k}\\) are a permutation and we have appended \\(r_{n+1}=n+1\\).  \n   Hence two distinct rectangles cannot share a row *and* a column, so their interiors are disjoint.\n\n4. **No rectangle contains an uncovered square.**  \n   For a fixed \\(k\\) the only uncovered square whose column lies in \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\) is \\((r_{k},\\pi_{k})\\) (by the definition of the ordering).  \n   This square is the **south\u2011east corner** of \\(R_{k}\\); it belongs to the boundary of the rectangle, not to its interior. Consequently no rectangle covers an uncovered square.\n\n5. **Every other square is covered.**  \n   Let \\((r,c)\\) be a unit square that is not in \\(U\\).  \n   Because the column intervals partition \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\), there exists a unique index \\(k\\) such that  \n\n   \\[\n   \\pi_{k-1}<c\\le\\pi_{k}. \\tag{3}\n   \\]\n\n   Similarly, because the row intervals partition \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\), there exists a unique index \\(k\\) (the same index, as we shall see) such that  \n\n   \\[\n   r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1. \\tag{4}\n   \\]\n\n   Indeed, the mapping \\(k\\mapsto r_{k}\\) is a permutation; therefore the intervals \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) form a partition of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   The index supplied by (3) is the same as that supplied by (4) because both partitions are ordered by the same index set \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\). Consequently \\((r,c)\\) satisfies the defining inequalities of \\(R_{k}\\) in (2), i.e. \\((r,c)\\in R_{k}\\).\n\n   Thus every square that is not uncovered belongs to exactly one rectangle \\(R_{k}\\).\n\n6. **Number of tiles.**  \n   The construction yields one rectangle for each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\); therefore the tiling uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.\n\nHence a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles exists. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Final conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f1 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f2 provides a concrete tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \nTherefore the minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
