"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains a **Critical Error** and is therefore invalid.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, step\u202f2\u20133 \u2013 definition of the rectangles \\(R_k\\) and the claim that the row intervals \\([r_{k},\\,r_{k+1}-1]\\) are pairwise disjoint because the \\(r_k\\) form a permutation.\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the permutation \\((r_1,\\dots ,r_n)\\) is not necessarily ordered, so the intervals \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) can overlap. Consequently the rectangles \\(R_k\\) may intersect, invalidating the construction of a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n#### Preliminary definitions\n- The solution correctly models the uncovered squares as a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) (Equation\u202f(1)). This follows directly from the condition \u201cexactly one uncovered square in each row and each column\u201d. No issue.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f1 (Lower bound)\n\n1. **Definition of \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\).**  \n   The smallest row index of a square belonging to a tile \\(T\\) is well\u2011defined because each tile consists of a non\u2011empty set of unit squares. Correct.\n\n2. **Argument that the uncovered square in that row lies strictly left or right of the tile.**  \n   Since the interior of \\(T\\) contains no uncovered square, the unique uncovered square in row \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\) cannot be inside \\(T\\). A tile occupies a contiguous block of columns, so the column of the uncovered square must be either smaller than the leftmost column of the tile or larger than the rightmost column. This reasoning is sound.\n\n3. **Injectivity of the map \\(T\\mapsto (r_{\\text{top}}(T),\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T)))\\).**  \n   Two distinct tiles cannot share the same topmost row, because that would force them to intersect (they would both contain squares in that row). Hence the map is injective. Correct.\n\n4. **Conclusion \\(|\\text{tiles}|\\ge n\\).**  \n   Since \\(|U|=n\\) and the map is injective into \\(U\\), the number of tiles is at least \\(n\\). The lower bound is therefore valid.\n\n*Lemma\u202f1 is completely rigorous and contains no errors.*\n\n#### Lemma\u202f2 (Upper bound \u2013 claimed construction)\n\nThe goal is to exhibit a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles. The construction proceeds in several steps; we examine each.\n\n1. **Ordering the uncovered columns.**  \n   The solution sorts the values \\(\\pi(1),\\dots ,\\pi(n)\\) into an increasing list \\(\\pi_1<\\dots <\\pi_n\\) and defines \\(\\pi_0=0,\\ \\pi_{n+1}=n+1\\). This is legitimate. It also defines \\(r_k\\) as the (unique) row with \\(\\pi(r_k)=\\pi_k\\). The set \\(\\{r_1,\\dots ,r_n\\}\\) is indeed a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\). No problem here.\n\n2. **Definition of the rectangles \\(R_k\\).**  \n   \\[\n   R_k=\\{(r,c)\\mid r_k\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1,\\; \\pi_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\pi_k\\}.\n   \\]\n   This is a well\u2011defined axis\u2011parallel rectangle provided the intervals for rows and columns are non\u2011empty. The column interval is non\u2011empty because \\(\\pi_{k-1}<\\pi_k\\). However, the row interval \\([r_k,\\,r_{k+1}-1]\\) may be empty or may have negative length if \\(r_{k+1}\\le r_k\\). The solution does not address this possibility.\n\n3. **Claim of disjoint interiors.**  \n   The argument given:\n\n   > \u201cThe column intervals \\([\\pi_{k-1}+1,\\pi_{k}]\\) are pairwise disjoint \u2026 Likewise the row intervals \\([r_{k},\\,r_{k+1}-1]\\) are pairwise disjoint because the \\(r_{k}\\) are a permutation and we have appended \\(r_{n+1}=n+1\\). Hence two distinct rectangles cannot share a row *and* a column, so their interiors are disjoint.\u201d\n\n   **Critical Error:**  \n   The fact that \\((r_1,\\dots ,r_n)\\) is a permutation does **not** imply that the intervals \\([r_k, r_{k+1}-1]\\) are disjoint. A permutation is an unordered collection; the indices \\(k\\) are ordered, but the corresponding row numbers \\(r_k\\) can appear in any order. For example, with \\(n=3\\) one could have \\((r_1,r_2,r_3)=(3,1,2)\\). Then the intervals are \\([3, r_2-1]=[3,0]\\) (empty), \\([1, r_3-1]=[1,1]\\), and \\([2, r_4-1]=[2, n]\\). Clearly the intervals are not guaranteed to be disjoint, and they may even overlap or be empty. Consequently the rectangles \\(R_k\\) may intersect, violating the requirement that tiles be interior\u2011disjoint.\n\n   Because the construction of the rectangles relies on this false claim, the entire upper\u2011bound argument collapses. No valid tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles has been exhibited.\n\n4. **Subsequent steps (4\u20136).**  \n   These steps assume the correctness of the disjointness claim and of the partition of the board into the \\(R_k\\). Since the foundational claim is false, the reasoning in steps\u202f4,\u202f5, and\u202f6 is built on an invalid premise. Even though the statements themselves (e.g., \u201cthe uncovered square is on the boundary\u201d) would be true **if** the rectangles were correctly defined, they cannot be verified because the rectangles may not exist as described.\n\n*Because the error in step\u202f3 is a logical flaw that breaks the construction, Lemma\u202f2 does not provide a valid upper bound.*\n\n#### Final conclusion of the solution\n\nThe solution combines Lemma\u202f1 (valid) with Lemma\u202f2 (invalid) to claim that the minimum number of tiles equals \\(n=2025\\). Since Lemma\u202f2 fails, the claimed upper bound is unsupported, and the overall conclusion is not justified.\n\n**Overall assessment:** The solution contains a critical logical error in the construction of the tiling with \\(n\\) tiles (Lemma\u202f2, step\u202f3). Therefore the solution is invalid."
