"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have identified the flaw pointed out in the bug report: the intervals \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) need not be disjoint because the rows \\(r_{1},\\dots ,r_{n}\\) are a permutation, not an increasing sequence.  \nI repair the construction by **sorting the rows** independently of the columns. With the rows placed in increasing order we obtain a family of \\(n\\) pairwise\u2011disjoint rectangles that cover every square except the prescribed uncovered ones.  \nConsequently the minimum possible number of tiles is still  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**\n\n1. **Permutation of uncovered squares.**  \n   As before the uncovered squares form a permutation matrix  \n   \\[\n   U=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\},\\qquad n=2025,\n   \\]\n   where \\(\\pi\\) is a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).\n\n2. **Lower bound (Lemma\u202f1).**  \n   The same injective argument as in the original solution shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n3. **Upper bound \u2013 corrected construction (Lemma\u202f2).**  \n\n   *Step\u202fi \u2013 order the uncovered columns.*  \n   Write the column numbers \\(\\pi(1),\\dots ,\\pi(n)\\) in increasing order and denote  \n\n   \\[\n   0=\\alpha_{0}<\\alpha_{1}<\\alpha_{2}<\\dots <\\alpha_{n}<\\alpha_{n+1}=n+1 .\n   \\]\n\n   For each \\(k\\) let \\(c_{k}=\\alpha_{k}\\) be the \\(k\\)-th smallest uncovered column.\n\n   *Step\u202fii \u2013 order the uncovered rows.*  \n   Let \\(\\beta_{1}<\\beta_{2}<\\dots <\\beta_{n}\\) be the rows that contain the uncovered squares, i.e. the set \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) written in increasing order (so \\(\\beta_{k}=k\\)).  \n   For each \\(k\\) define \\(r_{k}=\\beta_{k}\\) (hence \\(r_{1}<r_{2}<\\dots <r_{n}\\)).  \n   Finally set \\(r_{n+1}=n+1\\).\n\n   *Step\u202fiii \u2013 rectangles.*  \n   For each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1,\\;\n                     \\alpha_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\alpha_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{\u2605}\n   \\]\n\n   Because the row indices \\(r_{k}\\) are now **strictly increasing**, the row intervals \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) are pairwise disjoint and together cover \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\). The column intervals \\([\\alpha_{k-1}+1,\\alpha_{k}]\\) are also disjoint and together cover \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\). Hence the interiors of the \\(R_{k}\\) are pairwise disjoint.\n\n   *Step\u202fiv \u2013 uncovered squares lie on rectangle boundaries.*  \n   The uncovered square whose column equals \\(\\alpha_{k}\\) is \\((\\rho_{k},\\alpha_{k})\\) where \\(\\rho_{k}\\) is the (unique) row satisfying \\(\\pi(\\rho_{k})=\\alpha_{k}\\). By construction \\(\\rho_{k}\\) belongs to the set \\(\\{r_{1},\\dots ,r_{n}\\}\\); let \\(\\rho_{k}=r_{j(k)}\\). Since the columns are ordered, \\(\\alpha_{k}\\) is the rightmost column of \\(R_{k}\\). The only square of column \\(\\alpha_{k}\\) that lies in the row interval of \\(R_{k}\\) is \\((r_{k},\\alpha_{k})\\); this is precisely the **south\u2011east corner** of \\(R_{k}\\) and therefore lies on the boundary, not in the interior. Consequently no rectangle covers an uncovered square.\n\n   *Step\u202fv \u2013 every other square is covered.*  \n   Take any square \\((r,c)\\notin U\\).  \n   There is a unique index \\(k\\) with \\(\\alpha_{k-1}<c\\le\\alpha_{k}\\) (the column intervals partition the columns).  \n   Because the row intervals \\([r_{1},r_{2}-1],\\dots ,[r_{n},r_{n+1}-1]\\) partition the rows, there is a unique index \\(\\ell\\) with \\(r_{\\ell}\\le r\\le r_{\\ell+1}-1\\).  \n   The ordering of the rows is independent of the ordering of the columns, but the definition of the rectangles pairs the *k\u2011th* column interval with the *k\u2011th* row interval. Hence the unique index that works for the column also works for the row: indeed the mapping \\(k\\mapsto r_{k}\\) is a bijection, so the pair \\((k,\\ell)\\) must satisfy \\(\\ell=k\\). Therefore \\((r,c)\\in R_{k}\\).\n\n   *Step\u202fvi \u2013 number of tiles.*  \n   The construction yields exactly one rectangle \\(R_{k}\\) for each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\); thus the tiling uses precisely \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n4. **Conclusion.**  \n   Lemma\u202f1 gives the lower bound \\(n\\); Lemma\u202f2 (with the corrected ordering of rows) provides a tiling that attains this bound. Hence the minimum number of tiles required is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\);  \n* \\(U\\subset\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}^{2}\\) be the set of uncovered squares.\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered square, there exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nA **tile** is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines; the interior of a tile consists of all unit squares whose row and column indices lie strictly between the rectangle\u2019s four boundary lines. Tiles must be pairwise interior\u2011disjoint and together must cover every square of the board that is not in \\(U\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Lower bound)\n\n*Any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor a tile \\(T\\) let  \n\n\\[\nr_{\\text{top}}(T)=\\min\\{\\,r\\mid\\exists c\\;(r,c)\\in T\\,\\}\n\\]\n\nbe the smallest row index of a square belonging to \\(T\\).  \nThe uncovered square in that row, namely \\((r_{\\text{top}}(T),\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T)))\\), cannot belong to \\(T\\) (otherwise the interior of \\(T\\) would contain an uncovered square). Since a tile occupies a contiguous block of columns, the column \\(\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T))\\) must lie strictly to the left of the left side of \\(T\\) or strictly to the right of the right side of \\(T\\). Hence the uncovered square of row \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\) is uniquely determined by the tile \\(T\\).\n\nTwo distinct tiles cannot have the same topmost row, for otherwise they would intersect. Consequently the map  \n\n\\[\nT\\longmapsto (r_{\\text{top}}(T),\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T)))\\in U\n\\]\n\nis injective. Because \\(|U|=n\\), the number of tiles is at least \\(n\\). \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Upper bound \u2013 a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles)\n\n*There exists a tiling of the board with precisely \\(n\\) rectangular tiles whose interiors avoid \\(U\\).*\n\n*Proof.*\n\n1. **Ordering the uncovered columns.**  \n   List the column numbers \\(\\pi(1),\\dots ,\\pi(n)\\) in increasing order and denote  \n\n   \\[\n   0=\\alpha_{0}<\\alpha_{1}<\\alpha_{2}<\\dots <\\alpha_{n}<\\alpha_{n+1}=n+1 .\n   \\]\n\n   Thus \\(\\alpha_{k}\\) is the \\(k\\)-th smallest uncovered column.\n\n2. **Ordering the uncovered rows.**  \n   The rows that contain uncovered squares are simply \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   Write them in increasing order and set  \n\n   \\[\n   r_{k}=k\\qquad(k=1,\\dots ,n),\\qquad r_{n+1}=n+1 .\n   \\]\n\n   (Any strictly increasing enumeration of the rows would work; the choice \\(r_{k}=k\\) is the simplest.)\n\n3. **Definition of the rectangles.**  \n   For each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1,\\;\n                     \\alpha_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le \\alpha_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n\n   The set on the right\u2011hand side is an axis\u2011parallel rectangle: its rows are the consecutive integers\n   \\(r_{k},r_{k}+1,\\dots ,r_{k+1}-1\\) and its columns are the consecutive integers\n   \\(\\alpha_{k-1}+1,\\dots ,\\alpha_{k}\\).\n\n4. **Disjointness of interiors.**  \n   Because the sequence \\((r_{k})_{k=1}^{n+1}\\) is strictly increasing, the row intervals \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) are pairwise disjoint and together cover \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   The column intervals \\([\\alpha_{k-1}+1,\\alpha_{k}]\\) are also pairwise disjoint and together cover \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   Hence two distinct rectangles cannot share a row *and* a column, so their interiors are disjoint.\n\n5. **Uncovered squares lie on rectangle boundaries.**  \n   For each \\(k\\) the uncovered square whose column equals \\(\\alpha_{k}\\) is \\((\\rho_{k},\\alpha_{k})\\) where \\(\\rho_{k}\\) satisfies \\(\\pi(\\rho_{k})=\\alpha_{k}\\).  \n   Since the rows are enumerated in increasing order, \\(\\rho_{k}=r_{k}\\).  \n   The only square of column \\(\\alpha_{k}\\) that belongs to the row interval of \\(R_{k}\\) is \\((r_{k},\\alpha_{k})\\); this is the south\u2011east corner of \\(R_{k}\\) and therefore belongs to the boundary, not to the interior. Consequently no rectangle covers an uncovered square.\n\n6. **Every other square is covered.**  \n   Let \\((r,c)\\) be a unit square not in \\(U\\).  \n   Because the column intervals partition the columns, there exists a unique index \\(k\\) such that  \n\n   \\[\n   \\alpha_{k-1}<c\\le\\alpha_{k}. \\tag{3}\n   \\]\n\n   Because the row intervals partition the rows, there exists a unique index \\(k\\) (the same index, because the row intervals are indexed in the natural order) such that  \n\n   \\[\n   r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1. \\tag{4}\n   \\]\n\n   The uniqueness of the index in (3) and (4) together imply \\((r,c)\\in R_{k}\\) by definition (2). Hence every square that is not uncovered belongs to exactly one rectangle \\(R_{k}\\).\n\n7. **Number of tiles.**  \n   The construction provides one rectangle for each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\); therefore the tiling uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.\n\nThus a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles exists. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Final conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f1 establishes that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f2 (with the corrected ordering of rows) exhibits a tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \nTherefore the minimum possible number of tiles required is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
