"**Final Verdict:** The solution is **invalid** because it contains Critical Errors that break the logical chain of the proof.\n\n**List of Findings**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f1, \u201cTwo distinct tiles cannot have the same topmost row, for otherwise they would intersect.\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 two tiles may share the same topmost row while occupying disjoint column intervals, so they need not intersect.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, Step\u202f5 (\u201cSince the rows are enumerated in increasing order,\u202f\u03c1\u2096\u202f=\u202fr\u2096.\u201d) and the subsequent use of the same index\u202fk\u202ffor both row and column partitions.\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the ordering of uncovered columns (the\u202f\u03b1\u2096) is unrelated to the ordering of uncovered rows (the\u202fr\u2096); there is no guarantee that the uncovered square in row\u202fr\u2096\u202flies in column\u202f\u03b1\u2096. Consequently the constructed rectangles may cover uncovered squares or leave squares uncovered.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, Step\u202f6 (\u201cBecause the row intervals are indexed in the natural order\u2026 the same index\u202fk\u202f\u2026\u201d) \n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the argument that the unique index\u202fk\u202ffrom the column partition coincides with the unique index\u202fk\u202ffrom the row partition is unjustified; the two partitions are independent and need not align.\n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n#### Preliminary definitions\n- The solution defines \\(n=2025\\) and the set of uncovered squares \\(U=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n  *Correct*: This follows directly from the condition that each row and each column contains exactly one uncovered square; such a set is precisely a permutation graph.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f1 (Lower bound)\n\n1. **Definition of \\(r_{\\text{top}}(T)\\).**  \n   *Correct*: The smallest row index of a square belonging to tile \\(T\\) is well\u2011defined.\n\n2. **Claim:** \u201cThe uncovered square in that row \u2026 cannot belong to \\(T\\) (otherwise the interior of \\(T\\) would contain an uncovered square).\u201d  \n   *Correct*: By definition an uncovered square must not be covered by any tile, so it cannot lie in the interior of \\(T\\).\n\n3. **Claim:** \u201cSince a tile occupies a contiguous block of columns, the column \\(\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T))\\) must lie strictly to the left of the left side of \\(T\\) or strictly to the right of the right side of \\(T\\).\u201d  \n   *Correct*: If the uncovered square is not inside the tile, its column must be outside the column interval of the tile.\n\n4. **Claim:** \u201cTwo distinct tiles cannot have the same topmost row, for otherwise they would intersect.\u201d  \n   *Critical Error*: Two tiles may have the same topmost row while being placed side\u2011by\u2011side in disjoint column intervals. Their interiors would then be disjoint, so the statement is false. Because this claim is used to assert that the map \\(T\\mapsto (r_{\\text{top}}(T),\\pi(r_{\\text{top}}(T)))\\) is injective, the injectivity argument collapses. Consequently the lower bound \u201cat least \\(n\\) tiles\u201d is not justified.\n\n   *Since this is a critical error, any subsequent reasoning that depends on Lemma\u202f1 is not guaranteed to hold. We therefore stop checking any conclusions that rely on the lower bound.*\n\n#### Lemma\u202f2 (Upper bound \u2013 construction)\n\nEven if we ignore the flawed lower bound, the construction itself is incorrect.\n\n1. **Step\u202f1 \u2013 Ordering the uncovered columns.**  \n   *Correct*: Defining \\(\\alpha_{1}<\\dots<\\alpha_{n}\\) as the sorted list of uncovered column indices is legitimate.\n\n2. **Step\u202f2 \u2013 Ordering the uncovered rows.**  \n   *Correct*: The rows are naturally \\(1,\\dots ,n\\); setting \\(r_{k}=k\\) is fine.\n\n3. **Step\u202f3 \u2013 Definition of rectangles \\(R_{k}\\).**  \n   *Correct as a definition*: The set described is indeed an axis\u2011parallel rectangle.\n\n4. **Step\u202f4 \u2013 Disjointness of interiors.**  \n   *Correct*: Because the row intervals \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) are disjoint and the column intervals \\([\\alpha_{k-1}+1,\\alpha_{k}]\\) are disjoint, any two distinct rectangles differ in at least one coordinate, so their interiors are disjoint.\n\n5. **Step\u202f5 \u2013 Claim \u201cSince the rows are enumerated in increasing order, \\(\\rho_{k}=r_{k}\\).\u201d**  \n   *Critical Error*: \\(\\rho_{k}\\) is defined by \\(\\pi(\\rho_{k})=\\alpha_{k}\\); it is the row whose uncovered square lies in column \\(\\alpha_{k}\\). There is no reason for this row to be \\(k\\). The permutation \\(\\pi\\) can map rows to columns in an arbitrary way, so the ordering of the columns \\(\\alpha_{k}\\) does **not** correspond to the natural ordering of the rows. Hence the equality \\(\\rho_{k}=r_{k}\\) is generally false.\n\n6. **Step\u202f5 \u2013 Consequence \u201cthe uncovered square \u2026 is the south\u2011east corner of \\(R_{k}\\) and therefore belongs to the boundary, not to the interior.\u201d**  \n   Because the previous equality is false, the uncovered square \\((\\rho_{k},\\alpha_{k})\\) need not lie on the boundary of \\(R_{k}\\); it may lie strictly inside \\(R_{k}\\) or outside it altogether. Thus the claim that no rectangle covers an uncovered square is unsupported.\n\n7. **Step\u202f6 \u2013 Claim \u201cthe same index\u202fk\u202fappears in (3) and (4)\u201d.**  \n   *Critical Error*: Equation (3) selects the unique \\(k\\) such that the column \\(c\\) lies in the interval \\((\\alpha_{k-1},\\alpha_{k}]\\). Equation (4) selects the unique \\(k\\) such that the row \\(r\\) lies in \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\). These two selections are independent; there is no justification that they yield the same \\(k\\). The argument assumes a coupling that does not exist, so the conclusion that every non\u2011uncovered square belongs to some \\(R_{k}\\) is invalid.\n\n8. **Step\u202f7 \u2013 Counting tiles.**  \n   *Correct*: The construction indeed creates exactly \\(n\\) rectangles, but because steps\u202f5\u20136 are flawed, these rectangles do **not** form a valid tiling that respects the uncovered squares.\n\nBecause the upper\u2011bound construction fails, the claim that a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles exists is unproved.\n\n#### Final conclusion of the solution\nThe solution combines a faulty lower bound (Lemma\u202f1) with an incorrect construction for the upper bound (Lemma\u202f2). Both lemmas contain critical logical errors, so the derived statement that the minimum number of tiles equals \\(2025\\) is not justified. Consequently the entire solution is invalid."
