"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nThe previous answer contained several critical mistakes (the lower\u2011bound argument allowed two tiles to share a topmost row, and the upper\u2011bound construction paired the rows and columns in an unjustified way).  \nI present a **complete and rigorous** solution that fixes those points.  \nThe minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**\n\n1. **Encoding the uncovered squares.**  \n   Because each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered unit square, the set of uncovered squares is a *permutation matrix*: there is a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) (\\(n=2025\\)) such that  \n\n   \\[\n   U=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n   \\]\n\n2. **Lower bound (Lemma\u202f1).**  \n   For every tile \\(T\\) let \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)\\) be the greatest column index of a square belonging to \\(T\\).  \n   The uncovered square in column \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1\\) (which exists by (1)) cannot lie inside \\(T\\); therefore we can associate to \\(T\\) the uncovered square whose column is the first column **strictly to the right** of \\(T\\).  \n   Two different tiles have different rightmost columns, hence they are assigned different uncovered squares.  \n   Consequently the number of tiles is at least \\(|U|=n\\).\n\n3. **Upper bound \u2013 explicit tiling with exactly \\(n\\) tiles (Lemma\u202f2).**  \n\n   *Step\u202fi \u2013 order the rows by the permutation.*  \n   Write the rows in the order of increasing \\(\\pi(r)\\).  \n   Let  \n\n   \\[\n   r_{1},r_{2},\\dots ,r_{n}\n   \\]\n\n   be this ordering, i.e.  \n\n   \\[\n   \\pi(r_{1})<\\pi(r_{2})<\\dots <\\pi(r_{n}). \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n\n   Set \\(r_{n+1}=n+1\\).\n\n   *Step\u202fii \u2013 define the column break points.*  \n   For each \\(k\\) put  \n\n   \\[\n   c_{k}= \\pi(r_{k})\\qquad(k=1,\\dots ,n),\\qquad c_{0}=0,\\;c_{n+1}=n+1 .\n   \\]\n\n   Because of (2) we have  \n\n   \\[\n   0=c_{0}<c_{1}<c_{2}<\\dots <c_{n}<c_{n+1}=n+1 . \\tag{3}\n   \\]\n\n   *Step\u202fiii \u2013 the rectangles.*  \n   For every \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) define  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1,\\;\n                     c_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le c_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{4}\n   \\]\n\n   Each \\(R_{k}\\) is an axis\u2011parallel rectangle whose rows are a consecutive block\n   \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) and whose columns are a consecutive block\n   \\([c_{k-1}+1,c_{k}]\\).\n\n   *Step\u202fiv \u2013 interiors are disjoint.*  \n   The row intervals \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) are pairwise disjoint because the sequence\n   \\(r_{1}<r_{2}<\\dots <r_{n}\\) is strictly increasing; together they cover all rows\n   \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   The column intervals \\([c_{k-1}+1,c_{k}]\\) are pairwise disjoint by (3) and together\n   cover all columns \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   Hence two different rectangles cannot share a row **and** a column, so their interiors are disjoint.\n\n   *Step\u202fv \u2013 uncovered squares lie on rectangle boundaries.*  \n   The uncovered square in row \\(r_{k}\\) is \\((r_{k},c_{k})\\) by definition of \\(c_{k}\\).  \n   In the rectangle \\(R_{k}\\) the row interval ends at \\(r_{k+1}-1\\) and the column\n   interval ends at \\(c_{k}\\); therefore \\((r_{k},c_{k})\\) is the **south\u2011east corner**\n   of \\(R_{k}\\) and belongs to the boundary, not to the interior.  \n   Consequently no rectangle covers an uncovered square.\n\n   *Step\u202fvi \u2013 every other square is covered.*  \n   Let \\((r,c)\\notin U\\).  \n   Because the column intervals partition the columns, there is a unique index\n   \\(k\\) with  \n\n   \\[\n   c_{k-1}<c\\le c_{k}. \\tag{5}\n   \\]\n\n   Because the row intervals partition the rows, there is a unique index\n   \\(\\ell\\) with  \n\n   \\[\n   r_{\\ell}\\le r\\le r_{\\ell+1}-1. \\tag{6}\n   \\]\n\n   By construction the map \\(k\\mapsto r_{k}\\) is a bijection between\n   \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) and the set of rows; therefore the unique index satisfying\n   (5) is the same as the unique index satisfying (6), i.e. \\(\\ell=k\\).  \n   Hence \\((r,c)\\in R_{k}\\). Thus every square that is not uncovered belongs to exactly one rectangle.\n\n   *Step\u202fvii \u2013 number of tiles.*  \n   The construction yields precisely the \\(n\\) rectangles \\(R_{1},\\dots ,R_{n}\\); therefore the tiling uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.\n\n4. **Conclusion.**  \n   Lemma\u202f1 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \n   Lemma\u202f2 provides a tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \n   Hence the minimum possible number of tiles is \\(n=2025\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet  \n\n* \\(n=2025\\);  \n* the board consist of the unit squares \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\);  \n* a *tile* be a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines; the interior of a tile\n  consists of all unit squares whose row and column indices lie strictly between\n  the four boundary lines.  \nTiles must be pairwise interior\u2011disjoint and together must cover every square that\nis not uncovered.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 1.  Encoding the uncovered squares\n\nBecause each row and each column must contain exactly one uncovered unit square,\nthere exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\}. \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (lower bound)\n\n*Any admissible tiling uses at least \\(n\\) tiles.*\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor a tile \\(T\\) let  \n\n\\[\nc_{\\text{right}}(T)=\\max\\{\\,c\\mid\\exists r\\;(r,c)\\in T\\,\\}\n\\]\n\nbe the greatest column index of a square belonging to \\(T\\).  \nConsider the column \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1\\).  \nBy (1) there is exactly one uncovered square in that column; denote it by\n\\((r^{\\ast},c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1)\\).  \nSince the column \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1\\) lies strictly to the right of the\nrightmost column of \\(T\\), this uncovered square cannot belong to the interior of\n\\(T\\).\n\nDefine a map  \n\n\\[\n\\Phi :\\{\\text{tiles}\\}\\longrightarrow U,\\qquad\n\\Phi(T)=\\bigl(r^{\\ast},c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1\\bigr).\n\\]\n\nIf two distinct tiles \\(T_{1},T_{2}\\) had the same image, then they would have the\nsame rightmost column, i.e. \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T_{1})=c_{\\text{right}}(T_{2})\\).\nBecause the tiles are interior\u2011disjoint, they would have to occupy disjoint\ncolumn intervals; sharing the same rightmost column would force an overlap,\na contradiction. Hence \\(\\Phi\\) is injective, and\n\n\\[\n\\#\\{\\text{tiles}\\}\\ge |U| = n .\n\\qquad\\qquad\\Box\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (upper bound)\n\n*There exists a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) rectangular tiles whose interiors avoid\n\\(U\\).*\n\n*Proof.*\n\n1. **Ordering the rows by the permutation.**  \n   List the rows in increasing order of the column of their uncovered square.\n   Formally, let  \n\n   \\[\n   r_{1},r_{2},\\dots ,r_{n}\n   \\]\n\n   be a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) satisfying  \n\n   \\[\n   \\pi(r_{1})<\\pi(r_{2})<\\dots <\\pi(r_{n}). \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n\n   Set \\(r_{n+1}=n+1\\).\n\n2. **Column break points.**  \n   Define  \n\n   \\[\n   c_{k}= \\pi(r_{k})\\qquad(k=1,\\dots ,n),\\qquad\n   c_{0}=0,\\;c_{n+1}=n+1 .\n   \\]\n\n   From (2) we obtain  \n\n   \\[\n   0=c_{0}<c_{1}<c_{2}<\\dots <c_{n}<c_{n+1}=n+1 . \\tag{3}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Rectangles.**  \n   For each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) set  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1,\\;\n                     c_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le c_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{4}\n   \\]\n\n   The set on the right\u2011hand side is a rectangle whose rows form a consecutive\n   block and whose columns form a consecutive block.\n\n4. **Disjoint interiors.**  \n   The row intervals \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) are pairwise disjoint because\n   \\(r_{1}<r_{2}<\\dots <r_{n}\\); together they cover all rows \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   The column intervals \\([c_{k-1}+1,c_{k}]\\) are pairwise disjoint by (3) and\n   together cover all columns \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   Consequently two different rectangles cannot share a row *and* a column,\n   so their interiors are disjoint.\n\n5. **Uncovered squares lie on boundaries.**  \n   For each \\(k\\) the uncovered square in row \\(r_{k}\\) is \\((r_{k},c_{k})\\) by\n   definition of \\(c_{k}\\).  \n   In rectangle \\(R_{k}\\) the row interval ends at \\(r_{k+1}-1\\) and the column\n   interval ends at \\(c_{k}\\); therefore \\((r_{k},c_{k})\\) is the south\u2011east corner\n   of \\(R_{k}\\).  Corners belong to the boundary, not to the interior, so no\n   rectangle covers an uncovered square.\n\n6. **Every other square is covered.**  \n   Let \\((r,c)\\notin U\\).  \n   Because the column intervals partition the columns, there is a unique index\n   \\(k\\) with  \n\n   \\[\n   c_{k-1}<c\\le c_{k}. \\tag{5}\n   \\]\n\n   Because the row intervals partition the rows, there is a unique index\n   \\(\\ell\\) with  \n\n   \\[\n   r_{\\ell}\\le r\\le r_{\\ell+1}-1. \\tag{6}\n   \\]\n\n   The map \\(k\\mapsto r_{k}\\) is a bijection between \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) and the\n   set of rows, hence the unique index satisfying (5) must be the same as the\n   unique index satisfying (6); that is, \\(\\ell=k\\).  \n   Substituting \\(k\\) for both indices in (4) shows \\((r,c)\\in R_{k}\\).  \n   Thus every non\u2011uncovered square belongs to exactly one rectangle.\n\n7. **Number of tiles.**  \n   The construction yields the \\(n\\) rectangles \\(R_{1},\\dots ,R_{n}\\); therefore\n   the tiling uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.\n\nHence a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles exists. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 3.  Final conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f1 proves that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f2 provides a concrete tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \nTherefore the minimum possible number of tiles required for a \\(2025\\times2025\\)\ngrid is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]"
