right of the\nrightmost column of \\(T\\), this uncovered square cannot belong to the interior of\n\\(T\\).\n\nDefine a map  \n\n\\[\n\\Phi :\\{\\text{tiles}\\}\\longrightarrow U,\\qquad\n\\Phi(T)=\\bigl(r^{\\ast},c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1\\bigr).\n\\]\n\nIf two distinct tiles \\(T_{1},T_{2}\\) had the same image, then they would have the\nsame rightmost column, i.e. \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T_{1})=c_{\\text{right}}(T_{2})\\).\nBecause the tiles are interior\u2011disjoint, they would have to occupy disjoint\ncolumn intervals; sharing the same rightmost column would force an overlap,\na contradiction. Hence \\(\\Phi\\) is injective, and\n\n\\[\n\\#\\{\\text{tiles}\\}\\ge |U| = n .\n\\qquad\\qquad\\Box\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (upper bound)\n\n*There exists a tiling with exactly \\(n\\) rectangular tiles whose interiors avoid\n\\(U\\).*\n\n*Proof.*\n\n1. **Ordering the rows by the permutation.**  \n   List the rows in increasing order of the column of their uncovered square.\n   Formally, let  \n\n   \\[\n   r_{1},r_{2},\\dots ,r_{n}\n   \\]\n\n   be a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) satisfying  \n\n   \\[\n   \\pi(r_{1})<\\pi(r_{2})<\\dots <\\pi(r_{n}). \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n\n   Set \\(r_{n+1}=n+1\\).\n\n2. **Column break points.**  \n   Define  \n\n   \\[\n   c_{k}= \\pi(r_{k})\\qquad(k=1,\\dots ,n),\\qquad\n   c_{0}=0,\\;c_{n+1}=n+1 .\n   \\]\n\n   From (2) we obtain  \n\n   \\[\n   0=c_{0}<c_{1}<c_{2}<\\dots <c_{n}<c_{n+1}=n+1 . \\tag{3}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Rectangles.**  \n   For each \\(k=1,\\dots ,n\\) set  \n\n   \\[\n   R_{k}= \\bigl\\{(r,c)\\mid r_{k}\\le r\\le r_{k+1}-1,\\;\n                     c_{k-1}+1\\le c\\le c_{k}\\bigr\\}. \\tag{4}\n   \\]\n\n   The set on the right\u2011hand side is a rectangle whose rows form a consecutive\n   block and whose columns form a consecutive block.\n\n4. **Disjoint interiors.**  \n   The row intervals \\([r_{k},r_{k+1}-1]\\) are pairwise disjoint because\n   \\(r_{1}<r_{2}<\\dots <r_{n}\\); together they cover all rows \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   The column intervals \\([c_{k-1}+1,c_{k}]\\) are pairwise disjoint by (3) and\n   together cover all columns \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\).  \n   Consequently two different rectangles cannot share a row *and* a column,\n   so their interiors are disjoint.\n\n5. **Uncovered squares lie on boundaries.**  \n   For each \\(k\\) the uncovered square in row \\(r_{k}\\) is \\((r_{k},c_{k})\\) by\n   definition of \\(c_{k}\\).  \n   In rectangle \\(R_{k}\\) the row interval ends at \\(r_{k+1}-1\\) and the column\n   interval ends at \\(c_{k}\\); therefore \\((r_{k},c_{k})\\) is the south\u2011east corner\n   of \\(R_{k}\\).  Corners belong to the boundary, not to the interior, so no\n   rectangle covers an uncovered square.\n\n6. **Every other square is covered.**  \n   Let \\((r,c)\\notin U\\).  \n   Because the column intervals partition the columns, there is a unique index\n   \\(k\\) with  \n\n   \\[\n   c_{k-1}<c\\le c_{k}. \\tag{5}\n   \\]\n\n   Because the row intervals partition the rows, there is a unique index\n   \\(\\ell\\) with  \n\n   \\[\n   r_{\\ell}\\le r\\le r_{\\ell+1}-1. \\tag{6}\n   \\]\n\n   The map \\(k\\mapsto r_{k}\\) is a bijection between \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) and the\n   set of rows, hence the unique index satisfying (5) must be the same as the\n   unique index satisfying (6); that is, \\(\\ell=k\\).  \n   Substituting \\(k\\) for both indices in (4) shows \\((r,c)\\in R_{k}\\).  \n   Thus every non\u2011uncovered square belongs to exactly one rectangle.\n\n7. **Number of tiles.**  \n   The construction yields the \\(n\\) rectangles \\(R_{1},\\dots ,R_{n}\\); therefore\n   the tiling uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.\n\nHence a tiling with \\(n\\) tiles exists. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 3.  Final conclusion\n\nLemma\u202f1 proves that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(n\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f2 provides a concrete tiling that uses exactly \\(n\\) tiles.  \nTherefore the minimum possible number of tiles required for a \\(2025\\times2025\\)\ngrid is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}.\n\\]\n\n\n### Verification Task Reminder ###\n\nYour task is to act as an IMO grader. Now, generate the **summary** and the **step-by-step verification log** for the solution above. In your log, justify each correct step and explain in detail any errors or justification gaps you find, as specified in the instructions above.\n\n"
