"**Final Verdict:** The solution is **invalid** because it contains several **Justification Gaps** that leave key steps unproved.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f1, definition of the map\u202f\\(\\Phi\\) and the claim that a tile cannot have its rightmost column equal to \\(n\\).\n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 the argument that the column \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1\\) always exists (i.e., \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)<n\\)) is not supplied.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, step\u202f6 (\u201cthe unique index satisfying (5) must be the same as the unique index satisfying (6) \u2026 \\(\\ell=k\\)\u201d).\n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 the equality \\(\\ell=k\\) is asserted without a rigorous proof; the reasoning that the bijection \\(k\\mapsto r_k\\) forces the two independently obtained indices to coincide is incorrect.\n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n---\n\n#### Preliminary definitions  \n\nThe solution introduces \\(n=2025\\) and the set of unit squares \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\).  \nThe definition of a *tile* as a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines and whose interior consists of all unit squares whose row and column indices lie strictly between the four boundary lines is clear and standard. No issue.\n\n---\n\n#### 1. Encoding the uncovered squares  \n\nThe claim that \u201cthere exists a permutation \\(\\pi\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\\(U=\\{(r,\\pi(r))\\mid r=1,\\dots ,n\\}\\)\u201d follows directly from the condition \u201ceach row and each column contains exactly one uncovered unit square\u201d. This is a correct bijective correspondence between rows and columns. No issue.\n\n---\n\n#### Lemma\u202f1 (lower bound)\n\n**Step 1 \u2013 Definition of \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)\\).**  \nCorrectly defined as the maximum column index of a square belonging to tile \\(T\\).\n\n**Step 2 \u2013 Consideration of column \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1\\).**  \nThe solution assumes this column always exists (i.e., \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)<n\\)).  \n*Justification Gap:* If a tile occupies the rightmost column of the board, then \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)=n\\) and the column \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1=n+1\\) is not part of the board, so the uncovered square \u201cin that column\u201d does not exist. The argument that such a tile cannot occur is not provided; it must be shown that any tile reaching column \\(n\\) would necessarily cover the unique uncovered square of column \\(n\\), contradicting the definition of uncovered squares. Since this justification is omitted, the injectivity claim rests on an unproved premise.\n\n**Step 3 \u2013 Definition of \\(\\Phi\\).**  \nGiven the (unproved) existence of the column \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1\\), the map \\(\\Phi\\) is well\u2011defined.\n\n**Step 4 \u2013 Injectivity argument.**  \nThe reasoning \u201cif two distinct tiles had the same image, then they would have the same rightmost column \u2026 they would have to occupy disjoint column intervals; sharing the same rightmost column would force an overlap\u201d is correct **provided** the map is well\u2011defined. No further issues.\n\n**Conclusion of Lemma\u202f1.**  \nBecause of the earlier gap, the lower bound \\(\\#\\{\\text{tiles}\\}\\ge n\\) is not rigorously established.\n\n---\n\n#### Lemma\u202f2 (upper bound)\n\n**Step 1 \u2013 Ordering rows by the permutation.**  \nChoosing a permutation \\(r_1,\\dots ,r_n\\) such that \\(\\pi(r_1)<\\dots <\\pi(r_n)\\) is always possible (simply sort the rows according to the column of their uncovered square). Correct.\n\n**Step 2 \u2013 Definition of break points \\(c_k\\).**  \nSetting \\(c_k=\\pi(r_k)\\) and \\(c_0=0,\\;c_{n+1}=n+1\\) yields the strict inequalities (3). Correct.\n\n**Step 3 \u2013 Definition of rectangles \\(R_k\\).**  \nThe formula (4) correctly describes a rectangle whose row interval is \\([r_k,\\,r_{k+1}-1]\\) and column interval is \\([c_{k-1}+1,\\,c_k]\\). No issue.\n\n**Step 4 \u2013 Disjoint interiors.**  \nSince the row intervals are disjoint and the column intervals are disjoint, any two rectangles cannot share both a row and a column, hence interiors are disjoint. Correct.\n\n**Step 5 \u2013 Uncovered squares lie on boundaries.**  \nFor each \\(k\\), the uncovered square \\((r_k,c_k)\\) is indeed the south\u2011east corner of \\(R_k\\); corners belong to the boundary, not the interior. Correct.\n\n**Step 6 \u2013 Claim that every other square belongs to exactly one rectangle.**  \n\n- The solution first finds the unique \\(k\\) satisfying (5) (column partition) and the unique \\(\\ell\\) satisfying (6) (row partition). This part is fine.\n- Then it asserts: \u201cThe map \\(k\\mapsto r_k\\) is a bijection \u2026 the unique index satisfying (5) must be the same as the unique index satisfying (6); that is, \\(\\ell=k\\).\u201d  \n\n  **Justification Gap:** The bijectivity of \\(k\\mapsto r_k\\) only tells us that each row appears exactly once among the \\(r_k\\). It does **not** imply that the index determined by the column interval coincides with the index determined by the row interval. For a given square \\((r,c)\\) with \\(c\\) in the \\(k\\)-th column block, the row \\(r\\) could belong to any row block \\(\\ell\\); there is no inherent reason that \\(\\ell=k\\). The argument would need to use the ordering property (2) to show that if \\(c\\) lies between \\(c_{k-1}+1\\) and \\(c_k\\), then the row of any square with that column must lie between \\(r_k\\) and \\(r_{k+1}-1\\). This requires a careful monotonicity argument that is omitted. Consequently, the statement that \\(\\ell=k\\) is unproved, and the conclusion that every non\u2011uncovered square lies in some \\(R_k\\) is not justified.\n\n**Step 7 \u2013 Number of tiles.**  \nAssuming the previous step were valid, the count of \\(n\\) rectangles follows. As the covering claim is not established, this step cannot be confirmed.\n\n**Conclusion of Lemma\u202f2.**  \nBecause of the gap in step\u202f6, the construction does not rigorously prove that all non\u2011uncovered squares are covered, so the existence of an \\(n\\)-tile tiling remains unverified.\n\n---\n\n#### Final conclusion  \n\nThe solution correctly identifies that the problem reduces to a permutation and that at least \\(n\\) tiles are needed, but both Lemma\u202f1 and Lemma\u202f2 contain unproved assertions (the existence of the column \\(c_{\\text{right}}(T)+1\\) and the equality \\(\\ell=k\\) in the covering argument). These justification gaps prevent the proof from being complete. Hence the solution is **invalid**."
