"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have proved that the minimum possible number of tiles is **2025**.  \n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n* Let the uncovered squares be \\(U=\\{(r_i,c_i)\\mid i=1,\\dots ,2025\\}\\); the condition \u201cexactly one uncovered square in each row and each column\u2019\u2019 forces the pairs \\((r_i,c_i)\\) to form a permutation of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,2025\\}\\).  \n* **Lemma 1.** If a rectangle contains squares from two different rows, then it must also contain the uncovered square of at least one of those rows, which is forbidden. Consequently every admissible rectangle is contained in a single row. (The same argument with rows and columns interchanged shows that a rectangle cannot contain squares from two different columns either.)  \n* From Lemma\u202f1 each tile can cover squares of at most one row, so at least one tile is needed for every row. Hence any tiling uses **\u2265\u202f2025** tiles.  \n* A construction attaining this bound: in row \\(r\\) leave the uncovered square \\((r,c_r)\\) empty and cover the remaining \\(2024\\) squares of the row by a single horizontal \\(1\\times2024\\) rectangle. The 2025 rectangles are pairwise disjoint and satisfy the required condition.  \n* Therefore the lower bound and the construction coincide, and the minimum number of tiles is exactly \\(2025\\).\n\n---\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet the grid consist of the unit squares \\((i,j)\\) with \\(1\\le i,j\\le n\\) where \\(n=2025\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 2.1  The set of uncovered squares\n\nDenote by \\(U\\) the set of squares that are **not** covered by any tile.  \nThe hypothesis says that each row contains exactly one element of \\(U\\) and each column contains exactly one element of \\(U\\).  \nHence there exist permutations \\(\\sigma\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n\\tag{1}\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 2.2  A geometric restriction on admissible rectangles  \n\n\\[\n\\textbf{Lemma 1.}\\qquad\n\\text{No admissible rectangle can contain squares from two distinct rows.}\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \nAssume a rectangle \\(R\\) contains squares from rows \\(r_1\\neq r_2\\).  \nBecause \\(R\\) is axis\u2011parallel, its projection on the column axis is an interval\n\\([a,b]\\) of column indices.  \nRow \\(r_1\\) has the unique uncovered square \\((r_1,\\sigma(r_1))\\).  \nIf \\(\\sigma(r_1)\\in[a,b]\\) then \\((r_1,\\sigma(r_1))\\in R\\), contradicting the definition of \\(U\\).  \nThus \\(\\sigma(r_1)\\notin[a,b]\\). The same argument applied to row \\(r_2\\) yields\n\\(\\sigma(r_2)\\notin[a,b]\\).\n\nSince the columns \\(\\sigma(r_1)\\) and \\(\\sigma(r_2)\\) are distinct (the map \\(\\sigma\\) is a permutation), the interval \\([a,b]\\) cannot avoid **both** of them unless it is empty, which is impossible for a rectangle containing at least one square. Hence our assumption is false, and \\(R\\) cannot involve two different rows. \u220e\n\nInterchanging the roles of rows and columns gives the analogous statement:\n\n\\[\n\\textbf{Corollary 1.}\\qquad\n\\text{No admissible rectangle can contain squares from two distinct columns.}\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 2.3  Lower bound on the number of tiles  \n\nFrom Lemma\u202f1 each tile lies entirely inside a single row.  \nRow \\(i\\) contains \\(n-1\\) squares that must be covered (all except \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\)).  \nConsequently at least one tile is required for each row, i.e.\n\n\\[\n\\text{number of tiles}\\;\\ge\\; n = 2025 .\n\\tag{2}\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 2.4  Construction attaining the bound  \n\nFor every row \\(i\\) place a single horizontal rectangle covering all squares of that row except the uncovered one:\n\n\\[\nT_i = \\{(i,j)\\mid j\\neq \\sigma(i)\\},\\qquad i=1,\\dots ,n .\n\\]\n\nEach \\(T_i\\) is a \\(1\\times (n-1)\\) rectangle; the family \\(\\{T_i\\}_{i=1}^{n}\\) consists of \\(n\\) pairwise disjoint tiles, covers every square not in \\(U\\), and leaves exactly the squares of \\(U\\) uncovered.  \n\nThus a tiling with \\(2025\\) tiles exists.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 2.5  Conclusion  \n\nThe lower bound (2) and the explicit construction show that the minimum possible number of tiles equals \\(2025\\).\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2025}\n\\]"
