        "content": "**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have not been able to produce a completely rigorous proof that the minimum possible number of tiles is\u202f2025.  \nWhat I can establish rigorously are the following points  \n\n* The uncovered squares must form a permutation matrix: there is exactly one uncovered square in each row and each column, and the set of uncovered squares is \\(\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,2025\\}\\) for some permutation \\(\\sigma\\) of \\(\\{1,\\dots ,2025\\}\\).  \n* A tiling that uses exactly 2025 tiles exists: in each row \\(i\\) place a single horizontal \\(1\\times2024\\) rectangle covering all squares of that row except the uncovered one \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\).  \n\nThus the number 2025 is an **upper bound** for the minimum.  \nThe main difficulty that remains is to prove a matching **lower bound**: to show that no tiling with fewer than 2025 tiles can satisfy the condition. I was unable to close this gap.\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Structure of uncovered squares.**  \n   * Show that the condition \u201cexactly one uncovered square in each row and each column\u2019\u2019 forces the uncovered squares to be a permutation matrix (Lemma\u202f1).  \n\n2. **Construction attaining 2025 tiles.**  \n   * For each row \\(i\\) place a single horizontal rectangle of size \\(1\\times(2025-1)\\) covering all squares of that row except the uncovered one.  \n   * Verify that the 2025 rectangles are disjoint and meet the required condition, giving an explicit tiling with 2025 tiles.  \n\n3. **Attempt at a lower\u2011bound argument (partial).**  \n   * Observe that any rectangle that occupies \\(k\\) distinct rows must avoid the \\(k\\) distinct uncovered columns belonging to those rows; consequently its width is at most \\(2025-k\\) and its area at most \\(k(2025-k)\\).  \n   * From this we obtain a crude bound on the total number of tiles, but the bound is far from the desired value 2025, and a sharper argument has not been found.  \n\nThe rigorous parts are Lemma\u202f1 and the explicit construction; the lower\u2011bound part remains incomplete.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet \\(n=2025\\).  Index the unit squares of the grid by ordered pairs \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 2.1  The uncovered squares form a permutation matrix  \n\nDenote by \\(U\\) the set of squares that are **not** covered by any tile.  \nBy hypothesis each row contains exactly one element of \\(U\\) and each column contains exactly one element of \\(U\\).  \n\nHence there exists a bijection \\(\\sigma:\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\to\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{U=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}} \\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nIn other words, the uncovered squares are precisely the 1\u2019s of a permutation matrix.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 2.2  A tiling with \\(n\\) tiles  \n\nFor each row \\(i\\) define the set  \n\n\\[\nT_i=\\{(i,j)\\mid j\\neq\\sigma(i)\\}.\n\\]\n\n\\(T_i\\) consists of all squares of row \\(i\\) except the uncovered square \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\); it is a rectangle of dimensions \\(1\\times (n-1)\\).  \n\nThe family \\(\\{T_i\\}_{i=1}^{n}\\) has the following properties:\n\n* The rectangles are pairwise disjoint, because they lie in distinct rows.  \n* Their union is exactly the complement of \\(U\\); therefore every square that is not in \\(U\\) is covered by precisely one rectangle.  \n* Each row contains exactly one uncovered square, and each column contains exactly one uncovered square, as required.\n\nThus a tiling with **\\(n=2025\\) tiles** exists.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 2.3  Observations towards a lower bound (partial)\n\nLet a tile \\(R\\) occupy a set of rows \\(S\\subseteq\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) with \\(|S|=k\\).  \nBecause of (1), row \\(r\\in S\\) has its unique uncovered square in column \\(\\sigma(r)\\).  \nSince a tile may not contain any uncovered square, the column interval of \\(R\\) must avoid every column \\(\\sigma(r)\\) with \\(r\\in S\\).  \nConsequently the set of admissible columns for \\(R\\) is a subset of  \n\n\\[\n\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\setminus\\{\\sigma(r)\\mid r\\in S\\},\n\\]\n\nwhich has size \\(n-k\\).  Hence the width of \\(R\\) is at most \\(n-k\\), and its area satisfies  \n\n\\[\n|R|\\le k\\,(n-k). \\tag{2}\n\\]\n\nSumming (2) over all tiles gives an inequality for the total number \\(m\\) of tiles:\n\n\\[\nn^{2}-n=\\sum_{j=1}^{m}|R_j|\\le\\sum_{j=1}^{m}k_j\\,(n-k_j),\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(k_j\\) is the number of rows occupied by the \\(j\\)-th tile.  \nThe right\u2011hand side is maximised when each \\(k_j\\) is as close as possible to \\(n/2\\); the maximal possible value of a single term \\(k\\,(n-k)\\) is \\(\\lfloor n^{2}/4\\rfloor\\).  Therefore\n\n\\[\nm\\ge\\frac{n^{2}-n}{\\lfloor n^{2}/4\\rfloor}\n      =\\frac{n^{2}-n}{\\lfloor n^{2}/4\\rfloor}\n      >4\\qquad\\text{for }n=2025.\n\\]\n\nThis yields only the very weak bound \\(m\\ge5\\).  A stronger argument that forces \\(m\\ge n\\) has not been found.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### 2.4  Current status  \n\n*We have proved*  \n\n* the uncovered squares must be a permutation matrix (Lemma\u202f1);  \n* a tiling with exactly \\(2025\\) tiles exists (construction in \u00a72.2).  \n\n*What remains open* is a rigorous proof that no tiling with fewer than \\(2025\\) tiles can satisfy the condition.  The simple area\u2011based estimate (2) is far from sufficient, and a more delicate combinatorial argument is required.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n**Conclusion**\n\nThe problem\u2019s answer is known to be at most \\(2025\\) (by the explicit construction).  A matching lower bound has not been established in the present work; consequently the exact minimum remains unproved."
