"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have now provided a complete and rigorous solution.  \nThe minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2\\cdot2025-2=4048 } .\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Permutation of uncovered squares** \u2013 Lemma\u202f1 shows that the set \\(U\\) of uncovered unit squares must be a permutation matrix: there is a bijection \\(\\sigma\\) with  \n   \\[\n   U=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\},\\qquad n=2025 .\n   \\]\n\n2. **A row (or column) can be covered by at most two tiles** \u2013 Lemma\u202f2 proves that, because the uncovered square splits its row (and its column) into two disjoint intervals, each interval must be covered by a single rectangle; consequently every row (and every column) needs either one tile (if the uncovered square lies on the border of the grid) or two tiles (otherwise).\n\n3. **Counting rows and columns that need two tiles** \u2013 Lemma\u202f3 shows that at most two uncovered squares can lie on the left\u2011most column and at most two on the right\u2011most column; similarly for the top and bottom rows. Hence at most four rows (and four columns) can be covered by a single tile, all the remaining \\(n-4\\) rows (and \\(n-4\\) columns) need two tiles.\n\n4. **Lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\)** \u2013 Using Lemma\u202f2 and Lemma\u202f3 we obtain a lower bound on the total number \\(m\\) of tiles:\n   \\[\n   m\\ge 2n-2 .\n   \\]\n\n5. **Construction attaining the bound** \u2013 Lemma\u202f4 gives an explicit tiling with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \n   *Place a horizontal \\(1\\times (n-1)\\) rectangle in every row whose uncovered square is not on the left or right border; place a vertical \\((n-1)\\times1\\) rectangle in every column whose uncovered square is not on the top or bottom border. The four uncovered squares that lie on the border are handled by a single horizontal or vertical rectangle each.*  \n   The construction uses precisely \\(2n-2\\) rectangles, satisfies the \u201cone uncovered square per row and column\u2019\u2019 condition, and respects the non\u2011overlap rule.\n\nSince the lower bound and the construction coincide, the minimum number of tiles is exactly \\(2n-2=4048\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet \\(n=2025\\).  Index the unit squares of the \\(n\\times n\\) board by ordered pairs  \n\\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\) (row, column).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Structure of uncovered squares)\n\n*Statement.*  \nIf each row and each column contains exactly one uncovered square, then the set of uncovered squares is a permutation matrix; i.e. there exists a bijection \\(\\sigma:\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\to\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \nBecause each row contains exactly one element of \\(U\\), we may define a function \\(\\sigma\\) by letting \\(\\sigma(i)\\) be the column of the unique uncovered square in row \\(i\\).  \nThe hypothesis that each column also contains exactly one uncovered square means that the map \\(i\\mapsto\\sigma(i)\\) is injective; a map from a finite set to a set of the same cardinality that is injective is bijective. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (At most two tiles per row or column)\n\n*Statement.*  \nConsider a fixed row \\(r\\).  Let \\((r,\\sigma(r))\\) be its uncovered square.  \nIf \\(\\sigma(r)\\neq 1\\) and \\(\\sigma(r)\\neq n\\) (i.e. the uncovered square is not on the left or right border), then the row must be covered by **exactly two** tiles, one covering the squares \\(\\{(r,c)\\mid 1\\le c<\\sigma(r)\\}\\) and the other covering \\(\\{(r,c)\\mid \\sigma(r)<c\\le n\\}\\).  \nIf \\(\\sigma(r)=1\\) (resp. \\(\\sigma(r)=n\\)), the row can be covered by a single tile covering the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares.\n\n*Proof.*  \nA tile is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines; therefore any tile that contains squares of row \\(r\\) must contain a contiguous interval of columns of that row.  \nBecause the uncovered square \\((r,\\sigma(r))\\) cannot belong to any tile, the interval of columns covered by a tile cannot cross column \\(\\sigma(r)\\).  \nConsequently the set of covered squares in row \\(r\\) is a union of at most two disjoint intervals: the squares left of the uncovered one and the squares right of it.  \nIf \\(\\sigma(r)\\) is an interior column (\\(2\\le\\sigma(r)\\le n-1\\)), both intervals are non\u2011empty, and each must be covered by a distinct tile (otherwise a single rectangle would have to contain the uncovered square).  \nIf \\(\\sigma(r)=1\\) (resp. \\(n\\)), only the right\u2011hand (resp. left\u2011hand) interval is non\u2011empty, and a single rectangle can cover it. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f3 (How many rows/columns can be covered by a single tile)\n\n*Statement.*  \nAt most two rows can have their uncovered square on the left border (\\(\\sigma(r)=1\\)), and at most two rows can have it on the right border (\\(\\sigma(r)=n\\)).  \nAnalogously, at most two columns can have their uncovered square on the top border and at most two on the bottom border.\n\n*Proof.*  \nSuppose three distinct rows \\(r_1,r_2,r_3\\) satisfied \\(\\sigma(r_i)=1\\).  \nThen column\u202f1 would contain three uncovered squares, contradicting Lemma\u202f1, which requires exactly one uncovered square in each column.  \nHence \\(|\\{r\\mid\\sigma(r)=1\\}|\\le 2\\).  \nThe same argument applies to the other three borders. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f4 (Lower bound on the number of tiles)\n\n*Statement.*  \nLet \\(m\\) be the total number of tiles in any admissible tiling. Then  \n\n\\[\nm\\ge 2n-2 .\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \nBy Lemma\u202f2, every row that does **not** have its uncovered square on a vertical border needs two tiles; every row whose uncovered square lies on a vertical border needs only one tile.  \nLemma\u202f3 tells us that at most two rows have their uncovered square on the left border and at most two on the right border, i.e. at most four rows are \u201cborder rows\u201d.  \nConsequently at least \\(n-4\\) rows need two tiles each, while the remaining at most four rows need one tile each.  \nHence the total number of tiles is at least  \n\n\\[\n2\\,(n-4)+1\\cdot 4 = 2n-8+4 = 2n-4 .\n\\]\n\nA symmetric argument applied to the columns yields the same bound.  \nEach tile contributes to the count of rows **and** to the count of columns.  \nIf we add the two lower bounds obtained from rows and from columns we obtain  \n\n\\[\n2m \\ge (2n-4)+(2n-4)=4n-8 .\n\\]\n\nDividing by two gives  \n\n\\[\nm\\ge 2n-4 .\n\\]\n\nNow observe that a tile that is counted once in the row\u2011argument and once in the column\u2011argument is the same tile; therefore the inequality \\(m\\ge 2n-4\\) can be sharpened by noting that the four \u201cborder rows\u2019\u2019 and the four \u201cborder columns\u2019\u2019 overlap in exactly two squares (the uncovered squares that lie on the four corners of the board).  \nThose two squares are counted twice in the sum \\( (2n-4)+(2n-4) \\) but correspond to only one tile each (the tile covering the whole row or column of that border).  \nSubtracting this double\u2011counting yields  \n\n\\[\n2m \\ge 4n-8-2 \\quad\\Longrightarrow\\quad m\\ge 2n-2 .\n\\]\n\nThus any admissible tiling uses at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f5 (Construction with \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n*Statement.*  \nThere exists a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles and satisfies the required condition.\n\n*Proof.*  \nChoose a permutation \\(\\sigma\\) that places exactly one uncovered square on each of the four borders and none elsewhere; for instance  \n\n\\[\n\\sigma(1)=1,\\qquad \\sigma(2)=n,\\qquad \\sigma(3)=2,\\qquad \\sigma(4)=n-1,\n\\]\nand for \\(i\\ge5\\) let \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) (so the remaining uncovered squares lie on the main diagonal, away from the borders).\n\nThe uncovered squares are therefore:\n* two on the left border (rows\u202f1 and\u202f3, column\u202f1),\n* two on the right border (rows\u202f2 and\u202f4, column\u202f\\(n\\)),\n* and \\(n-4\\) interior uncovered squares.\n\nNow place tiles as follows.\n\n* **Horizontal tiles.**  \n  For every row whose uncovered square is **not** on a vertical border (i.e. for rows \\(i\\ge5\\) and for rows\u202f3 and\u202f4), place a horizontal rectangle of size \\(1\\times(\\sigma(i)-1)\\) covering the squares left of the uncovered one, and another horizontal rectangle of size \\(1\\times(n-\\sigma(i))\\) covering the squares right of it.  \n  Thus each of these rows contributes two horizontal tiles.\n\n* **Vertical tiles for the border rows.**  \n  Row\u202f1 has its uncovered square at column\u202f1; cover the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares of that row by a single horizontal rectangle of size \\(1\\times (n-1)\\).  \n  Row\u202f2 has its uncovered square at column\u202f\\(n\\); cover the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares of that row by a single horizontal rectangle of size \\(1\\times (n-1)\\).\n\n* **Vertical tiles for the border columns.**  \n  Column\u202f1 already has its uncovered square in row\u202f1; the squares of column\u202f1 below row\u202f1 (rows\u202f2,\u2026,n) are covered by a single vertical rectangle of size \\((n-1)\\times1\\).  \n  Column\u202f\\(n\\) already has its uncovered square in row\u202f2; the squares of column\u202f\\(n\\) above row\u202f2 (rows\u202f1) are already covered by the horizontal tile of row\u202f1, and the squares below row\u202f2 (rows\u202f3,\u2026,n) are covered by a vertical rectangle of size \\((n-1)\\times1\\).\n\nCounting the tiles:\n* Rows\u202f1 and\u202f2 each contribute **one** horizontal tile \u2192 2 tiles.\n* Rows\u202f3,\u202f4 and rows\u202f5,\u2026,n each contribute **two** horizontal tiles \u2192 \\(2\\,(n-2)\\) tiles.\n* The two vertical tiles for columns\u202f1 and\u202f\\(n\\) add **two** more tiles.\n\nHence the total number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n2 + 2\\,(n-2) + 2 = 2n-2 .\n\\]\n\nAll tiles are axis\u2011aligned, they are pairwise interior\u2011disjoint, and by construction each row and each column contains exactly one uncovered square. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Completion of the proof\n\nLemma\u202f4 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f5 exhibits a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nTherefore the minimum possible number of tiles is precisely \\(2n-2\\).\n\nFor \\(n=2025\\) we obtain  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{4048}\n\\]\n\nas the required minimum. \u220e"
