"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains **Critical Errors** (in Lemma\u202f4 and Lemma\u202f5) that break the logical chain, so the answer is **invalid**.\n\n---\n\n### List of Findings\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f4, first paragraph \u2013 \u201cConsequently at least \\(n-4\\) rows need two tiles each, while the remaining at most four rows need one tile each. Hence the total number of tiles is at least \\(2\\,(n-4)+1\\cdot 4 = 2n-4\\).\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the deduction that the total number of tiles equals the sum of the numbers of tiles required per row is false; a single tile can serve two different rows (if it is vertical) or two different columns (if it is horizontal). The argument ignores this overlap and therefore under\u2011estimates the possible reduction, making the bound \\(2n-4\\) unjustified.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f4, second half \u2013 \u201cEach tile contributes to the count of rows **and** to the count of columns\u2026 Subtracting this double\u2011counting yields \\(2m \\ge 4n-8-2\\) \u2026 \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\).\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the \u201cdouble\u2011counting\u201d correction is not rigorously justified. The argument assumes that exactly two tiles are double\u2011counted and that all other tiles are counted once in each of the row\u2011 and column\u2011bounds, which is not guaranteed. No proof is given that the configuration of border rows and columns forces this precise accounting, so the derived inequality \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\) is unsupported.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f5, description of the construction \u2013 \u201cFor every row whose uncovered square is **not** on a vertical border (i.e. for rows \\(i\\ge5\\) and for rows\u202f3 and\u202f4), place a horizontal rectangle \u2026 Thus each of these rows contributes two horizontal tiles.\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 rows\u202f3 and\u202f4 have their uncovered squares on the **right** and **left** borders respectively (according to the chosen permutation), yet the proof treats them as interior rows and places two horizontal tiles. This would force a tile to cover the uncovered square, violating the problem condition. Moreover, the construction does not guarantee that the vertical tiles for columns\u202f1 and\u202f\\(n\\) do not intersect the horizontal tiles already placed, contradicting the requirement that tiles be interior\u2011disjoint.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f5, counting of tiles \u2013 \u201cRows\u202f3,\u202f4 and rows\u202f5,\u2026,n each contribute **two** horizontal tiles \u2192 \\(2\\,(n-2)\\) tiles.\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 because the previous point shows the placement for rows\u202f3 and\u202f4 is invalid, the tile count is based on an impossible configuration. Consequently the claimed total of \\(2n-2\\) tiles is not realized by a valid tiling.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Preliminary Setup\nThe solution defines \\(n=2025\\) and indexes squares by \\((r,c)\\). This is correct and needs no comment.\n\n---\n\n### Lemma\u202f1 \u2013 \u201cStructure of uncovered squares\u201d\n\n**Step:** Shows that the set of uncovered squares must be a permutation matrix.\n\n**Verification:**  \n- Each row contains exactly one uncovered square \u21d2 defines a function \\(\\sigma\\).  \n- Each column also contains exactly one uncovered square \u21d2 \\(\\sigma\\) is injective.  \n- Finite set of size \\(n\\) \u21d2 injective \u21d2 bijective.  \n\n**Conclusion:** The reasoning is complete and correct. No issue.\n\n---\n\n### Lemma\u202f2 \u2013 \u201cAt most two tiles per row or column\u201d\n\n**Step:** Argues that in any row the covered squares form at most two intervals, hence at most two tiles.\n\n**Verification:**  \n- A tile intersecting a given row must occupy a contiguous block of columns (true for axis\u2011aligned rectangles).  \n- The uncovered square blocks any interval from crossing its column.  \n- Therefore the covered set in that row is a union of at most two disjoint intervals.  \n- If the uncovered square is interior, both intervals are non\u2011empty, requiring two distinct tiles; if on a border, only one interval is non\u2011empty, allowing a single tile.  \n\n**Conclusion:** The argument is rigorous and correct.\n\n---\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 \u2013 \u201cHow many rows/columns can be covered by a single tile\u201d\n\n**Step:** Claims at most two rows can have their uncovered square in column\u202f1 (left border), and similarly for column\u202f\\(n\\).\n\n**Verification:**  \n- If three rows had uncovered squares in column\u202f1, column\u202f1 would contain three uncovered squares, contradicting Lemma\u202f1 (which requires exactly one per column).  \n- Hence at most two rows can have \\(\\sigma(r)=1\\). Same for \\(\\sigma(r)=n\\).  \n\n**Conclusion:** The reasoning is sound.\n\n---\n\n### Lemma\u202f4 \u2013 \u201cLower bound on the number of tiles\u201d\n\n#### Part\u202f1: Row\u2011based counting\n\n**Step:**  \n- Uses Lemma\u202f2: interior rows need two tiles, border rows need one.  \n- Lemma\u202f3 limits border rows to at most four, so at least \\(n-4\\) rows need two tiles.  \n- Concludes total tiles \\(\\ge 2(n-4)+4 = 2n-4\\).\n\n**Issue (Critical Error):**  \nThe deduction treats the number of tiles required per **row** as if each tile is counted exclusively for that row. This ignores that a **vertical** tile can simultaneously serve two (or more) rows, and a **horizontal** tile can simultaneously serve two (or more) columns. Consequently, the sum of \u201ctiles needed per row\u2019\u2019 is only an **upper bound** on the number of tiles, not a lower bound. The argument therefore does **not** establish that any tiling must contain at least \\(2n-4\\) tiles. The step is logically invalid.\n\n**Effect:** Because this step is invalid, any later bound that builds on it (including the final \\(2n-2\\) bound) is unsupported unless independently justified.\n\n#### Part\u202f2: Column\u2011based counting and combination\n\n**Step:**  \n- Repeats the same argument for columns, obtaining another lower bound \\(2n-4\\).  \n- Adds the two bounds to get \\(2m \\ge 4n-8\\) and then divides by two to obtain \\(m \\ge 2n-4\\).  \n- Claims a \u201cdouble\u2011counting\u201d correction of 2 tiles, leading to \\(m \\ge 2n-2\\).\n\n**Issue (Critical Error):**  \n1. Adding the two row\u2011 and column\u2011bounds presumes that each tile is counted once in the row\u2011bound and once in the column\u2011bound, which is not justified. Some tiles (e.g., a horizontal tile) are counted in the row\u2011bound but **not** in the column\u2011bound, while a vertical tile is counted in the column\u2011bound but not in the row\u2011bound. The equality \\(2m = (\\text{row bound})+(\\text{column bound})\\) is therefore false in general.  \n2. The \u201cdouble\u2011counting\u201d correction assumes exactly two tiles are over\u2011counted and that all other tiles are counted exactly once in each bound. No argument is provided that the configuration of border rows/columns forces this precise accounting. Without a rigorous combinatorial accounting, the inequality \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\) is unfounded.\n\n**Effect:** The claimed lower bound \\(2n-2\\) rests on an unjustified manipulation of inequalities; the lemma is invalid.\n\n---\n\n### Lemma\u202f5 \u2013 \u201cConstruction with \\(2n-2\\) tiles\u201d\n\n#### Choice of permutation \\(\\sigma\\)\n\n**Step:** Defines \\(\\sigma(1)=1,\\ \\sigma(2)=n,\\ \\sigma(3)=2,\\ \\sigma(4)=n-1,\\ \\sigma(i)=i\\) for \\(i\\ge5\\).\n\n**Verification:**  \n- This indeed places uncovered squares at (1,1), (2,n), (3,2), (4,n\u20111), and (i,i) for \\(i\\ge5\\).  \n- Thus there are two uncovered squares on the left border (rows\u202f1 and\u202f3) and two on the right border (rows\u202f2 and\u202f4).  \n\n**Issue:** None in the definition itself.\n\n#### Placement of horizontal tiles\n\n**Step:** Claims that for rows whose uncovered square is **not** on a vertical border (i.e. rows \\(i\\ge5\\) **and** rows\u202f3 and\u202f4) we place two horizontal tiles per row.\n\n**Critical Error:**  \n- Row\u202f3 has its uncovered square at column\u202f2, which **is** on a vertical border? Actually column\u202f2 is not a border; the vertical borders are columns\u202f1 and\u202f\\(n\\). So row\u202f3 is interior, okay.  \n- Row\u202f4 has its uncovered square at column\u202f\\(n-1\\), also interior. The statement \u201crows\u202f3 and\u202f4\u201d being included is acceptable.  \n- However, later the construction says \u201cRow\u202f1 \u2026 single horizontal rectangle \u2026 Row\u202f2 \u2026 single horizontal rectangle \u2026\u201d. That part is fine.\n\nThe real problem appears later with the **vertical tiles**.\n\n#### Placement of vertical tiles for border columns\n\n**Step:**  \n- Column\u202f1: uncovered square at (1,1); cover squares (2,\u2026,n,1) with a vertical rectangle of size \\((n-1)\\times1\\).  \n- Column\u202f\\(n\\): uncovered square at (2,n); cover squares below row\u202f2 with a vertical rectangle of size \\((n-1)\\times1\\).\n\n**Critical Error:**  \n- The vertical rectangle in column\u202f1 occupies squares \\((2,1), (3,1),\\dots,(n,1)\\).  \n- But many of these squares have already been covered by the **horizontal tiles** placed in rows\u202f2,\u2026,n (for interior rows we placed two horizontal tiles covering the left side **up to** column \\(\\sigma(i)-1\\)). For rows \\(i\\ge5\\), the left horizontal tile covers columns \\(1\\) through \\(\\sigma(i)-1 = i-1\\). Since \\(i\\ge5\\), column\u202f1 is included in that left horizontal tile. Thus the vertical tile in column\u202f1 would intersect those horizontal tiles, violating the condition that tiles be interior\u2011disjoint (each unit square may be covered by at most one tile). The solution never addresses this conflict.\n\n- Similarly, the vertical tile in column\u202f\\(n\\) overlaps the right horizontal tiles of rows \\(i\\ge5\\) (which cover columns \\(\\sigma(i)+1\\) through \\(n\\)). Hence the construction is not a valid tiling.\n\n#### Counting tiles\n\nBecause the placement described is impossible (tiles intersect), the counting of \\(2n-2\\) tiles is based on a non\u2011existent configuration.\n\n**Conclusion:** Lemma\u202f5 does **not** provide a valid construction; the claimed tiling cannot exist as described.\n\n---\n\n### Overall Assessment\n\nThe proof\u2019s lower\u2011bound argument (Lemma\u202f4) misapplies row\u2011 and column\u2011wise counting and contains an unjustified correction, leading to a **critical logical flaw**. The purported extremal construction (Lemma\u202f5) fails to respect the non\u2011overlap condition, constituting another **critical error**. Since the central lemmas are invalid, the final answer \\(4048\\) is not established. Consequently, the solution is **incorrect**."
