rted.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f5, description of the construction \u2013 \u201cFor every row whose uncovered square is **not** on a vertical border (i.e. for rows \\(i\\ge5\\) and for rows\u202f3 and\u202f4), place a horizontal rectangle \u2026 Thus each of these rows contributes two horizontal tiles.\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 rows\u202f3 and\u202f4 have their uncovered squares on the **right** and **left** borders respectively (according to the chosen permutation), yet the proof treats them as interior rows and places two horizontal tiles. This would force a tile to cover the uncovered square, violating the problem condition. Moreover, the construction does not guarantee that the vertical tiles for columns\u202f1 and\u202f\\(n\\) do not intersect the horizontal tiles already placed, contradicting the requirement that tiles be interior\u2011disjoint.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f5, counting of tiles \u2013 \u201cRows\u202f3,\u202f4 and rows\u202f5,\u2026,n each contribute **two** horizontal tiles \u2192 \\(2\\,(n-2)\\) tiles.\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 because the previous point shows the placement for rows\u202f3 and\u202f4 is invalid, the tile count is based on an impossible configuration. Consequently the claimed total of \\(2n-2\\) tiles is not realized by a valid tiling.\n\n---\n\n##"
