"**Final Verdict:** The solution is essentially correct, but it contains a few **Justification Gaps** where the arguments are not fully rigorous.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, *Claim\u202f1*: \u201cNo tile that appears in a covering of any square whose sum is smaller than \\(s(i)\\) can contain a square of \\(L_i\\).\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 the proof that an earlier tile cannot intersect \\(L_i\\) is hand\u2011wavy; it relies on an informal \u201crectangle cannot contain two uncovered squares\u201d argument without a detailed case analysis.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, *Claim\u202f2*: \u201cAnalogously, no tile used for earlier squares can contain a square of \\(U_i\\).\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 the same level of rigor as in Claim\u202f1 is missing; the claim is asserted by symmetry without a formal proof.\n\nAll other steps are valid and follow logically from the stated lemmas.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Preliminary Setup\n- The solution defines \\(n=2025\\) and indexes unit squares by \\((r,c)\\). This is a standard and correct way to model the grid. \u2705\n\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Structure of the uncovered squares)\n- **Statement** correctly identifies that the set of uncovered squares must form a permutation matrix.\n- **Proof**:  \n  - For each row \\(i\\) define \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered square.  \n  - Since each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, the map \\(i\\mapsto\\sigma(i)\\) is injective.  \n  - An injective map between two finite sets of equal size is bijective.  \n  This argument is complete and rigorous. \u2705\n\n### Lemma\u202f2 (A universal lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))\n\n#### Ordering of uncovered squares\n- The definition \\(s(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\) and the choice of the minimal sum \\(s(i_{0})\\) are clear.  \n- The observation that minimality forces \\(i_{0}=1\\) or \\(\\sigma(i_{0})=1\\) is correct: if both were \\(>1\\) then \\((i_{0}-1,\\sigma(i_{0})-1)\\) would have a smaller sum, contradicting minimality. \u2705\n\n#### First uncovered square\n- The claim that the whole row \\(i_{0}\\) (except the uncovered cell) can be covered by a single horizontal tile, and similarly for the column, is valid because a rectangle may span the entire row (or column) without intersecting any other uncovered square. \u2705\n\n#### Definition of \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\)\n- The sets are correctly defined as the cells left of the uncovered cell in its row and above it in its column.  \n- The statement \u201cBoth sets are non\u2011empty because \\(s(i)>s(i_{0})\\) implies \\(i>1\\) and \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\)\u201d is accurate: if either \\(i=1\\) or \\(\\sigma(i)=1\\) the sum could not exceed the minimal sum unless the other coordinate were larger, which would contradict minimality of \\(s(i_{0})\\). \u2705\n\n#### Claim\u202f1 (No earlier tile can contain a square of \\(L_i\\))\n- **What the solution says:**  \n  \u201cIf a tile covering a square of \\(L_i\\) also covered a square of an earlier uncovered row\u2011column pair, that tile would have to extend both to the right of column \\(\\sigma(j)\\) and to the left of column \\(\\sigma(i)\\), which is impossible because a rectangle cannot contain two uncovered squares.\u201d\n- **Why this is a justification gap:**  \n  The argument sketches the idea but does not rigorously rule out all configurations. A complete proof would need to consider:\n  1. The shape of a rectangle that contains a cell of \\(L_i\\) (it must lie entirely in row \\(i\\)).  \n  2. Show that any earlier uncovered square \\((j,\\sigma(j))\\) with \\(j+\\sigma(j)<i+\\sigma(i)\\) lies either strictly above row \\(i\\) or strictly to the right of column \\(\\sigma(i)\\), so a rectangle confined to row \\(i\\) cannot also contain that earlier square.  \n  The solution\u2019s wording \u201cextend both to the right \u2026 and to the left \u2026\u201d is informal and does not explicitly handle the case where the earlier square is in the same row but a different column, etc. Hence the reasoning is not fully rigorous. **(Justification Gap)**\n\n- **Assumption for subsequent steps:** We accept Claim\u202f1 as true for the remainder of the verification.\n\n#### Claim\u202f2 (Analogous statement for \\(U_i\\))\n- The solution states the claim follows by symmetry, but does not provide the detailed argument analogous to Claim\u202f1. The same level of rigor is missing, constituting another **Justification Gap**.  \n- **Assumption:** Accept Claim\u202f2 as true.\n\n#### Consequence of the two claims\n- Given the assumed truth of Claims\u202f1 and\u202f2, the solution correctly deduces that each of the non\u2011empty sets \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\) must be covered by *new* tiles, and that a single tile cannot cover both a cell of \\(L_i\\) and a cell of \\(U_i\\).  \n  - The argument that a rectangle covering a cell of \\(L_i\\) lies entirely in row \\(i\\) while a rectangle covering a cell of \\(U_i\\) lies entirely in column \\(\\sigma(i)\\) is correct; their intersection would be the uncovered cell, which is forbidden. \u2705\n- Therefore each later uncovered square forces at least one new horizontal tile and at least one new vertical tile. \u2705\n\n#### Counting argument\n- The first uncovered square contributes at most one horizontal and one vertical tile.  \n- The remaining \\(n-1\\) squares each contribute at least one new horizontal and one new vertical tile, all distinct from previously counted tiles.  \n- Hence the total number of horizontal tiles \\(\\ge n-1\\) and vertical tiles \\(\\ge n-1\\).  \n- Adding gives \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\). This counting is sound provided the previous claims hold. \u2705\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n#### Choice of permutation\n- Selecting \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) (the main diagonal) is a valid permutation. \u2705\n\n#### Definition of rectangles \\(H_i\\) and \\(V_i\\)\n- For each \\(i\\ge2\\), \\(H_i\\) is the set of cells \\((i,c)\\) with \\(1\\le c\\le i-1\\); this is a horizontal \\(1\\times(i-1)\\) rectangle.  \n- \\(V_i\\) is the set of cells \\((r,i)\\) with \\(1\\le r\\le i-1\\); this is a vertical \\((i-1)\\times1\\) rectangle.  \n- No rectangle is defined for \\(i=1\\) because the sets would be empty. All definitions are clear. \u2705\n\n#### Disjointness proof\n- The three cases (horizontal\u2013horizontal, vertical\u2013vertical, horizontal\u2013vertical) are examined.  \n  - Horizontal\u2013horizontal: different rows \u21d2 disjoint. \u2705  \n  - Vertical\u2013vertical: different columns \u21d2 disjoint. \u2705  \n  - Horizontal\u2013vertical: potential intersection at \\((i,j)\\). The solution correctly analyses the two sub\u2011cases \\(j<i\\) and \\(j>i\\) and shows the intersection is empty in both. This is a complete and rigorous argument. \u2705\n\n#### Coverage argument\n- Every non\u2011diagonal cell either lies left of the diagonal in its row (hence belongs to some \\(H_i\\)) or above the diagonal in its column (hence belongs to some \\(V_j\\)). This partition covers all off\u2011diagonal cells exactly once. \u2705\n\n#### Counting tiles\n- Two rectangles for each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) gives \\(2(n-1)=2n-2\\) tiles. \u2705\n\n### Completion of the proof\n- Lemma\u202f2 provides a lower bound \\(2n-2\\).  \n- Lemma\u202f3 provides a construction attaining this bound.  \n- Therefore the minimum number of tiles is \\(2n-2 = 4048\\) for \\(n=2025\\). \u2705\n\n### Overall Assessment\nAll major steps are logically sound. The only shortcomings are the informal justifications in Lemma\u202f2\u2019s Claims\u202f1 and\u202f2; they are plausible but not fully rigorous as written. No critical logical errors are present, and the final answer follows correctly from the lemmas. Hence the solution is **valid modulo the noted justification gaps**."
