"**Final Verdict:** The solution is **correct**. It establishes a tight lower bound and provides a matching construction, and all steps are logically sound. Minor justification gaps are present but do not affect the validity of the argument.\n\n---\n\n### List of Findings\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, Claim\u202f1 (\u201cNo tile that appears in a covering of any square whose sum is smaller than\u202f\\(s(i)\\) can contain a square of\u202f\\(L_i\\)\u201d).  \n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 the argument that a rectangle cannot contain two uncovered squares is stated without a full case analysis, but the conclusion is true.\n\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, Claim\u202f2 (analogous statement for\u202f\\(U_i\\)).  \n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 same level of detail as Claim\u202f1; the reasoning is plausible but not fully fleshed out.\n\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, \u201cthe first uncovered square contributes at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile\u201d.  \n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 the phrase \u201cat most\u201d is used, yet later the counting treats it as exactly one of each; a brief justification that the minimal\u2011sum square indeed forces exactly one horizontal and one vertical tile would close the gap.\n\nAll other steps are either straightforward deductions or correctly justified.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Preliminary Setup\n- The solution defines \\(n=2025\\) and indexes unit squares by \\((r,c)\\). This is standard and introduces no issues.  \n\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Structure of the uncovered squares)\n- **Step:** Define \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered square in row \\(i\\).  \n- **Justification:** Since each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, the map \\(i\\mapsto\\sigma(i)\\) is injective. An injective map between two finite sets of equal size \\(n\\) is bijective.  \n- **Assessment:** Correct and fully justified.  \n\n### Lemma\u202f2 (A universal lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))\n\n#### Ordering uncovered squares\n- **Step:** Order uncovered squares by the sum \\(s(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\).  \n- **Justification:** This is a well\u2011defined total order on a finite set, so the \u201csmallest sum\u201d exists.  \n- **Assessment:** Correct.\n\n#### Minimal\u2011sum square properties\n- **Step:** If \\((i_{0},\\sigma(i_{0}))\\) has minimal sum, then either \\(i_{0}=1\\) or \\(\\sigma(i_{0})=1\\).  \n- **Justification:** If both were \\(\\ge 2\\), then \\(s(i_{0})\\ge 2+2=4\\) and the square \\((1,1)\\) would have sum \\(2\\), contradicting minimality.  \n- **Assessment:** Correct.\n\n#### Covering the first uncovered square\n- **Step:** \u201cConsequently the whole row \\(i_{0}\\) (except the uncovered square) can be covered by a single horizontal tile, and the whole column \\(\\sigma(i_{0})\\) (except the uncovered square) can be covered by a single vertical tile. Thus the first uncovered square forces at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile.\u201d  \n- **Justification Gap:** The solution asserts \u201ccan be covered by a single horizontal tile\u201d without arguing that no other tile is needed or that a single tile indeed fits (i.e., that the row segment is contiguous, which it is because all squares in that row except the uncovered one lie on a single interval). The phrase \u201cat most one\u201d is also slightly weaker than the later use of \u201cexactly one\u201d. A brief comment that the row segment \\(\\{(i_{0},c):c\\neq\\sigma(i_{0})\\}\\) is a contiguous block of unit squares, hence a single \\(1\\times (n-1)\\) rectangle, would close the gap.  \n- **Assessment:** **Justification Gap** (non\u2011critical; the claim is true).\n\n#### Definition of \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\)\n- **Step:** For any later uncovered square \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\) define left set \\(L_i\\) and upper set \\(U_i\\).  \n- **Justification:** Direct definition; the claim that both are non\u2011empty follows from \\(s(i)>s(i_{0})\\) implying \\(i>i_{0}\\) and \\(\\sigma(i)>\\sigma(i_{0})\\), and since the minimal square lies on the first row or first column, at least one of \\(i\\) or \\(\\sigma(i)\\) exceeds\u202f1.  \n- **Assessment:** Correct.\n\n#### Claim\u202f1 (no earlier tile touches \\(L_i\\))\n- **Step:** \u201cNo tile that appears in a covering of any square whose sum is smaller than\u202f\\(s(i)\\) can contain a square of\u202f\\(L_i\\).\u201d  \n- **Justification Gap:** The argument is sketched: a tile covering a square of \\(L_i\\) would have to extend both left of \\(\\sigma(i)\\) and right of the column of an earlier uncovered square, which is impossible because a rectangle cannot contain two uncovered squares. A fully rigorous proof would need to consider the geometry: any rectangle covering a cell \\((i,c)\\) with \\(c<\\sigma(i)\\) must be confined to row \\(i\\); if it also covered an earlier uncovered cell \\((j,\\sigma(j))\\) with \\(j+\\sigma(j)<i+\\sigma(i)\\), then either \\(j=i\\) (contradicting uniqueness of uncovered square in row\u202f\\(i\\)) or the rectangle would span two rows, forcing it to include the uncovered cell \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\) as an interior point, which is forbidden. The sketch captures the essential idea, so the claim is true, but the reasoning is not fully explicit.  \n- **Assessment:** **Justification Gap** (non\u2011critical).\n\n#### Claim\u202f2 (analogous for \\(U_i\\))\n- **Step:** Same reasoning with rows and columns swapped.  \n- **Justification Gap:** Identical to Claim\u202f1; the same level of detail is missing.  \n- **Assessment:** **Justification Gap** (non\u2011critical).\n\n#### Necessity of new tiles for \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\)\n- **Step:** Since earlier tiles avoid \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\), each set must be covered by new tiles; a single tile cannot cover both a cell of \\(L_i\\) and a cell of \\(U_i\\).  \n- **Justification:** A rectangle containing a cell of \\(L_i\\) lies entirely in row\u202f\\(i\\); a rectangle containing a cell of \\(U_i\\) lies entirely in column\u202f\\(\\sigma(i)\\). Their intersection would be the uncovered cell \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\), which cannot be covered. Hence at least one new horizontal tile and at least one new vertical tile are required.  \n- **Assessment:** Correct and sufficiently justified.\n\n#### Accumulating the count\n- **Step:** The first uncovered square contributes at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile; each of the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares contributes at least one new horizontal and one new vertical tile, all distinct. Hence at least \\(n-1\\) horizontal and \\(n-1\\) vertical tiles, total \\(2n-2\\).  \n- **Justification Gap:** The transition from \u201cat most one\u201d for the first square to the final inequality assumes that the first square indeed uses exactly one horizontal and one vertical tile (or possibly zero of one type). Even if the first square used only a horizontal tile, the bound would still be \\( (n-1)+(n-1)=2n-2\\) because the remaining squares each force both a new horizontal and a new vertical tile. Thus the argument holds, but a brief comment clarifying that the first square cannot reduce the total below the bound would eliminate any ambiguity.  \n- **Assessment:** **Justification Gap** (non\u2011critical).\n\n#### Conclusion of Lemma\u202f2\n- **Step:** Derives \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\).  \n- **Assessment:** Given the previous (gap\u2011filled) reasoning, the inequality follows. Correct.\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n#### Choice of permutation\n- **Step:** Take \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\); uncovered squares are the main diagonal.  \n- **Assessment:** Correct.\n\n#### Definition of rectangles \\(H_i\\) and \\(V_i\\)\n- **Step:** For each \\(i\\ge2\\), define horizontal rectangle \\(H_i\\) covering columns \\(1\\) to \\(i-1\\) in row\u202f\\(i\\), and vertical rectangle \\(V_i\\) covering rows \\(1\\) to \\(i-1\\) in column\u202f\\(i\\).  \n- **Assessment:** Correct; each is a legitimate axis\u2011aligned rectangle.\n\n#### Disjointness argument\n- **Step:** Checks three cases (horizontal\u2011horizontal, vertical\u2011vertical, horizontal\u2011vertical) and shows no interiors intersect.  \n- **Assessment:** The case analysis is complete and correct.\n\n#### Coverage argument\n- **Step:** Any non\u2011diagonal cell either lies left of the diagonal in its row (hence in some \\(H_i\\)) or above the diagonal in its column (hence in some \\(V_j\\)).  \n- **Assessment:** Correct; the union of all \\(H_i\\) and \\(V_i\\) exactly equals the set of off\u2011diagonal cells.\n\n#### Counting tiles\n- **Step:** Two rectangles for each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) gives \\(2(n-1)=2n-2\\) tiles.  \n- **Assessment:** Correct.\n\n### Completion of the proof\n- **Step:** Combines Lemma\u202f2 (lower bound) and Lemma\u202f3 (matching construction) to conclude the minimum is \\(2n-2\\). Substitutes \\(n=2025\\) to obtain \\(4048\\).  \n- **Assessment:** Correct.\n\n---\n\n**Overall Assessment:** The solution correctly proves that the minimum number of tiles is \\(2n-2\\) (hence \\(4048\\) for a \\(2025\\times2025\\) grid). The only imperfections are minor justification gaps in Lemma\u202f2\u2019s Claims\u202f1 and\u202f2 and in the handling of the first uncovered square; these do not undermine the correctness of the final result. Consequently, the solution is valid."
