        "content": "\n======================================================================\n### Problem ###\n\n*** Problem Statement ***\n\nConsider a $2025\\times2025$ grid of unit squares. Matilda wishes to place on the grid some rectangular tiles, possibly of difference sizes, such that each side of every tile lies on a grid line and every unit square is covered by at most one tile.\n\nDetermine the minimum number of tiles Matilda needs to place so that each row and each column of the grid has exactly one unit square that is not covered by any tile.\n\n======================================================================\n### Solution ###\n\n**\n\nLet \\(n=2025\\).  Index the unit squares of the board by ordered pairs  \n\\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\) (row, column).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Structure of the uncovered squares)\n\n*Statement.*  \nIf each row and each column contains exactly one uncovered unit square, then the set of uncovered squares is a permutation matrix; i.e. there exists a bijection \\(\\sigma:\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\to\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) let \\(\\sigma(i)\\) be the column of the unique uncovered square in that row.  \nBecause each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, the map \\(i\\mapsto\\sigma(i)\\) is injective; an injective map between two finite sets of the same cardinality is bijective. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (A universal lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))\n\n*Statement.*  \nIn any admissible tiling the total number \\(m\\) of tiles satisfies  \n\n\\[\nm\\ge 2n-2 .\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \nOrder the uncovered squares by the value  \n\n\\[\ns(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\qquad (i=1,\\dots ,n).\n\\]\n\nLet \\((i_{0},\\sigma(i_{0}))\\) be the square with the smallest sum \\(s(i_{0})\\).  \nBecause \\(s(i_{0})\\) is minimal, either \\(i_{0}=1\\) (top row) or \\(\\sigma(i_{0})=1\\) (leftmost column).  \nConsequently the whole row \\(i_{0}\\) (except the uncovered square) can be covered by a single horizontal tile, and the whole column \\(\\sigma(i_{0})\\) (except the uncovered square) can be covered by a single vertical tile.  \nThus the first uncovered square forces at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile.\n\nNow consider any other uncovered square \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\) with \\(s(i)>s(i_{0})\\).  \nDefine  \n\n\\[\nL_i=\\{(i,c)\\mid 1\\le c<\\sigma(i)\\},\\qquad\nU_i=\\{(r,\\sigma(i))\\mid 1\\le r<i\\}.\n\\]\n\n\\(L_i\\) consists of the squares to the **left** of the uncovered one in its row; \\(U_i\\) consists of the squares **above** it in its column.  \nBoth sets are non\u2011empty because \\(s(i)>s(i_{0})\\) implies \\(i>1\\) and \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\).\n\n*Claim 1.*  No tile that appears in a covering of any square whose sum is **smaller** than \\(s(i)\\) can contain a square of \\(L_i\\).\n\nIndeed, any such earlier square \\((j,\\sigma(j))\\) satisfies \\(j+\\sigma(j)<i+\\sigma(i)\\).  \nIf a tile covering a square of \\(L_i\\) also covered a square of an earlier uncovered row\u2011column pair, that tile would have to extend both to the right of column \\(\\sigma(j)\\) and to the left of column \\(\\sigma(i)\\), which is impossible because a rectangle cannot contain two uncovered squares.  Hence the squares of \\(L_i\\) are untouched by all tiles already introduced.\n\n*Claim 2.*  Analogously, no tile used for earlier squares can contain a square of \\(U_i\\).\n\nThe same reasoning with rows and columns interchanged proves the claim.\n\nBecause the tiles placed so far avoid \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\), each of these two non\u2011empty sets must be covered by **new** tiles.  \nMoreover a single tile cannot cover both a square of \\(L_i\\) and a square of \\(U_i\\): any rectangle containing a point of \\(L_i\\) lies entirely in row \\(i\\), while any rectangle containing a point of \\(U_i\\) lies entirely in column \\(\\sigma(i)\\); the intersection of such a row\u2011rectangle and a column\u2011rectangle is the uncovered square \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\), which is forbidden.  \nHence at least one new horizontal tile (covering part of \\(L_i\\)) **and** at least one new vertical tile (covering part of \\(U_i\\)) are required.\n\nApplying the argument to the uncovered squares in increasing order of \\(s(i)\\) we obtain:\n\n* the first square contributes at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile;\n* each of the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares contributes **at least** one new horizontal tile and **at least** one new vertical tile, distinct from all previously counted tiles.\n\nTherefore the total number of horizontal tiles is at least \\(n-1\\) and the total number of vertical tiles is at least \\(n-1\\).  \nSince every tile is either horizontal or vertical, the total number of tiles satisfies  \n\n\\[\nm\\ge (n-1)+(n-1)=2n-2 .\n\\qquad\\blacksquare\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n*Statement.*  \nThere exists a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles and fulfills the requirement that each row and each column contains precisely one uncovered square.\n\n*Proof (explicit construction).*\n\nChoose the permutation \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) for all \\(i\\); thus the uncovered squares are the diagonal squares  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,i)\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n\\]\n\nFor every index \\(i\\) with \\(2\\le i\\le n\\) place two rectangles:\n\n* a **horizontal** rectangle  \n\n  \\[\n  H_i=\\{(i,c)\\mid 1\\le c\\le i-1\\},\n  \\]\n  which has size \\(1\\times (i-1)\\);\n\n* a **vertical** rectangle  \n\n  \\[\n  V_i=\\{(r,i)\\mid 1\\le r\\le i-1\\},\n  \\]\n  which has size \\((i-1)\\times 1\\).\n\nNo rectangle is placed for \\(i=1\\) because both \\(H_1\\) and \\(V_1\\) would be empty.\n\n*Disjointness.*  \nConsider any two distinct rectangles among the family \\(\\{H_i,V_i\\mid 2\\le i\\le n\\}\\).\n\n* If both are horizontal, say \\(H_i\\) and \\(H_j\\) with \\(i\\neq j\\), they lie in different rows, hence are disjoint.\n* If both are vertical, say \\(V_i\\) and \\(V_j\\) with \\(i\\neq j\\), they lie in different columns, hence are disjoint.\n* If one is horizontal \\(H_i\\) and the other vertical \\(V_j\\) with \\(i\\neq j\\), their possible intersection would be the single cell \\((i,j)\\).  \n  \u2013 If \\(j<i\\) then \\(V_j\\) occupies rows \\(1,\\dots ,j-1\\), which does **not** include row \\(i\\); thus the intersection is empty.  \n  \u2013 If \\(j>i\\) then \\(H_i\\) occupies columns \\(1,\\dots ,i-1\\), which does **not** include column \\(j\\); again the intersection is empty.  \n\nHence all rectangles are pairwise interior\u2011disjoint.\n\n*Coverage.*  \nEvery unit square that is not on the main diagonal belongs either to some \\(H_i\\) (if it lies left of the diagonal in its row) or to some \\(V_j\\) (if it lies above the diagonal in its column).  Consequently all non\u2011diagonal squares are covered, and the only uncovered squares are precisely the diagonal ones, one per row and one per column.\n\n*Counting.*  \nWe have created two rectangles for each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\); therefore the total number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n2\\,(n-1)=2n-2 .\n\\qquad\\blacksquare\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Completion of the proof\n\nLemma\u202f2 establishes that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f3 exhibits a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nHence the lower bound is attainable and is therefore optimal.\n\nFor the concrete size \\(n=2025\\) we obtain  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{4048}\n\\]\n\nas the minimum possible number of tiles. \u220e\n\n\n### Verification Task Reminder ###\n\nYour task is to act as an IMO grader. Now, generate the **summary** and the **step-by-step verification log** for the solution above. In your log, justify each correct step and explain in detail any errors or justification gaps you find, as specified in the instructions above.\n\n"
    }
