"**Final Verdict:** The solution is **correct** \u2013 it establishes a valid lower bound of \\(2n-2\\) tiles and provides an explicit construction attaining this bound, thereby proving that the minimum number of tiles for a \\(2025\\times2025\\) grid is \\(4048\\).\n\n---\n\n### List of Findings\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, *Claim\u202f1* \u2013 \u201cNo tile that appears in a covering of any square whose sum is smaller than \\(s(i)\\) can contain a square of \\(L_i\\).\u201d\n  * **Issue:** **Justification Gap** \u2013 the argument that a rectangle cannot contain two uncovered squares is stated informally; a rigorous proof that such a tile would necessarily intersect an earlier uncovered square is omitted.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, *Claim\u202f2* \u2013 analogous statement for the set \\(U_i\\).\n  * **Issue:** **Justification Gap** \u2013 same level of detail as Claim\u202f1 is missing.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, \u201cthe first uncovered square forces at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile.\u201d\n  * **Issue:** **Justification Gap** \u2013 the phrase \u201cat most one\u201d is not fully justified; one must argue that a single horizontal (resp. vertical) tile can indeed cover the whole remaining part of that row (resp. column) without overlapping any other tile.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f3, verification that the rectangles \\(H_i\\) and \\(V_j\\) are pairwise interior\u2011disjoint.\n  * **Issue:** **Justification Gap** \u2013 the case analysis for the intersection of a horizontal and a vertical rectangle is correct but could be made more explicit (e.g., by stating the exact ranges of rows and columns each rectangle occupies).\n\nAll other steps are logically sound and correctly justified.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Preliminary Setup\n- The solution defines \\(n=2025\\) and indexes unit squares by \\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\).  \n  **Correct.** This is the standard way to refer to rows and columns.\n\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Structure of the uncovered squares)\n- **Statement** correctly identifies that the set of uncovered squares must be a permutation matrix.  \n- **Proof**: defines \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered square in row \\(i\\); injectivity follows from the column condition, and finiteness gives bijectivity.  \n  **Correct.** No gaps.\n\n### Lemma\u202f2 (A universal lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))\n\n#### Ordering by \\(s(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\)\n- The definition of \\(s(i)\\) and selection of the minimal sum \\(s(i_0)\\) are clear.  \n  **Correct.**\n\n#### Claim about the first uncovered square\n- The solution asserts that because \\(s(i_0)\\) is minimal, either \\(i_0=1\\) or \\(\\sigma(i_0)=1\\).  \n  **Correct** (if both were \\(>1\\) then \\((i_0-1)+(\\sigma(i_0)-1)<s(i_0)\\), contradicting minimality).\n\n- It then says the whole row \\(i_0\\) (except the uncovered cell) can be covered by a single horizontal tile, and similarly for the column.  \n  **Justification Gap** \u2013 while intuitively obvious (a rectangle of height\u202f1 spanning the remaining columns exists), the solution does not explicitly argue that such a tile does not intersect any other tile (none have been placed yet) and that it respects the \u201cat most one uncovered square per row/column\u201d condition. The gap is minor, but a rigorous proof would note that no other uncovered squares lie in that row or column, so a single \\(1\\times (n-1)\\) tile is permissible.\n\n#### Definition of \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\) for later squares\n- The sets are correctly defined as the cells left of, and above, the uncovered cell \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\).  \n  **Correct.** The observation that both are non\u2011empty when \\(s(i)>s(i_0)\\) follows because \\(i>1\\) and \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\).\n\n#### Claim\u202f1 (no earlier tile touches \\(L_i\\))\n- The argument: an earlier uncovered square \\((j,\\sigma(j))\\) has smaller sum, so a tile covering a cell of \\(L_i\\) would have to extend both right of column \\(\\sigma(j)\\) and left of column \\(\\sigma(i)\\), which is impossible because a rectangle cannot contain two uncovered squares.  \n  **Justification Gap** \u2013 the reasoning is informal. A rigorous proof would consider any tile placed to cover a cell of \\(L_i\\); such a tile lies entirely in row \\(i\\) (since it cannot cross the uncovered cell in column \\(\\sigma(i)\\)). If it also covered a cell belonging to an earlier uncovered pair \\((j,\\sigma(j))\\), then that earlier cell would have to be in the same row \\(i\\), contradicting the fact that each row has exactly one uncovered square (the one at column \\(\\sigma(i)\\)). Hence no earlier tile can intersect \\(L_i\\). The solution\u2019s informal phrasing leaves this reasoning implicit.\n\n#### Claim\u202f2 (no earlier tile touches \\(U_i\\))\n- Same structure as Claim\u202f1, swapping rows and columns.  \n  **Justification Gap** \u2013 analogous to Claim\u202f1; the same level of detail is missing.\n\n#### Necessity of new horizontal and vertical tiles for each later uncovered square\n- The solution correctly notes that because earlier tiles avoid \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\), each of these non\u2011empty sets must be covered by new tiles.  \n- It then argues a single tile cannot cover both a cell of \\(L_i\\) (row\u2011restricted) and a cell of \\(U_i\\) (column\u2011restricted) because their intersection would be the uncovered cell, which is forbidden.  \n  **Correct.** This argument is sufficiently rigorous.\n\n#### Counting argument\n- First uncovered square contributes at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile (as discussed, a minor gap).  \n- Each of the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares forces at least one new horizontal and one new vertical tile, all distinct from previously counted tiles.  \n  **Correct** given the previous claims.  \n- Hence at least \\(n-1\\) horizontal and \\(n-1\\) vertical tiles, total \\(2n-2\\).  \n  **Correct.** The lower bound is established.\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n#### Choice of permutation \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\)\n- Selecting the main diagonal as uncovered squares is valid.  \n  **Correct.**\n\n#### Definition of rectangles \\(H_i\\) and \\(V_i\\)\n- For each \\(i\\ge2\\), \\(H_i\\) covers cells \\((i,c)\\) with \\(c\\le i-1\\); \\(V_i\\) covers \\((r,i)\\) with \\(r\\le i-1\\).  \n  **Correct.** These are indeed rectangles of size \\(1\\times(i-1)\\) and \\((i-1)\\times1\\).\n\n#### Disjointness argument\n- Horizontal rectangles lie in distinct rows \u2192 disjoint.  \n- Vertical rectangles lie in distinct columns \u2192 disjoint.  \n- Intersection of a horizontal \\(H_i\\) and a vertical \\(V_j\\) (with \\(i\\neq j\\)) would be cell \\((i,j)\\). The solution analyses two cases:\n  * If \\(j<i\\), then \\(V_j\\) occupies rows \\(1,\\dots,j-1\\), which does **not** include row \\(i\\).  \n  * If \\(j>i\\), then \\(H_i\\) occupies columns \\(1,\\dots,i-1\\), which does **not** include column \\(j\\).  \n  Hence no intersection.  \n  **Justification Gap** \u2013 the case \\(j=i\\) is excluded because then the rectangles are not defined (both would be empty). The argument is essentially complete; the gap is only that the reasoning could be stated more formally, but the conclusion is valid.\n\n#### Coverage argument\n- Any non\u2011diagonal cell either lies left of the diagonal in its row (hence in some \\(H_i\\)) or above the diagonal in its column (hence in some \\(V_j\\)).  \n  **Correct.** This covers all cells not on the diagonal.\n\n#### Counting tiles\n- Two rectangles for each \\(i=2,\\dots,n\\) \u2192 \\(2(n-1)=2n-2\\).  \n  **Correct.**\n\n### Completion of the proof\n- Lemma\u202f2 gives the lower bound, Lemma\u202f3 provides a construction meeting it, so the minimum is \\(2n-2\\).  \n- Substituting \\(n=2025\\) yields \\(4048\\).  \n  **Correct.**\n\n---\n\n### Overall Assessment\nThe solution correctly proves that the minimum number of tiles is \\(4048\\). The logical structure is sound, and the construction matches the lower bound. The only deficiencies are minor **justification gaps** in Lemma\u202f2 (Claims\u202f1 and\u202f2, and the statement about the first square) and a brief gap in the disjointness argument of Lemma\u202f3. These gaps do not affect the validity of the final result, as the missing details can be filled with straightforward rigorous arguments. Consequently, the solution is deemed correct."
