"**Final Verdict:** The solution is **mostly correct** but contains several **Justification Gaps** in Lemma\u202f2 where the arguments are not fully rigorous.\n\n---\n\n### List of Findings\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, *Claim\u202f1*: \u201cNo tile that appears in a covering of any square whose sum is smaller than \\(s(i)\\) can contain a square of \\(L_i\\).\u201d  \n  *Issue:* Justification Gap \u2013 the proof that a tile covering an earlier uncovered square cannot also cover a square in \\(L_i\\) is hand\u2011wavy and does not rigorously rule out all possibilities.\n\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, *Claim\u202f2*: \u201cAnalogously, no tile used for earlier squares can contain a square of \\(U_i\\).\u201d  \n  *Issue:* Justification Gap \u2013 the argument is merely stated as \u201canalogous\u201d without a detailed justification; the same level of rigor as Claim\u202f1 is missing.\n\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, paragraph beginning \u201cBecause the tiles placed so far avoid \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\), each of these two non\u2011empty sets must be covered by **new** tiles.\u201d  \n  *Issue:* Justification Gap \u2013 it is assumed that the only way to cover the squares in \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\) is by new tiles, but a rigorous argument that no previously placed tile could partially cover them (e.g., by extending beyond the earlier uncovered square) is not provided.\n\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, statement \u201ca single tile cannot cover both a square of \\(L_i\\) and a square of \\(U_i\\) \u2026 the intersection \u2026 is the uncovered square \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\), which is forbidden.\u201d  \n  *Issue:* Justification Gap \u2013 the claim that any rectangle containing a point of \\(L_i\\) must lie entirely in row \\(i\\) (and similarly for \\(U_i\\)) is asserted without proof; a rectangle could, in principle, extend over multiple rows and columns while still containing a point of \\(L_i\\).\n\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, conclusion \u201ceach of the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares contributes **at least** one new horizontal tile and **at least** one new vertical tile, distinct from all previously counted tiles.\u201d  \n  *Issue:* Justification Gap \u2013 the step that the new horizontal (resp. vertical) tiles required for different uncovered squares are necessarily distinct is not demonstrated; it is possible that a single horizontal tile could serve the left\u2011side portions of several uncovered squares.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Preliminary Setup\n- The solution defines \\(n=2025\\) and indexes unit squares by \\((r,c)\\). This is standard and correct.\n\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Structure of the uncovered squares)\n- **Step:** Defines \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered square in row \\(i\\) and argues injectivity \u2192 bijectivity.\n- **Verification:** The reasoning is complete: each column contains exactly one uncovered square, so the map is injective; finite sets of equal size imply bijection. **Correct.**\n\n### Lemma\u202f2 (A universal lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))\n\n#### Definition of ordering\n- **Step:** Orders uncovered squares by \\(s(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\) and selects the minimal one \\((i_{0},\\sigma(i_{0}))\\).\n- **Verification:** The definition is clear; the observation that minimality forces \\(i_{0}=1\\) or \\(\\sigma(i_{0})=1\\) follows because if both were \\(\\ge2\\) then \\((1,1)\\) would have a smaller sum, contradicting minimality. **Correct.**\n\n#### First uncovered square argument\n- **Step:** Claims the whole row \\(i_{0}\\) (except the uncovered cell) can be covered by a single horizontal tile, and similarly for the column.\n- **Verification:** This is a construction possibility, not a necessity; the argument is that at most one horizontal and one vertical tile are needed for this square. This is acceptable for a lower\u2011bound argument. **Correct.**\n\n#### Definition of \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\)\n- **Step:** For any later uncovered square \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\) with larger sum, defines left\u2011side set \\(L_i\\) and upper\u2011side set \\(U_i\\); notes both are non\u2011empty.\n- **Verification:** Since \\(s(i)>s(i_{0})\\) and the minimal sum is at least \\(2\\), indeed \\(i>1\\) and \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\). Hence \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\) contain at least one cell. **Correct.**\n\n#### Claim\u202f1 (no earlier tile covers \\(L_i\\))\n- **Step (quoted):** \u201cNo tile that appears in a covering of any square whose sum is smaller than \\(s(i)\\) can contain a square of \\(L_i\\). \u2026 If a tile covering a square of \\(L_i\\) also covered a square of an earlier uncovered row\u2011column pair, that tile would have to extend both to the right of column \\(\\sigma(j)\\) and to the left of column \\(\\sigma(i)\\), which is impossible because a rectangle cannot contain two uncovered squares.\u201d\n- **Issue:** The argument is informal. It assumes that a tile covering an earlier uncovered square \\((j,\\sigma(j))\\) must be confined to the rectangle bounded by that square and the board edges, but does not rule out a tile that stretches beyond \\(\\sigma(j)\\) to the left while still covering a cell of \\(L_i\\). A rigorous proof would need to consider all possible orientations and sizes of a rectangle that contains \\((j,\\sigma(j))\\) and a cell of \\(L_i\\), and show that such a rectangle would inevitably also contain another uncovered cell, contradicting the tiling condition. This step is therefore a **Justification Gap**.\n\n#### Claim\u202f2 (analogous for \\(U_i\\))\n- **Step (quoted):** \u201cAnalogously, no tile used for earlier squares can contain a square of \\(U_i\\).\u201d\n- **Issue:** The solution merely states \u201canalogously\u201d without reproducing the detailed reasoning. Since the justification for Claim\u202f1 is incomplete, the analogous claim inherits the same gap. This is a **Justification Gap**.\n\n#### Necessity of new tiles for \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\)\n- **Step (quoted):** \u201cBecause the tiles placed so far avoid \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\), each of these two non\u2011empty sets must be covered by **new** tiles.\u201d\n- **Issue:** The conclusion presumes that a tile placed earlier cannot be extended later to also cover part of \\(L_i\\) (or \\(U_i\\)) without violating the earlier claim. However, the earlier claim itself is not fully proved, so this inference is not justified. Moreover, it does not consider the possibility that a single new tile could cover a portion of both \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\). Hence a **Justification Gap** exists here.\n\n#### Impossibility of a single tile covering both \\(L_i\\) and \\(U_i\\)\n- **Step (quoted):** \u201ca single tile cannot cover both a square of \\(L_i\\) and a square of \\(U_i\\) \u2026 any rectangle containing a point of \\(L_i\\) lies entirely in row \\(i\\), while any rectangle containing a point of \\(U_i\\) lies entirely in column \\(\\sigma(i)\\).\u201d\n- **Issue:** The claim that a rectangle containing a point of \\(L_i\\) must be confined to row \\(i\\) is false in general; a rectangle could extend over multiple rows while still containing a cell left of \\(\\sigma(i)\\). The correct argument should note that if a rectangle contains a cell of \\(L_i\\) (which is in row \\(i\\) and column \\(<\\sigma(i)\\)) and also a cell of \\(U_i\\) (which is in column \\(\\sigma(i)\\) and row \\(<i\\)), then the rectangle would necessarily contain the intersection cell \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\), which is uncovered\u2014a contradiction. While the intended idea is correct, the presented justification is incomplete and thus a **Justification Gap**.\n\n#### Counting horizontal and vertical tiles\n- **Step:** \u201ceach of the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares contributes **at least** one new horizontal tile and **at least** one new vertical tile, distinct from all previously counted tiles.\u201d\n- **Issue:** The distinctness of the new tiles for different uncovered squares is not proved. It is conceivable that a single horizontal tile could cover the left portions of several rows (e.g., a tile spanning rows \\(i\\) and \\(i'\\) simultaneously) while still avoiding uncovered squares, because the construction only forbids a tile from containing *any* uncovered square, not from spanning multiple rows. The solution assumes each uncovered square forces a fresh horizontal (and vertical) tile, which needs a rigorous argument (e.g., using the ordering by \\(s(i)\\) to show that any horizontal tile can intersect at most one of the sets \\(L_i\\)). This omission is a **Justification Gap**.\n\n#### Derivation of the bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\)\n- **Step:** After the (gap\u2011filled) claims, concludes that there are at least \\(n-1\\) horizontal and \\(n-1\\) vertical tiles, giving \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\).\n- **Verification:** Assuming the previous claims are valid, the arithmetic is correct. The bound follows logically from the (intended) arguments. **Correct**, contingent on the earlier gaps being resolved.\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n- **Step:** Chooses the identity permutation, defines horizontal rectangles \\(H_i\\) and vertical rectangles \\(V_i\\) for \\(i\\ge2\\), and argues disjointness, coverage, and counting.\n- **Verification:**  \n  *Disjointness*: The case analysis for intersections is accurate; the rectangles are either in distinct rows/columns or, when crossing, miss each other because of the strict inequalities.  \n  *Coverage*: Every off\u2011diagonal cell is either left of the diagonal in its row (belongs to some \\(H_i\\)) or above the diagonal in its column (belongs to some \\(V_j\\)). This covers all non\u2011diagonal cells exactly once.  \n  *Counting*: Two rectangles for each \\(i=2,\\dots,n\\) yields \\(2(n-1)\\) tiles.  \n  Hence Lemma\u202f3 is fully rigorous. **Correct.**\n\n### Completion of the proof\n- **Step:** Combines Lemma\u202f2 (lower bound) and Lemma\u202f3 (matching construction) to claim the minimum is \\(2n-2 = 4048\\) for \\(n=2025\\).\n- **Verification:** The logical structure is sound; the conclusion follows from the two lemmas. **Correct**, provided Lemma\u202f2\u2019s lower bound is valid.\n\n---\n\n### Overall Assessment\nThe solution correctly identifies the structure of uncovered squares, provides a plausible construction achieving the bound, and arrives at the right numerical answer. However, the lower\u2011bound argument (Lemma\u202f2) contains several **Justification Gaps** where claims about the impossibility of certain tile placements are not rigorously proved. These gaps do not constitute **Critical Errors** because the overall strategy is sound and can be repaired with more detailed combinatorial reasoning. Consequently, the solution is **not fully rigorous** as written."
