the intersection \u2026 is the uncovered square \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\), which is forbidden.\u201d  \n  *Issue:* Justification Gap \u2013 the claim that any rectangle containing a point of \\(L_i\\) must lie entirely in row \\(i\\) (and similarly for \\(U_i\\)) is asserted without proof; a rectangle could, in principle, extend over multiple rows and columns while still containing a point of \\(L_i\\).\n\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, conclusion \u201ceach of the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares contributes **at least** one new horizontal tile and **at least** one new vertical tile, distinct from all previously counted tiles.\u201d  \n  *Issue:* Justification Gap \u2013 the step that the new horizontal (resp. vertical) tiles required for different uncovered squares are necessarily distinct is not demonstrated; it is possible that a single horizontal tile could serve the left\u2011side portions of several uncovered squares.\n\n---\n\n##"
