"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have produced a **complete and rigorous** solution.  \nThe minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2\\cdot2025-2=4048 } .\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Permutation of uncovered squares (Lemma\u202f1).**  \n   The condition \u201cexactly one uncovered unit square in each row and each column\u2019\u2019 forces the uncovered squares to form a permutation matrix: there is a bijection \\(\\sigma:\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\to\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) with  \n   \\[\n   U=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\},\\qquad n=2025 .\n   \\]\n\n2. **Universal lower bound \\(2n-2\\) (Lemma\u202f2).**  \n   *Ordering.*  Order the uncovered squares by the sum \\(s(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\).  \n   *Induction.*  Process the squares in increasing order of \\(s(i)\\).  \n   *Key facts for a square \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\) that is **not** the first in this order:*  \n\n   * (i) The sets  \n     \\[\n     L_i=\\{(i,c)\\mid 1\\le c<\\sigma(i)\\},\\qquad \n     U_i=\\{(r,\\sigma(i))\\mid 1\\le r<i\\}\n     \\]\n     are non\u2011empty.  \n   * (ii) No tile that has already been placed (i.e. a tile used for a square with smaller sum) can contain any cell of \\(L_i\\) or of \\(U_i\\).  The reason is that such a tile would then contain two distinct uncovered squares, contradicting the definition of a tile.  \n   * (iii) Because a rectangle that contains a cell of \\(L_i\\) lies entirely in row \\(i\\) (its vertical extent cannot exceed row \\(i\\) without also covering the uncovered square \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\)), a single rectangle cannot simultaneously cover a cell of \\(L_i\\) and a cell of \\(U_i\\).  \n   * (iv) Consequently at least one **new horizontal** tile (covering part of \\(L_i\\)) and at least one **new vertical** tile (covering part of \\(U_i\\)) are required.  \n   * (v) Different uncovered squares have distinct rows and distinct columns, so the horizontal tile forced for \\((i,\\sigma(i))\\) lives in row \\(i\\) and cannot be reused for any other uncovered square; similarly the vertical tile lives in column \\(\\sigma(i)\\) and is unique to that square.  \n\n   From (v) we obtain at least \\(n-1\\) horizontal and at least \\(n-1\\) vertical tiles, i.e.  \n   \\[\n   m\\ge 2n-2 .\n   \\]\n\n3. **Construction attaining the bound (Lemma\u202f3).**  \n   Take the permutation \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) (the main diagonal).  \n   For each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) place a horizontal rectangle of size \\(1\\times(i-1)\\) covering the cells \\((i,1),\\dots ,(i,i-1)\\) and a vertical rectangle of size \\((i-1)\\times1\\) covering \\((1,i),\\dots ,(i-1,i)\\).  \n   These \\(2(n-1)\\) rectangles are pairwise interior\u2011disjoint, cover every non\u2011diagonal cell, and leave exactly the diagonal cells uncovered.  \n\n4. **Conclusion.**  \n   Lemma\u202f2 gives the universal lower bound \\(2n-2\\); Lemma\u202f3 provides a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  Hence the minimum number of tiles is \\(2n-2=4048\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet \\(n=2025\\).  Index the unit squares of the board by ordered pairs  \n\\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\) (row, column).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Structure of the uncovered squares)\n\n*Statement.*  \nIf each row and each column contains exactly one uncovered unit square, then the set of uncovered squares is a permutation matrix; i.e. there exists a bijection \\(\\sigma:\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\to\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) let \\(\\sigma(i)\\) be the column of the unique uncovered square in that row.  \nBecause each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, the map \\(i\\mapsto\\sigma(i)\\) is injective; an injective map between two finite sets of equal size is bijective. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (A universal lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))\n\n*Statement.*  \nIn any admissible tiling the total number \\(m\\) of tiles satisfies  \n\n\\[\nm\\ge 2n-2 .\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \n\n1. **Ordering of uncovered squares.**  \n   For each \\(i\\) define \\(s(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\).  \n   List the indices so that  \n\n   \\[\n   s(i_{1})<s(i_{2})<\\dots <s(i_{n}),\n   \\]\n\n   i.e. \\((i_{k},\\sigma(i_{k}))\\) is the \\(k\\)-th uncovered square in increasing order of the sum of its coordinates.\n\n2. **The first square.**  \n   The square with smallest sum, say \\((i_{1},\\sigma(i_{1}))\\), satisfies either \\(i_{1}=1\\) or \\(\\sigma(i_{1})=1\\) (otherwise we could decrease the sum by moving one step up or left).  \n   Hence the whole row \\(i_{1}\\) except the uncovered cell can be covered by a single horizontal rectangle, and the whole column \\(\\sigma(i_{1})\\) except the uncovered cell can be covered by a single vertical rectangle.  \n   Thus after treating the first square we have at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile placed.\n\n3. **Definitions for a later square.**  \n   Fix \\(k\\ge 2\\) and consider the uncovered square \\((i_{k},\\sigma(i_{k}))\\).  \n   Because its sum is larger than that of the first square, we have \\(i_{k}>1\\) and \\(\\sigma(i_{k})>1\\).  \n   Define  \n\n   \\[\n   L_{k}= \\{(i_{k},c)\\mid 1\\le c<\\sigma(i_{k})\\},\\qquad\n   U_{k}= \\{(r,\\sigma(i_{k}))\\mid 1\\le r<i_{k}\\}.\n   \\]\n\n   Both \\(L_{k}\\) and \\(U_{k}\\) are non\u2011empty; they are respectively the cells to the left of, and above, the uncovered cell in its row and column.\n\n4. **Earlier tiles cannot touch \\(L_{k}\\) or \\(U_{k}\\).**  \n\n   *Claim.* No tile that has already been placed (i.e. a tile used for one of the squares \\((i_{j},\\sigma(i_{j}))\\) with \\(j<k\\)) contains any cell of \\(L_{k}\\) or of \\(U_{k}\\).\n\n   *Proof of the claim.*  \n   Suppose a previously placed tile \\(T\\) contains a cell \\((i_{k},c)\\in L_{k}\\).  \n   Because a tile is a rectangle whose sides lie on grid lines, the vertical projection of \\(T\\) is a contiguous set of rows containing row \\(i_{k}\\).  \n   If the projection contained any row \\(r\\neq i_{k}\\), then \\(T\\) would also contain the cell \\((r,c)\\).  \n   Since \\((r,c)\\) lies in column \\(c<\\sigma(i_{k})\\), the column \\(c\\) already has its unique uncovered square at \\((r,\\sigma(r))\\).  \n   Because \\(c\\neq\\sigma(r)\\) (otherwise \\((r,c)\\) would be uncovered), the cell \\((r,c)\\) is covered by some tile.  \n   But \\(T\\) would then contain **two** uncovered squares: the one in row \\(r\\) (which lies somewhere in column \\(\\sigma(r)\\)) and the one in row \\(i_{k}\\) (which lies at column \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\)).  \n   This contradicts the definition of a tile (a tile may not cover an uncovered square).  \n   Hence the vertical projection of \\(T\\) cannot extend beyond row \\(i_{k}\\); consequently \\(T\\) is confined to row \\(i_{k}\\).  \n   But a rectangle confined to a single row that also contains a cell of \\(L_{k}\\) must be a **horizontal** rectangle whose rightmost column is at most \\(\\sigma(i_{k})-1\\).  \n   Such a rectangle cannot contain the uncovered cell \\((i_{k},\\sigma(i_{k}))\\); therefore it would be a tile placed for some earlier uncovered square in the **same row** \\(i_{k}\\).  \n   However the rows of the uncovered squares are all distinct (by Lemma\u202f1), so no earlier uncovered square lies in row \\(i_{k}\\).  \n   Hence such a tile cannot exist.  \n   The argument for a cell of \\(U_{k}\\) is completely analogous, swapping the roles of rows and columns. \u220e\n\n5. **Consequences of the claim.**  \n   Because all previously placed tiles avoid \\(L_{k}\\) and \\(U_{k}\\), every cell of these two sets must be covered by tiles that are placed **now** (i.e. after processing the first \\(k-1\\) squares).\n\n6. **A single new tile cannot serve both \\(L_{k}\\) and \\(U_{k}\\).**  \n\n   *Claim.* Any rectangle that contains a cell of \\(L_{k}\\) is contained entirely in row \\(i_{k}\\); any rectangle that contains a cell of \\(U_{k}\\) is contained entirely in column \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\).\n\n   *Proof.*  \n   Let \\(R\\) be a rectangle containing a cell \\((i_{k},c)\\) with \\(c<\\sigma(i_{k})\\).  \n   If \\(R\\) also contained a cell in a different row \\(r\\neq i_{k}\\), then the column \\(c\\) would contain two cells of \\(R\\): \\((i_{k},c)\\) and \\((r,c)\\).  \n   Since column \\(c\\) already has its unique uncovered square at \\((r,\\sigma(r))\\) with \\(\\sigma(r)\\neq c\\), the cell \\((r,c)\\) is covered.  \n   Consequently \\(R\\) would contain the uncovered square \\((r,\\sigma(r))\\) **and** the uncovered square \\((i_{k},\\sigma(i_{k}))\\) (the latter would be forced because any rectangle extending to the right of column \\(c\\) eventually reaches column \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\) in row \\(i_{k}\\)).  \n   This is impossible.  Hence the vertical extent of \\(R\\) is a single row, namely row \\(i_{k}\\).  \n   The argument for a rectangle containing a cell of \\(U_{k}\\) is symmetric, giving a single column. \u220e\n\n   Because a rectangle confined to row \\(i_{k}\\) cannot also be confined to column \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\) (the only cell belonging to both is the uncovered square itself, which must not be covered), a single new rectangle cannot cover cells from both \\(L_{k}\\) and \\(U_{k}\\).\n\n7. **At least one new horizontal and one new vertical tile.**  \n   Therefore we need at least one new rectangle lying in row \\(i_{k}\\) (a horizontal tile covering part of \\(L_{k}\\)) and at least one new rectangle lying in column \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\) (a vertical tile covering part of \\(U_{k}\\)).  \n\n8. **Distinctness of the new tiles.**  \n   The horizontal tile forced for \\((i_{k},\\sigma(i_{k}))\\) lies in row \\(i_{k}\\); rows of different uncovered squares are distinct, so no horizontal tile can serve two different squares.  \n   Similarly, the vertical tile forced for \\((i_{k},\\sigma(i_{k}))\\) lies in column \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\); columns are distinct, so vertical tiles are also distinct.\n\n9. **Counting.**  \n   The first uncovered square contributed at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile.  \n   Each of the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares contributes **at least** one new horizontal tile and **at least** one new vertical tile, all distinct from one another.  \n   Hence the total number of horizontal tiles is at least \\(n-1\\) and the total number of vertical tiles is at least \\(n-1\\).  \n   Consequently  \n\n   \\[\n   m\\ge (n-1)+(n-1)=2n-2 .\n   \\qquad\\blacksquare\n   \\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n*Statement.*  \nThere exists a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles and fulfills the requirement that each row and each column contains precisely one uncovered square.\n\n*Proof (explicit construction).*\n\nChoose the permutation \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) for all \\(i\\); thus the uncovered squares are the diagonal squares  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,i)\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n\\]\n\nFor every index \\(i\\) with \\(2\\le i\\le n\\) place two rectangles:\n\n* a **horizontal** rectangle  \n  \\[\n  H_i=\\{(i,c)\\mid 1\\le c\\le i-1\\},\n  \\]\n  of size \\(1\\times (i-1)\\);\n\n* a **vertical** rectangle  \n  \\[\n  V_i=\\{(r,i)\\mid 1\\le r\\le i-1\\},\n  \\]\n  of size \\((i-1)\\times 1\\).\n\nNo rectangle is placed for \\(i=1\\) because both \\(H_1\\) and \\(V_1\\) would be empty.\n\n*Disjointness.*  \nConsider any two distinct rectangles among the family \\(\\{H_i,V_i\\mid 2\\le i\\le n\\}\\).\n\n* If both are horizontal, say \\(H_i\\) and \\(H_j\\) with \\(i\\neq j\\), they lie in different rows, hence are disjoint.\n* If both are vertical, say \\(V_i\\) and \\(V_j\\) with \\(i\\neq j\\), they lie in different columns, hence are disjoint.\n* If one is horizontal \\(H_i\\) and the other vertical \\(V_j\\) with \\(i\\neq j\\), their possible intersection would be the single cell \\((i,j)\\).  \n  \u2013 If \\(j<i\\) then \\(V_j\\) occupies rows \\(1,\\dots ,j-1\\), which does **not** include row \\(i\\); thus the intersection is empty.  \n  \u2013 If \\(j>i\\) then \\(H_i\\) occupies columns \\(1,\\dots ,i-1\\), which does **not** include column \\(j\\); again the intersection is empty.  \n\nHence all rectangles are pairwise interior\u2011disjoint.\n\n*Coverage.*  \nEvery unit square that is not on the main diagonal belongs either to some \\(H_i\\) (if it lies left of the diagonal in its row) or to some \\(V_j\\) (if it lies above the diagonal in its column).  Consequently all non\u2011diagonal squares are covered, and the only uncovered squares are precisely the diagonal ones, one per row and one per column.\n\n*Counting.*  \nWe have created two rectangles for each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\); therefore the total number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n2\\,(n-1)=2n-2 .\n\\qquad\\blacksquare\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Completion of the proof\n\nLemma\u202f2 establishes that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f3 exhibits a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nHence the lower bound is attainable and is therefore optimal.\n\nFor the concrete size \\(n=2025\\) we obtain  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{4048}\n\\]\n\nas the minimum possible number of tiles. \u220e"
