"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains a **Critical Error** and is therefore invalid.\n\n**List of Findings**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, step\u202f4 (claim that a previously placed tile cannot contain any cell of \\(L_{k}\\) or \\(U_{k}\\)).  \n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the argument that such a tile would necessarily contain two uncovered squares is false; a tile may lie entirely in rows/columns that already have their unique uncovered squares elsewhere, covering only already\u2011covered cells. This breaks the logical chain of the lower\u2011bound proof.\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, step\u202f6 (claim that any rectangle containing a cell of \\(L_{k}\\) must be confined to row \\(i_{k}\\)).  \n  * **Issue:** Justification Gap \u2013 the proof relies on the flawed argument from step\u202f4 and does not rigorously exclude the possibility of a rectangle extending over multiple rows without covering an uncovered square.\n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n#### Preliminary definitions\n- The solution defines \\(n=2025\\) and indexes unit squares by \\((r,c)\\).  \n  *Correct*: Standard notation, no issue.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f1\n- Claims the uncovered squares form a permutation matrix and proves it by defining \\(\\sigma(i)\\).  \n  *Correct*: The argument that each column contains exactly one uncovered square makes \\(\\sigma\\) injective, and finiteness gives bijectivity. No gaps.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f2 (lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))\n\n**Step\u202f1 \u2013 Ordering of uncovered squares**  \n- Introduces \\(s(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\) and orders the squares by increasing \\(s\\).  \n  *Correct*: Well\u2011defined ordering; no problem.\n\n**Step\u202f2 \u2013 The first square**  \n- Argues the square with smallest sum must lie in row\u202f1 or column\u202f1; then says the whole row (resp. column) can be covered by a single horizontal (resp. vertical) tile, giving \u201cat most one\u201d of each.  \n  *Correct but informal*: It is true that a single tile suffices, and \u201cat most one\u201d is a valid observation (using more tiles would only increase the count). No logical error.\n\n**Step\u202f3 \u2013 Definition of \\(L_{k}\\) and \\(U_{k}\\)**  \n- Defines the sets of cells left of and above the \\(k\\)-th uncovered square.  \n  *Correct*: Clear definitions.\n\n**Step\u202f4 \u2013 Claim: No earlier tile contains a cell of \\(L_{k}\\) or \\(U_{k}\\)**  \n- **Argument summary**: Suppose an earlier tile \\(T\\) contains a cell \\((i_{k},c)\\in L_{k}\\). Because \\(T\\) is a rectangle, its vertical projection includes some other row \\(r\\neq i_{k}\\); then \\((r,c)\\) lies in column \\(c\\) which already has its unique uncovered square \\((r,\\sigma(r))\\). The solution claims that \\(T\\) would then contain two uncovered squares (the one in row \\(r\\) and the one in row \\(i_{k}\\)), contradicting the definition of a tile.  \n- **Critical error**: A tile is *forbidden* to cover an uncovered square, but it is **not required** to contain any uncovered square at all. The presence of \\((r,c)\\) in the same column does **not** force \\((r,c)\\) to be uncovered; indeed \\((r,c)\\) is covered (by definition of the problem) because the only uncovered cell in column \\(c\\) is \\((r,\\sigma(r))\\) with \\(\\sigma(r)\\neq c\\). Hence \\(T\\) could contain \\((r,c)\\) without covering an uncovered square. The reasoning that \u201c\\(T\\) would contain two uncovered squares\u201d is false. Consequently the claim that earlier tiles cannot intersect \\(L_{k}\\) (or \\(U_{k}\\)) is unsupported. This invalidates the subsequent deductions that rely on the claim.\n\n**Impact**: The lower\u2011bound argument hinges on the impossibility of earlier tiles touching \\(L_{k}\\) or \\(U_{k}\\). Since this claim is unfounded, the conclusion that each later uncovered square forces at least one new horizontal and one new vertical tile is not justified.\n\n**Step\u202f5 \u2013 Consequence of the claim**  \n- Uses the (invalid) claim from Step\u202f4 to assert that all cells of \\(L_{k}\\) and \\(U_{k}\\) must be covered by *new* tiles.  \n  *Invalid*: Because Step\u202f4 is false, this consequence does not follow.\n\n**Step\u202f6 \u2013 Claim: A rectangle containing a cell of \\(L_{k}\\) is confined to row \\(i_{k}\\)**  \n- Relies on the same flawed reasoning as Step\u202f4 (that extending to another row would force inclusion of an uncovered square).  \n  *Justification Gap*: Even if one accepts the intended idea, the proof does not rigorously exclude a rectangle that spans multiple rows but avoids all uncovered squares (e.g., by staying entirely within columns that already have their uncovered squares elsewhere). The argument is therefore incomplete.\n\n**Step\u202f7\u20139 \u2013 Counting argument**  \n- Based on the (now unsupported) conclusions of Steps\u202f4\u20136, the solution counts at least one new horizontal and one new vertical tile for each of the remaining \\(n-1\\) uncovered squares, leading to the bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\).  \n  *Invalid*: Since the premises are false, the derived bound is not proven.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f3 (construction achieving \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n- Provides an explicit tiling using the main diagonal as uncovered squares and, for each \\(i\\ge2\\), a horizontal tile covering cells left of the diagonal in row \\(i\\) and a vertical tile covering cells above the diagonal in column \\(i\\).  \n  *Correct*: The construction is clearly described, the disjointness argument is sound, and the count of tiles is indeed \\(2(n-1)\\). No issues.\n\n#### Completion of the proof\n\n- Combines Lemma\u202f2 (lower bound) and Lemma\u202f3 (matching construction) to claim optimality.  \n  *Invalid*: Because Lemma\u202f2 is not correctly proved, the conclusion that the lower bound is optimal is unsupported.\n\n#### Overall assessment\n- The constructive part (Lemma\u202f3) is valid, but the essential lower\u2011bound argument (Lemma\u202f2) contains a critical logical flaw in Step\u202f4, which propagates through the rest of the lemma. Consequently the solution does not rigorously establish that \\(2n-2\\) is the minimum number of tiles. Therefore the solution is **invalid**."
