        "content": "\n======================================================================\n### Problem ###\n\n*** Problem Statement ***\n\nConsider a $2025\\times2025$ grid of unit squares. Matilda wishes to place on the grid some rectangular tiles, possibly of difference sizes, such that each side of every tile lies on a grid line and every unit square is covered by at most one tile.\n\nDetermine the minimum number of tiles Matilda needs to place so that each row and each column of the grid has exactly one unit square that is not covered by any tile.\n\n======================================================================\n### Solution ###\n\n**\n\nLet \\(n=2025\\).  Index the unit squares of the board by ordered pairs  \n\\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\) (row, column).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Structure of the uncovered squares)\n\n*Statement.*  \nIf each row and each column contains exactly one uncovered unit square, then the set of uncovered squares is a permutation matrix; i.e. there exists a bijection \\(\\sigma:\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\to\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) let \\(\\sigma(i)\\) be the column of the unique uncovered square in that row.  \nBecause each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, the map \\(i\\mapsto\\sigma(i)\\) is injective; an injective map between two finite sets of equal size is bijective. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Reduction to 1\u2011by\u2011k / k\u2011by\u20111 tiles)\n\n*Statement.*  \nFrom any admissible tiling we can obtain another admissible tiling that uses **no more** tiles and in which every tile is either a horizontal rectangle of height\u202f1 or a vertical rectangle of width\u202f1.\n\n*Proof.*  \nConsider a tile \\(R\\) whose height \\(h\\ge2\\) and width \\(w\\ge2\\).  \nSplit \\(R\\) into two rectangles:\n\n* a horizontal rectangle \\(H\\) consisting of the first row of \\(R\\) (size \\(1\\times w\\));\n* a vertical rectangle \\(V\\) consisting of the remaining \\(h-1\\) rows of the first column of \\(R\\) (size \\((h-1)\\times1\\)).\n\nBoth \\(H\\) and \\(V\\) lie on grid lines, are interior\u2011disjoint, together cover exactly the cells of \\(R\\), and do not cover any uncovered square (the uncovered squares are outside \\(R\\) because a tile never contains an uncovered square).  \nReplacing \\(R\\) by \\(H\\cup V\\) therefore preserves admissibility and increases the number of tiles by **one**.  \n\nIf the original tiling contains \\(t\\) tiles, after repeatedly applying this operation to every tile of size at least \\(2\\times2\\) we obtain a tiling with at most \\(t\\)\u202f+\u202f(number of replaced tiles)\u202f\u2264\u202f\\(2t\\) tiles, all of which are horizontal or vertical.  \nSince we are interested only in a **lower bound** on the number of tiles, we may work with the latter (horizontal/vertical) tiling, because any lower bound that holds for it also holds for the original tiling. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\) for horizontal/vertical tilings)\n\n*Statement.*  \nIn any tiling that uses only horizontal tiles (height\u202f1) and vertical tiles (width\u202f1) and satisfies the condition of Lemma\u202f1, the total number \\(m\\) of tiles satisfies  \n\n\\[\nm\\ge 2n-2 .\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \n\n1. **Ordering of uncovered squares.**  \n   For each \\(i\\) set \\(s(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\).  \n   Relabel the indices so that  \n\n   \\[\n   s(i_{1})<s(i_{2})<\\dots <s(i_{n}),\n   \\]\n\n   i.e. \\((i_{k},\\sigma(i_{k}))\\) is the \\(k\\)-th uncovered square in increasing order of the sum of its coordinates.\n\n2. **The first uncovered square.**  \n   For \\((i_{1},\\sigma(i_{1}))\\) we may use at most one horizontal tile (covering cells to the left of the uncovered cell) and at most one vertical tile (covering cells above it).  \n   Thus after processing the first square we have introduced at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile.\n\n3. **Definitions for a later square.**  \n   Fix \\(k\\ge2\\) and consider \\((i_{k},\\sigma(i_{k}))\\).  \n   Because its sum is larger than that of the first square, we have \\(i_{k}>1\\) and \\(\\sigma(i_{k})>1\\).  \n   Define  \n\n   \\[\n   L_{k}= \\{(i_{k},c)\\mid 1\\le c<\\sigma(i_{k})\\},\\qquad\n   U_{k}= \\{(r,\\sigma(i_{k}))\\mid 1\\le r<i_{k}\\}.\n   \\]\n\n   Both sets are non\u2011empty; they are respectively the cells to the left of, and above, the uncovered cell in its row and column.\n\n4. **Previously placed tiles avoid \\(L_{k}\\) and \\(U_{k}\\).**  \n\n   **Claim.** No tile that has already been placed (i.e. a tile used for one of the squares \\((i_{j},\\sigma(i_{j}))\\) with \\(j<k\\)) contains any cell of \\(L_{k}\\) or of \\(U_{k}\\).\n\n   *Proof of the claim.*  \n   All tiles are horizontal or vertical.  \n   Suppose a previously placed tile \\(T\\) contains a cell \\((i_{k},c)\\in L_{k}\\).  \n   Then \\(T\\) must be horizontal (a vertical tile would be confined to a single column, contradicting the presence of two different columns \\(c\\) and \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\) in the same tile).  \n   A horizontal tile occupies exactly one row; because it contains a cell of row \\(i_{k}\\) it lies in row \\(i_{k}\\).  \n   But rows of uncovered squares are all distinct (Lemma\u202f1), so no uncovered square with index \\(j<k\\) lies in row \\(i_{k}\\); consequently no tile placed earlier could have been assigned to row \\(i_{k}\\).  \n   Hence such a tile cannot exist.  \n   The argument for a cell of \\(U_{k}\\) is symmetric (a tile containing a cell of \\(U_{k}\\) would have to be vertical and would lie in column \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\), which is unavailable to earlier squares). \u220e\n\n5. **Nature of tiles that cover \\(L_{k}\\) and \\(U_{k}\\).**  \n\n   **Claim.** Any tile that contains a cell of \\(L_{k}\\) is a horizontal tile lying in row \\(i_{k}\\); any tile that contains a cell of \\(U_{k}\\) is a vertical tile lying in column \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\).\n\n   *Proof.*  \n   By Lemma\u202f2 every tile is horizontal or vertical.  \n   If a tile contains a cell of \\(L_{k}\\) its column is \\(c<\\sigma(i_{k})\\).  \n   A vertical tile would be confined to column \\(c\\); column \\(c\\) already possesses its unique uncovered square at \\((r,\\sigma(r))\\) with \\(\\sigma(r)\\neq c\\).  \n   A vertical tile in column \\(c\\) would therefore have to cover that uncovered square, which is forbidden.  \n   Hence the tile must be horizontal, and a horizontal tile occupies a single row; because it contains a cell of row \\(i_{k}\\) it must be the row \\(i_{k}\\) itself.  \n   The statement for \\(U_{k}\\) follows by interchanging rows and columns. \u220e\n\n   Consequently a single new tile cannot simultaneously cover cells from both \\(L_{k}\\) and \\(U_{k}\\); one new horizontal tile is needed for \\(L_{k}\\) and one new vertical tile is needed for \\(U_{k}\\).\n\n6. **Distinctness of the new tiles.**  \n   The horizontal tile forced for \\((i_{k},\\sigma(i_{k}))\\) lies in row \\(i_{k}\\); rows of different uncovered squares are distinct, so this tile cannot be reused for any other uncovered square.  \n   Similarly the vertical tile lies in column \\(\\sigma(i_{k})\\), a column that is unique to this square.\n\n7. **Counting.**  \n   The first uncovered square contributes at most one horizontal and at most one vertical tile.  \n   Each of the remaining \\(n-1\\) squares contributes **at least** one new horizontal tile and **at least** one new vertical tile, all distinct from one another.  \n   Hence the total numbers of horizontal and vertical tiles are each at least \\(n-1\\), and the total number of tiles satisfies  \n\n   \\[\n   m\\ge (n-1)+(n-1)=2n-2 .\n   \\tag{2}\n   \\]\n\n   This proves the claimed lower bound. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f4 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n*Statement.*  \nThere exists a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles and fulfills the requirement that each row and each column contains precisely one uncovered square.\n\n*Proof (explicit construction).*\n\nChoose the permutation \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) for all \\(i\\); thus the uncovered squares are the diagonal squares  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,i)\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n\\]\n\nFor every index \\(i\\) with \\(2\\le i\\le n\\) place two rectangles:\n\n* a **horizontal** rectangle  \n  \\[\n  H_i=\\{(i,c)\\mid 1\\le c\\le i-1\\},\n  \\]\n  of size \\(1\\times (i-1)\\);\n\n* a **vertical** rectangle  \n  \\[\n  V_i=\\{(r,i)\\mid 1\\le r\\le i-1\\},\n  \\]\n  of size \\((i-1)\\times 1\\).\n\nNo rectangle is placed for \\(i=1\\) because both \\(H_1\\) and \\(V_1\\) would be empty.\n\n*Disjointness.*  \nIf two rectangles are both horizontal they lie in different rows, hence are disjoint; if both are vertical they lie in different columns, hence are disjoint.  \nIf one is horizontal \\(H_i\\) and the other vertical \\(V_j\\) with \\(i\\neq j\\), their possible intersection would be the single cell \\((i,j)\\).  \nWhen \\(j<i\\), \\(V_j\\) occupies rows \\(1,\\dots ,j-1\\) and therefore does not reach row \\(i\\); when \\(j>i\\), \\(H_i\\) occupies columns \\(1,\\dots ,i-1\\) and therefore does not reach column \\(j\\).  \nThus all rectangles are pairwise interior\u2011disjoint.\n\n*Coverage.*  \nEvery non\u2011diagonal cell either lies to the left of the diagonal in its row (hence belongs to some \\(H_i\\)) or lies above the diagonal in its column (hence belongs to some \\(V_j\\)).  \nConsequently all non\u2011diagonal cells are covered, and the only uncovered cells are the diagonal ones, one per row and one per column.\n\n*Counting.*  \nWe have created two rectangles for each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\); therefore the total number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n2\\,(n-1)=2n-2 .\n\\qquad\\blacksquare\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Completion of the proof\n\nLemma\u202f3 establishes that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f4 exhibits a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nHence the lower bound is attainable and is optimal.\n\nFor the concrete board size \\(n=2025\\) we obtain  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{4048}\n\\]\n\nas the minimum possible number of tiles. \u220e\n\n\n### Verification Task Reminder ###\n\nYour task is to act as an IMO grader. Now, generate the **summary** and the **step-by-step verification log** for the solution above. In your log, justify each correct step and explain in detail any errors or justification gaps you find, as specified in the instructions above.\n\n"
    }
