"**Final Verdict:** The solution is correct.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* No issues were found. All steps are rigorously justified, and the argument establishes both a valid lower bound and a matching construction.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Lemma\u202f1  \n- **Step:** Definition of \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered square in row \\(i\\).  \n- **Verification:** Since each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, the map \\(i\\mapsto\\sigma(i)\\) is injective. An injective map between two finite sets of the same cardinality \\(n\\) is bijective. Hence the uncovered squares form a permutation matrix.  \n- **Conclusion:** Correct.\n\n### Lemma\u202f2  \n- **Step:** Replace any tile \\(R\\) of size \\(h\\times w\\) with \\(h\\ge2,\\;w\\ge2\\) by a horizontal \\(1\\times w\\) tile \\(H\\) (first row) and a vertical \\((h-1)\\times1\\) tile \\(V\\) (first column of the remaining rows).  \n- **Verification:**  \n  1. \\(H\\) and \\(V\\) lie on grid lines and are interior\u2011disjoint.  \n  2. Their union exactly covers the cells of \\(R\\).  \n  3. No uncovered square lies inside \\(R\\) (by definition of admissible tiling), so the replacement does not cover any uncovered square.  \n  4. The operation increases the number of tiles by exactly one. Repeating for every tile of size at least \\(2\\times2\\) yields a tiling using at most \\(2t\\) tiles if the original used \\(t\\).  \n  5. Any lower bound proved for this restricted class (tiles of height\u202f1 or width\u202f1) automatically applies to the original class, because the restricted class can only have *more* tiles.  \n- **Conclusion:** Correct.\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))\n\n1. **Ordering uncovered squares.**  \n   - Define \\(s(i)=i+\\sigma(i)\\) and relabel so that \\(s(i_1)<s(i_2)<\\dots<s(i_n)\\). This is a legitimate reordering of the indices.  \n\n2. **First uncovered square.**  \n   - At most one horizontal tile can cover cells left of \\((i_1,\\sigma(i_1))\\) and at most one vertical tile can cover cells above it. Hence at most one of each type is needed for the first square.  \n\n3. **Definition of \\(L_k\\) and \\(U_k\\).**  \n   - For \\(k\\ge2\\), because \\(s(i_k)>s(i_1)\\) we have \\(i_k>1\\) and \\(\\sigma(i_k)>1\\); thus the sets \\(L_k\\) (cells left of the uncovered cell in its row) and \\(U_k\\) (cells above it in its column) are non\u2011empty.  \n\n4. **Claim: previously placed tiles avoid \\(L_k\\) and \\(U_k\\).**  \n   - Any earlier tile lies either in a different row (if horizontal) or a different column (if vertical) because rows and columns of uncovered squares are all distinct (Lemma\u202f1). Hence it cannot intersect \\(L_k\\) (same row) nor \\(U_k\\) (same column). The argument given is explicit and valid.  \n\n5. **Claim: any tile covering a cell of \\(L_k\\) must be horizontal in row \\(i_k\\); any tile covering a cell of \\(U_k\\) must be vertical in column \\(\\sigma(i_k)\\).**  \n   - Since all tiles are height\u202f1 or width\u202f1 (Lemma\u202f2), a tile that contains a cell of \\(L_k\\) cannot be vertical (a vertical tile would be confined to a single column, contradicting the presence of two different columns in the same tile). Thus it is horizontal, and because it contains a cell of row \\(i_k\\) it occupies exactly row \\(i_k\\). The symmetric argument for \\(U_k\\) is valid.  \n\n6. **Consequences.**  \n   - A single new tile cannot cover both a cell of \\(L_k\\) and a cell of \\(U_k\\); therefore at least one new horizontal tile and at least one new vertical tile are required for each \\(k\\ge2\\).  \n\n7. **Distinctness.**  \n   - Horizontal tiles forced for different uncovered squares lie in different rows (rows are distinct), so they cannot be reused. The same holds for vertical tiles in distinct columns.  \n\n8. **Counting.**  \n   - First square: \u22641 horizontal + \u22641 vertical.  \n   - Remaining \\(n-1\\) squares: each contributes \u22651 new horizontal and \u22651 new vertical tile, all distinct.  \n   - Hence \\(\\#\\text{horizontal}\\ge n-1\\) and \\(\\#\\text{vertical}\\ge n-1\\).  \n   - Total tiles \\(m\\ge (n-1)+(n-1)=2n-2\\).  \n\nAll sub\u2011steps are justified; no logical gaps are present.\n\n### Lemma\u202f4 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n- **Choice of permutation:** \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) gives uncovered squares on the main diagonal.  \n- **Tiles defined:** For each \\(i=2,\\dots,n\\) a horizontal tile \\(H_i\\) covering columns \\(1\\) to \\(i-1\\) in row \\(i\\), and a vertical tile \\(V_i\\) covering rows \\(1\\) to \\(i-1\\) in column \\(i\\).  \n- **Disjointness:**  \n  * Horizontal tiles are in distinct rows \u2192 disjoint.  \n  * Vertical tiles are in distinct columns \u2192 disjoint.  \n  * Intersection of a horizontal \\(H_i\\) and a vertical \\(V_j\\) would be cell \\((i,j)\\). If \\(j<i\\), \\(V_j\\) stops at row \\(j-1\\) and does not reach row \\(i\\); if \\(j>i\\), \\(H_i\\) stops at column \\(i-1\\) and does not reach column \\(j\\). Hence no intersection.  \n- **Coverage:** Every off\u2011diagonal cell either lies left of the diagonal in its row (belongs to some \\(H_i\\)) or above the diagonal in its column (belongs to some \\(V_j\\)). Thus all non\u2011diagonal cells are covered, and only diagonal cells remain uncovered.  \n- **Counting:** Two tiles for each \\(i=2,\\dots,n\\) gives \\(2(n-1)=2n-2\\) tiles.  \n\nAll statements are proved rigorously.\n\n### Completion of the proof\n- Lemma\u202f3 gives the lower bound \\(2n-2\\).  \n- Lemma\u202f4 provides a construction attaining this bound.  \n- Therefore the minimum number of tiles is \\(2n-2\\).  \n- Substituting \\(n=2025\\) yields \\(2\\cdot2025-2 = 4048\\).\n\nAll logical steps are sound; the solution correctly determines the minimum number of tiles."
