"**Final Verdict:** The solution contains a **Critical Error** and is therefore invalid.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, \u201cSplit\u202f\\(R\\) into two rectangles: a horizontal rectangle\u202f\\(H\\) consisting of the first row of\u202f\\(R\\) (size\u202f\\(1\\times w\\)); a vertical rectangle\u202f\\(V\\) consisting of the remaining\u202f\\(h-1\\) rows of the first column of\u202f\\(R\\) (size\u202f\\((h-1)\\times1\\)).\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the two new rectangles together cover only \\(w+(h-1)\\) unit squares, which is strictly less than the original \\(h\\cdot w\\) squares when \\(h,w\\ge 2\\). Thus the replacement does **not** preserve the covered region, breaking the logical chain of the proof.\n\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f2, \u201cReplacing\u202f\\(R\\) by\u202f\\(H\\cup V\\) therefore preserves admissibility\u2026\u201d\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 because the replacement fails to cover the whole original tile, the resulting configuration is not a valid tiling of the same cells, so the claim that admissibility is preserved is false.\n\n* **Location:** Lemma\u202f3, the entire argument relies on Lemma\u202f2\u2019s reduction to horizontal/vertical tiles.\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 since Lemma\u202f2 is invalid, the lower\u2011bound proof in Lemma\u202f3 is built on a false premise; consequently the derived bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\) is not justified.\n\n* **Location:** Overall conclusion that the minimum number of tiles is \\(2n-2=4048\\).\n  * **Issue:** Critical Error \u2013 the lower\u2011bound part of the argument is unsound, so the optimality claim is unsupported.\n\n---\n\n### Detailed Verification Log\n\n#### Lemma\u202f1  \n*Statement:* The uncovered squares form a permutation matrix.  \n*Verification:* The argument correctly defines \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered square in row \\(i\\). Since each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, \\(\\sigma\\) is injective; a map between two finite sets of equal size that is injective is bijective. This step is rigorous and correct.  \n\n#### Lemma\u202f2  \n*Statement:* Any admissible tiling can be transformed into one using only height\u20111 or width\u20111 tiles without increasing the number of tiles.  \n\n*Step examined:*  \n> \u201cConsider a tile \\(R\\) whose height \\(h\\ge2\\) and width \\(w\\ge2\\). Split \\(R\\) into two rectangles: a horizontal rectangle \\(H\\) consisting of the first row of \\(R\\) (size \\(1\\times w\\)); a vertical rectangle \\(V\\) consisting of the remaining \\(h-1\\) rows of the first column of \\(R\\) (size \\((h-1)\\times1\\)).\u201d\n\n*Analysis:*  \n- The original tile \\(R\\) contains \\(h\\cdot w\\) unit squares.  \n- The proposed replacement covers \\(w\\) squares in \\(H\\) plus \\((h-1)\\) squares in \\(V\\), totalling \\(w+(h-1)\\) squares.  \n- For any \\(h,w\\ge2\\) we have \\(w+(h-1) < h\\cdot w\\) (e.g., \\(h=2,w=3\\): \\(3+1=4\\) vs. \\(6\\)).  \n- Hence the two new rectangles **do not** cover the entire area of \\(R\\); a large sub\u2011rectangle of size \\((h-1)\\times(w-1)\\) is omitted.  \n\n*Conclusion:* This is a **Critical Error**. The claimed \u201cpreserves admissibility\u201d is false because the replacement leaves uncovered cells that were previously covered, violating the definition of a tiling. Consequently the rest of Lemma\u202f2 collapses.\n\n*Further steps in Lemma\u202f2:* The subsequent statements (\u201cincreases the number of tiles by one\u201d, \u201cafter repeatedly applying \u2026 we obtain a tiling with at most \\(2t\\) tiles\u201d, \u201cany lower bound that holds for it also holds for the original tiling\u201d) all depend on the faulty replacement. Since the replacement is invalid, these conclusions are unsupported.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f3  \n*Statement:* For tilings consisting only of horizontal (height\u202f1) and vertical (width\u202f1) tiles, at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles are needed.  \n\n*Dependency:* The lemma explicitly assumes we may restrict attention to such \u201chorizontal/vertical\u201d tilings because of Lemma\u202f2. Since Lemma\u202f2 is incorrect, the restriction is unjustified. The combinatorial argument that follows (ordering uncovered squares, defining sets \\(L_k\\) and \\(U_k\\), and counting forced new tiles) is internally consistent **if** the premise that we may consider only horizontal/vertical tiles were true. However, without a valid reduction from arbitrary admissible tilings to this restricted class, the lower bound does not apply to the original problem. Therefore the entire Lemma\u202f3 is **invalid** due to reliance on a critical error.\n\n#### Lemma\u202f4  \n*Statement:* Provides an explicit construction using exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles (the diagonal uncovered squares and row/column \u201cstaircase\u201d tiles).  \n\n*Verification:* The construction is correct: each non\u2011diagonal cell is covered exactly once, tiles are disjoint, and the count is \\(2(n-1)\\). This part of the solution is sound.\n\n#### Final Conclusion  \nThe solution correctly identifies a feasible tiling with \\(2n-2\\) tiles, but it fails to prove that fewer tiles are impossible because the lower\u2011bound argument rests on Lemma\u202f2, which contains a critical error in the tile\u2011splitting step. Consequently the claim that \\(2n-2\\) is the **minimum** number of tiles is unsupported. The solution is therefore invalid."
