"**Final Verdict:** The solution is correct.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n*No issues were found; every step is rigorously justified.*\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Lemma\u202f1  \n- **Statement:** The uncovered squares form a permutation matrix.  \n- **Verification:** Defining \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered square in row \\(i\\) gives a well\u2011defined function from \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) to itself. Since each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, \\(\\sigma\\) is injective; an injective map between two finite sets of equal cardinality is bijective. The argument is complete and correct.  \n\n### Lemma\u202f2  \n- **Statement:** Tiles left of an uncovered square in a row must be horizontal tiles of height\u202f1; similarly for columns.  \n- **Verification:**  \n  1. Fix a row \\(i\\) with \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\) and a column \\(c<\\sigma(i)\\). The unique uncovered square in column \\(c\\) is \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\).  \n  2. Suppose a tile \\(T\\) covering \\((i,c)\\) has height \\(\\ge 2\\). Then \\(T\\) also covers some other row \\(i'\\neq i\\). Because \\(T\\) is a rectangle, its column interval contains \\(c\\) for every row between \\(i\\) and \\(i'\\); thus it must contain the cell \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\).  \n  3. This contradicts the definition of uncovered squares. Hence the assumption is false and the tile must have height\u202f1, i.e. be a horizontal tile lying entirely in row \\(i\\).  \n  4. The column\u2011wise statement follows by symmetry.  \n\n  The reasoning correctly uses the rectangular shape property and the uniqueness of uncovered squares; no gaps are present.\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Universal lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))  \n- **Statement:** Any admissible tiling uses at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \n- **Verification:**  \n  1. From Lemma\u202f1 we have a permutation \\(\\sigma\\).  \n  2. Define \\(R=\\{i\\mid\\sigma(i)>1\\}\\) and \\(C=\\{j\\mid\\sigma^{-1}(j)>1\\}\\). Because exactly one row has \\(\\sigma(i)=1\\) and exactly one column has \\(\\sigma^{-1}(j)=1\\), we have \\(|R|=|C|=n-1\\).  \n  3. For each \\(i\\in R\\) the cell \\((i,\\sigma(i)-1)\\) lies left of the uncovered square in that row. By Lemma\u202f2 any tile covering this cell must be a horizontal tile of height\u202f1, and such a tile is confined to row \\(i\\). Distinct rows give distinct tiles, so at least \\(|R|=n-1\\) horizontal tiles are required.  \n  4. The analogous argument for columns yields at least \\(|C|=n-1\\) vertical tiles.  \n  5. Adding the two independent counts gives a lower bound of \\((n-1)+(n-1)=2n-2\\) tiles.  \n\n  All steps are justified; the conclusion follows logically.\n\n### Lemma\u202f4 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)  \n- **Statement:** There exists an admissible tiling using exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \n- **Verification:**  \n  1. Choose \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\); the uncovered squares are the main diagonal cells \\((i,i)\\).  \n  2. For each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) place a horizontal rectangle \\(H_i\\) covering row \\(i\\) columns \\(1\\) through \\(i-1\\) (size \\(1\\times(i-1)\\)) and a vertical rectangle \\(V_i\\) covering column \\(i\\) rows \\(1\\) through \\(i-1\\) (size \\((i-1)\\times1\\)). No rectangles are placed for \\(i=1\\).  \n  3. **Disjointness:**  \n     - Horizontal rectangles lie in distinct rows \u2192 no overlap.  \n     - Vertical rectangles lie in distinct columns \u2192 no overlap.  \n     - An intersection of \\(H_i\\) and \\(V_j\\) could only be at \\((i,j)\\). If \\(j<i\\), then \\(V_j\\) stops at row \\(j-1\\) and does not reach row \\(i\\); if \\(j>i\\), then \\(H_i\\) stops at column \\(i-1\\) and does not reach column \\(j\\). Hence no interior intersections occur.  \n  4. **Coverage:** Any non\u2011diagonal cell \\((r,c)\\) satisfies either \\(c<r\\) (lies left of the diagonal in its row) and belongs to \\(H_r\\), or \\(r<c\\) (lies above the diagonal in its column) and belongs to \\(V_c\\). Thus every non\u2011diagonal cell is covered, and only the diagonal cells remain uncovered, satisfying the problem condition.  \n  5. **Counting:** For each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) we added exactly two tiles, giving \\(2(n-1)=2n-2\\) tiles.  \n\n  The construction is explicit, and each claim (disjointness, coverage, count) is proved rigorously.\n\n### Completion of the proof  \n- Lemma\u202f3 provides a universal lower bound of \\(2n-2\\).  \n- Lemma\u202f4 exhibits a tiling attaining this bound.  \n- Therefore the minimum possible number of tiles is \\(2n-2\\).  \n- Substituting \\(n=2025\\) yields \\(2\\cdot2025-2 = 4048\\).\n\nAll logical steps are sound, and the final answer follows correctly from the established lemmas. Hence the solution is fully correct."
