"**Final Verdict:** The solution is correct.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n*No issues were found; every step is rigorously justified.*\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Lemma\u202f1  \n- **Statement:** The uncovered squares form a permutation matrix.  \n- **Verification:** Defining \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered cell in row \\(i\\) gives a well\u2011defined function from \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) to itself. Since each column also contains exactly one uncovered cell, \\(\\sigma\\) is injective; an injective map between two finite sets of equal cardinality is bijective. The argument is complete and correct.  \n\n### Lemma\u202f2  \n- **Statement:** Tiles covering cells left of (or above) an uncovered square must be 1\u2011high (or 1\u2011wide) horizontal (or vertical) tiles.  \n- **Verification:**  \n  - For a row \\(i\\) with \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\) and a column \\(c<\\sigma(i)\\), the unique uncovered cell in column \\(c\\) is \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\).  \n  - Assuming a covering tile \\(T\\) is not a height\u20111 horizontal tile forces its height \\(\\ge 2\\), so it spans at least two rows. Because \\(T\\) is a rectangle, its column interval contains \\(c\\); consequently every row between the two rows of \\(T\\) at column \\(c\\) is also inside \\(T\\). The row \\(\\sigma^{-1}(c)\\) lies between those two rows (otherwise the rectangle would have to \u201cskip\u201d that row, which a rectangle cannot do). Hence \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\) would be covered, contradicting the definition of uncovered squares.  \n  - The same symmetric reasoning applies to columns.  \n  The proof correctly rules out all other possibilities, establishing the claim.  \n\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))  \n- **Construction of sets \\(R\\) and \\(C\\):**  \n  - Exactly one index satisfies \\(\\sigma(i)=1\\); thus \\(|R|=n-1\\).  \n  - Exactly one index satisfies \\(\\sigma^{-1}(j)=1\\); thus \\(|C|=n-1\\).  \n- **Counting horizontal tiles:**  \n  - For each \\(i\\in R\\) the cell \\((i,\\sigma(i)-1)\\) lies left of the uncovered cell in its row. By Lemma\u202f2 any tile covering this cell must be a height\u20111 horizontal tile confined to row \\(i\\). Different rows give distinct tiles, so at least \\(|R|=n-1\\) horizontal tiles are required.  \n- **Counting vertical tiles:**  \n  - The symmetric argument using \\(C\\) yields at least \\(|C|=n-1\\) vertical tiles.  \n- **Conclusion:** Adding the two lower bounds gives at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles in any admissible tiling. The reasoning is sound and complete.  \n\n### Lemma\u202f4 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)  \n- **Choice of permutation:** \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) gives uncovered squares on the main diagonal.  \n- **Definition of tiles:**  \n  - For each \\(i\\ge 2\\), \\(H_i\\) covers row \\(i\\) columns \\(1\\) through \\(i-1\\) (a \\(1\\times(i-1)\\) rectangle).  \n  - For each \\(i\\ge 2\\), \\(V_i\\) covers column \\(i\\) rows \\(1\\) through \\(i-1\\) (an \\((i-1)\\times1\\) rectangle).  \n- **Disjointness:**  \n  - Horizontal tiles lie in distinct rows \u21d2 no overlap.  \n  - Vertical tiles lie in distinct columns \u21d2 no overlap.  \n  - A horizontal \\(H_i\\) and a vertical \\(V_j\\) could intersect only at \\((i,j)\\). If \\(j<i\\), \\(V_j\\) stops at row \\(j-1\\) and does not reach row \\(i\\); if \\(j>i\\), \\(H_i\\) stops at column \\(i-1\\) and does not reach column \\(j\\). Hence they never share a cell.  \n- **Coverage:**  \n  - Any non\u2011diagonal cell \\((r,c)\\) with \\(c<r\\) lies in \\(H_r\\); if \\(r<c\\) it lies in \\(V_c\\). Thus every cell off the diagonal is covered exactly once.  \n- **Counting:** Two tiles for each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) \u21d2 \\(2(n-1)=2n-2\\) tiles.  \nAll statements are justified; the construction satisfies the problem constraints.  \n\n### Completion of the proof  \n- Lemma\u202f3 provides a universal lower bound of \\(2n-2\\).  \n- Lemma\u202f4 exhibits a tiling attaining this bound.  \n- Therefore the minimum number of tiles for an \\(n\\times n\\) board is \\(2n-2\\).  \n- Substituting \\(n=2025\\) yields \\(2\\cdot2025-2 = 4048\\).  \n\nAll logical steps are rigorously justified; no critical errors or justification gaps are present. The solution is therefore correct."
