"**Final Verdict:** The solution is correct.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n*No issues were found; every step is rigorously justified.*  \n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Lemma\u202f1  \n- **Step:** Definition of \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered square in row \\(i\\).  \n- **Verification:** Since each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, the map \\(i\\mapsto\\sigma(i)\\) is injective. On two finite sets of equal cardinality (\\(n\\)), injectivity implies bijectivity. Hence the uncovered squares form a permutation matrix.  \n- **Conclusion:** Correct.\n\n### Lemma\u202f2  \n- **Step:** For a row \\(i\\) with \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\), any tile covering a cell \\((i,c)\\) with \\(c<\\sigma(i)\\) must be a horizontal tile of height\u202f1.  \n- **Verification:**  \n  1. Column \\(c\\) contains the unique uncovered square \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\).  \n  2. Suppose a tile \\(T\\) covering \\((i,c)\\) has height \\(\\ge 2\\). Then \\(T\\) also covers some other row \\(i'\\neq i\\). Because \\(T\\) is a rectangle, its column interval includes \\(c\\) for all rows between \\(i\\) and \\(i'\\).  \n  3. The row \\(\\sigma^{-1}(c)\\) lies somewhere between the topmost and bottommost rows of \\(T\\) (otherwise \\(T\\) would have to \u201cskip\u201d that row, which a rectangle cannot do). Hence \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\in T\\), contradicting that uncovered squares are not covered.  \n  4. Therefore the assumption is false and the tile must have height\u202f1, i.e. be horizontal.  \n- The symmetric argument for columns is identical.  \n- **Conclusion:** Correct; the reasoning is complete and rigorous.\n\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))  \n- **Step:** Define \\(R=\\{i\\mid\\sigma(i)>1\\}\\) and \\(C=\\{j\\mid\\sigma^{-1}(j)>1\\}\\).  \n- **Verification:** Because \\(\\sigma\\) is a bijection, exactly one row has \\(\\sigma(i)=1\\); thus \\(|R|=n-1\\). Similarly \\(|C|=n-1\\).  \n- **Step:** For each \\(i\\in R\\), the cell \\((i,\\sigma(i)-1)\\) lies left of the uncovered square in its row; by Lemma\u202f2 it must belong to a horizontal tile of height\u202f1 that lies entirely in row \\(i\\). Distinct rows give distinct tiles, giving at least \\(|R|=n-1\\) horizontal tiles.  \n- **Step:** The analogous argument for columns yields at least \\(|C|=n-1\\) vertical tiles.  \n- **Conclusion:** The total number of tiles is at least \\((n-1)+(n-1)=2n-2\\). All deductions follow logically; the lemma is correct.\n\n### Lemma\u202f4 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)  \n- **Step:** Choose \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) (uncovered squares on the main diagonal).  \n- **Step:** For each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) place a horizontal rectangle \\(H_i\\) covering cells \\((i,1)\\) through \\((i,i-1)\\) and a vertical rectangle \\(V_i\\) covering cells \\((1,i)\\) through \\((i-1,i)\\).  \n- **Disjointness:**  \n  * Horizontal rectangles occupy distinct rows \u2192 no overlap.  \n  * Vertical rectangles occupy distinct columns \u2192 no overlap.  \n  * An \\(H_i\\) and a \\(V_j\\) can intersect only at \\((i,j)\\). If \\(j<i\\), \\(V_j\\) stops at row \\(j-1\\) and does not reach row \\(i\\); if \\(j>i\\), \\(H_i\\) stops at column \\(i-1\\) and does not reach column \\(j\\). Hence they never share a cell.  \n- **Coverage:** Every non\u2011diagonal cell is either left of the diagonal in its row (belongs to some \\(H_i\\)) or above the diagonal in its column (belongs to some \\(V_j\\)). Thus all non\u2011diagonal cells are covered, and only the diagonal cells remain uncovered, satisfying the condition.  \n- **Counting:** Two rectangles for each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) give \\(2(n-1)=2n-2\\) tiles.  \n- **Conclusion:** The construction is valid and meets the required lower bound.\n\n### Completion of the Proof  \n- Lemma\u202f3 provides a universal lower bound of \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \n- Lemma\u202f4 exhibits a tiling that attains this bound.  \n- Therefore the minimum number of tiles for an \\(n\\times n\\) board is \\(2n-2\\).  \n- Substituting \\(n=2025\\) yields \\(2\\cdot2025-2 = 4048\\).  \n\nAll arguments are logically sound and fully justified. Hence the solution is correct."
