"**Final Verdict:** The solution is correct.\n\n**List of Findings:**\n*No issues were found; every step is rigorously justified.*\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Verification Log\n\n### Lemma\u202f1  \n- **Statement:** The uncovered squares form a permutation matrix.  \n- **Verification:** Defining \\(\\sigma(i)\\) as the column of the unique uncovered square in row \\(i\\) gives a well\u2011defined function from \\(\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) to itself. Since each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, \\(\\sigma\\) is injective; an injective map between two finite sets of equal cardinality is bijective. The argument is complete and correct.  \n\n### Lemma\u202f2  \n- **Statement:** Tiles covering cells left of (or above) an uncovered square must be 1\u2011high (or 1\u2011wide) rectangles.  \n- **Verification:**  \n  1. Fix a row \\(i\\) with \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\) and a column \\(c<\\sigma(i)\\).  \n  2. Column \\(c\\) contains the uncovered square \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\) by Lemma\u202f1.  \n  3. Suppose a tile \\(T\\) covering \\((i,c)\\) has height \\(\\ge 2\\). Then \\(T\\) also covers some other row \\(i'\\neq i\\). Because \\(T\\) is a rectangle, its column interval includes \\(c\\); consequently every row between \\(i\\) and \\(i'\\) in column \\(c\\) lies inside \\(T\\).  \n  4. The row \\(\\sigma^{-1}(c)\\) lies between \\(i\\) and \\(i'\\) (otherwise the rectangle would have to \u201cskip\u201d that row, which a rectangle cannot do). Hence \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\) would be covered by \\(T\\), contradicting that it is uncovered.  \n  5. Therefore the assumption is false and the tile must have height\u202f1, i.e. be horizontal.  \n  6. The column\u2011wise argument is symmetric.  \n\nAll logical steps are explicit; no hidden assumptions are made. Lemma\u202f2 is valid.\n\n### Lemma\u202f3  \n- **Statement:** Any admissible tiling uses at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \n- **Verification:**  \n  1. From Lemma\u202f1 we have a permutation \\(\\sigma\\).  \n  2. Define \\(R=\\{i\\mid\\sigma(i)>1\\}\\) and \\(C=\\{j\\mid\\sigma^{-1}(j)>1\\}\\). Because exactly one row has \\(\\sigma(i)=1\\), \\(|R|=n-1\\); similarly \\(|C|=n-1\\).  \n  3. For each \\(i\\in R\\) consider the cell \\((i,\\sigma(i)-1)\\). By Lemma\u202f2 any tile covering this cell must be a horizontal tile of height\u202f1 lying wholly in row \\(i\\). Distinct rows give distinct tiles, so at least \\(|R|=n-1\\) horizontal tiles are required.  \n  4. The analogous column argument yields at least \\(|C|=n-1\\) vertical tiles.  \n  5. Adding the two lower bounds gives at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles in total.  \n\nEach inference follows directly from the previous lemmas; the counting is precise. Lemma\u202f3 is correct.\n\n### Lemma\u202f4  \n- **Statement:** There exists a tiling with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \n- **Verification:**  \n  1. Choose \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\); the uncovered squares are the main diagonal cells \\((i,i)\\).  \n  2. For each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) place a horizontal rectangle \\(H_i\\) covering row \\(i\\) columns \\(1\\) through \\(i-1\\) (size \\(1\\times(i-1)\\)) and a vertical rectangle \\(V_i\\) covering column \\(i\\) rows \\(1\\) through \\(i-1\\) (size \\((i-1)\\times1\\)). No rectangle is needed for \\(i=1\\).  \n  3. **Disjointness:**  \n     - Horizontal rectangles lie in distinct rows \u2192 never intersect.  \n     - Vertical rectangles lie in distinct columns \u2192 never intersect.  \n     - A horizontal \\(H_i\\) and a vertical \\(V_j\\) could intersect only at \\((i,j)\\). If \\(j<i\\), then \\(V_j\\) stops at row \\(j-1\\) and does not reach row \\(i\\); if \\(j>i\\), then \\(H_i\\) stops at column \\(i-1\\) and does not reach column \\(j\\). Hence they are interior\u2011disjoint.  \n  4. **Coverage:** Any non\u2011diagonal cell \\((r,c)\\) satisfies either \\(c<r\\) (lies left of the diagonal in its row) or \\(r<c\\) (lies above the diagonal in its column). In the first case it belongs to \\(H_r\\); in the second case it belongs to \\(V_c\\). Thus every non\u2011diagonal cell is covered, and only the diagonal cells remain uncovered.  \n  5. **Counting:** For each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) we added exactly two tiles, giving \\(2(n-1)=2n-2\\) tiles.  \n\nAll claims are proved with explicit reasoning; the construction satisfies the problem constraints. Lemma\u202f4 is correct.\n\n### Completion of the Proof  \n- Lemma\u202f3 provides a universal lower bound of \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \n- Lemma\u202f4 exhibits a tiling attaining this bound.  \n- Therefore the minimum possible number of tiles is \\(2n-2\\).  \n\nSubstituting \\(n=2025\\) yields \\(2\\cdot2025-2 = 4048\\).\n\nAll steps are logically sound and fully justified. Hence the solution correctly solves the problem."
