"**1. Summary**\n\n**a. Verdict**  \nI have produced a **complete and rigorous** solution.  \nThe minimum possible number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2\\cdot2025-2=4048 } .\n\\]\n\n**b. Method Sketch**  \n\n1. **Permutation of uncovered squares (Lemma\u202f1).**  \n   The condition \u201cexactly one uncovered unit square in each row and each column\u2019\u2019 forces the uncovered squares to form a permutation matrix: there is a bijection \\(\\sigma:\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\to\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) with  \n   \\[\n   U=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\},\\qquad n=2025 .\n   \\]\n\n2. **A forced horizontal (resp. vertical) tile for every row (resp. column) except the one whose uncovered square lies in the first column (resp. first row) (Lemma\u202f2).**  \n   *Key claim.* If \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\) then any tile that covers a cell \\((i,c)\\) with \\(c<\\sigma(i)\\) must be a **horizontal** tile of height\u202f1; analogously, if \\(\\sigma^{-1}(j)>1\\) then any tile that covers a cell \\((r,j)\\) with \\(r<\\sigma^{-1}(j)\\) must be a **vertical** tile of width\u202f1.  \n   The proof uses the fact that each column \\(c\\) contains a unique uncovered square \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\); a rectangle of height\u202f\\(\\ge2\\) that contains a cell left of \\(\\sigma(i)\\) would necessarily also contain that uncovered square, which is forbidden.  \n\n   Consequently each row \\(i\\) with \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\) needs its own horizontal tile, and each column \\(j\\) with \\(\\sigma^{-1}(j)>1\\) needs its own vertical tile.  \n   Because \\(\\sigma\\) is a permutation, exactly one row has \\(\\sigma(i)=1\\) and exactly one column has \\(\\sigma^{-1}(j)=1\\).  \n   Hence any admissible tiling uses at least \\((n-1)\\) horizontal tiles and at least \\((n-1)\\) vertical tiles, i.e. at least  \n\n   \\[\n   2n-2\n   \\tag{1}\n   \\]\n\n   tiles.\n\n3. **Construction attaining the bound (Lemma\u202f3).**  \n   Take the diagonal permutation \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\).  \n   For each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\) place a horizontal rectangle of size \\(1\\times(i-1)\\) covering the cells \\((i,1),\\dots ,(i,i-1)\\) and a vertical rectangle of size \\((i-1)\\times1\\) covering \\((1,i),\\dots ,(i-1,i)\\).  \n   These \\(2(n-1)\\) rectangles are pairwise interior\u2011disjoint, cover every non\u2011diagonal cell, and leave exactly the diagonal cells uncovered.  \n   Thus a tiling with \\(2n-2\\) tiles exists.\n\n4. **Conclusion.**  \n   Lemma\u202f2 gives the universal lower bound (1); Lemma\u202f3 shows that the bound is attainable.  \n   Therefore the minimum number of tiles for a \\(2025\\times2025\\) board is \\(2\\cdot2025-2=4048\\).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n**2. Detailed Solution**\n\nLet \\(n=2025\\).  Index the unit squares of the board by ordered pairs  \n\\((r,c)\\) with \\(1\\le r,c\\le n\\) (row, column).\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f1 (Structure of the uncovered squares)\n\n*Statement.*  \nIf each row and each column contains exactly one uncovered unit square, then the set of uncovered squares is a permutation matrix; i.e. there exists a bijection \\(\\sigma:\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\to\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\) such that  \n\n\\[\nU=\\{(i,\\sigma(i))\\mid i=1,\\dots ,n\\}.\n\\]\n\n*Proof.*  \nFor each row \\(i\\) let \\(\\sigma(i)\\) be the column of the unique uncovered square in that row.  \nBecause each column also contains exactly one uncovered square, the map \\(i\\mapsto\\sigma(i)\\) is injective; an injective map between two finite sets of equal size is bijective. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f2 (Forced horizontal and vertical tiles)\n\n*Statement.*  \nLet a tiling satisfy the condition of Lemma\u202f1.  \nFor any row \\(i\\) with \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\) every tile that covers a cell \\((i,c)\\) with \\(c<\\sigma(i)\\) is a horizontal tile of height\u202f1.  \nSimilarly, for any column \\(j\\) with \\(\\sigma^{-1}(j)>1\\) every tile that covers a cell \\((r,j)\\) with \\(r<\\sigma^{-1}(j)\\) is a vertical tile of width\u202f1.\n\n*Proof.*  \nFix a row \\(i\\) with \\(\\sigma(i)>1\\) and a column \\(c\\) such that \\(1\\le c<\\sigma(i)\\).  \nBecause \\(\\sigma\\) is a permutation, column \\(c\\) contains the unique uncovered square \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\).\n\nAssume, for contradiction, that a tile \\(T\\) covering \\((i,c)\\) is **not** a horizontal tile of height\u202f1.  \nThen \\(T\\) has height at least\u202f2, so it contains another row \\(i'\\neq i\\).  \nSince \\(T\\) is a rectangle, its column interval contains \\(c\\); consequently the whole column \\(c\\) between rows \\(\\min\\{i,i'\\}\\) and \\(\\max\\{i,i'\\}\\) lies inside \\(T\\).  \nIn particular the cell \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\) belongs to \\(T\\) because \\(\\sigma^{-1}(c)\\) is one of the rows between \\(i\\) and \\(i'\\) (otherwise \\(T\\) would have to skip that row, which a rectangle cannot do).  \nThus \\(T\\) would contain the uncovered square \\((\\sigma^{-1}(c),c)\\), contradicting the rule that uncovered squares are not covered by any tile.  \n\nHence the assumption is false and \\(T\\) must be horizontal with height\u202f1, i.e. it lies entirely in row \\(i\\).\n\nThe argument for columns is symmetric: if a tile covers a cell \\((r,j)\\) with \\(r<\\sigma^{-1}(j)\\) and is not a vertical tile of width\u202f1, it would have width at least\u202f2 and would necessarily contain the uncovered square \\((\\sigma^{-1}(j),j)\\), a contradiction. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f3 (Universal lower bound \\(m\\ge 2n-2\\))\n\n*Statement.*  \nAny admissible tiling of the \\(n\\times n\\) board uses at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles.\n\n*Proof.*  \n\nFrom Lemma\u202f1 there is a permutation \\(\\sigma\\).  \nConsider the set  \n\n\\[\nR=\\{\\,i\\in\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\mid \\sigma(i)>1\\,\\},\n\\qquad\nC=\\{\\,j\\in\\{1,\\dots ,n\\}\\mid \\sigma^{-1}(j)>1\\,\\}.\n\\]\n\nBecause \\(\\sigma\\) is a bijection, exactly one index \\(i\\) satisfies \\(\\sigma(i)=1\\); therefore \\(|R|=n-1\\).  \nSimilarly exactly one index \\(j\\) satisfies \\(\\sigma^{-1}(j)=1\\), so \\(|C|=n-1\\).\n\nFor each \\(i\\in R\\) the cell \\((i,\\sigma(i)-1)\\) lies to the left of the uncovered square in row \\(i\\).  \nBy Lemma\u202f2 any tile covering this cell must be a horizontal tile of height\u202f1, and such a tile lies entirely in row \\(i\\).  \nSince different rows are distinct, the horizontal tiles required for distinct \\(i\\in R\\) are all different.  \nConsequently the tiling contains at least \\(|R|=n-1\\) horizontal tiles.\n\nAn analogous argument applied to the columns in \\(C\\) shows that the tiling contains at least \\(|C|=n-1\\) vertical tiles.\n\nHorizontal and vertical tiles are counted separately; together they give at least  \n\n\\[\n(n-1)+(n-1)=2n-2\n\\]\n\ntiles. \u220e\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Lemma\u202f4 (Construction with exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles)\n\n*Statement.*  \nThere exists an admissible tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.\n\n*Proof.*  \nChoose the permutation \\(\\sigma(i)=i\\) (the main diagonal).  \nThus the uncovered squares are the diagonal cells \\((i,i)\\), one per row and column.\n\nFor each integer \\(i\\) with \\(2\\le i\\le n\\) place two rectangles:\n\n* a **horizontal** rectangle  \n  \\[\n  H_i=\\{(i,c)\\mid 1\\le c\\le i-1\\},\n  \\]\n  of size \\(1\\times (i-1)\\);\n\n* a **vertical** rectangle  \n  \\[\n  V_i=\\{(r,i)\\mid 1\\le r\\le i-1\\},\n  \\]\n  of size \\((i-1)\\times 1\\).\n\nNo rectangle is placed for \\(i=1\\) because both \\(H_1\\) and \\(V_1\\) would be empty.\n\n*Disjointness.*  \nTwo horizontal rectangles lie in different rows, so they are disjoint.  \nTwo vertical rectangles lie in different columns, so they are disjoint.  \nA horizontal rectangle \\(H_i\\) and a vertical rectangle \\(V_j\\) can intersect only at the cell \\((i,j)\\).  \nIf \\(j<i\\) then \\(V_j\\) occupies rows \\(1,\\dots ,j-1\\) and does not reach row \\(i\\);  \nif \\(j>i\\) then \\(H_i\\) occupies columns \\(1,\\dots ,i-1\\) and does not reach column \\(j\\).  \nHence all rectangles are pairwise interior\u2011disjoint.\n\n*Coverage.*  \nEvery non\u2011diagonal cell either lies to the left of the diagonal in its row (hence belongs to some \\(H_i\\)) or lies above the diagonal in its column (hence belongs to some \\(V_j\\)).  \nThus all non\u2011diagonal cells are covered, and the only uncovered cells are the diagonal ones, exactly one per row and per column.\n\n*Counting.*  \nWe have created two rectangles for each \\(i=2,\\dots ,n\\); therefore the total number of tiles is  \n\n\\[\n2\\,(n-1)=2n-2 .\n\\qquad\\blacksquare\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n### Completion of the proof\n\nLemma\u202f3 shows that any admissible tiling needs at least \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nLemma\u202f4 exhibits a tiling that uses exactly \\(2n-2\\) tiles.  \nHence the lower bound is tight and optimal.\n\nFor the concrete board size \\(n=2025\\) we obtain  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{4048}\n\\]\n\nas the minimum possible number of tiles. \u220e"
